INSERT INTO `link` VALUES (1,8,0,'Midlife angst? Turmoil? Not at all!','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/midlife-angst-turmoil-not-at-all.html','self-actualisation',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-29 16:17:02',19,'A paper by Hoffman, E., S. Kaneshiro, et al, questions whether the common midlife experience really is one of creeping anxiety and turmoil - the midlife crisis... and they discover that, actually, we don&apos;t really know, as there has been no published research in this area. So they have gone ahead and asked people about a recent joyful experience and its subsequent impact on their outlook on life. All participants reported \"a personally meaningful, inspirational experience occurring during this life period\" (p.493). This is cheering - and no wonder, when we find that this is based on Maslow&apos;s positive psychology and especially the idea of &apos;peak experiences&apos;, which is a full part of the experience of being a self-actualised person. As the authors report:<br /><blockquote class=\"tr_bq\">Maslow offered repeated and trenchant criticism of mainstream psychoanalysis for fixating on the \"nasty . . . &apos;dark, dirty&apos;\" elements of human personality (Maslow, 1971, p. 310). For precisely this reason, Maslow helped launch what he called the \"Third Force\" of humanistic psychology, to transcend the reductionism of both behaviorism and psychoanalysis. Central to this focus was the investiga-tion of peak-experiences as a foundation of healthy psychological function-ing and optimization of one&apos;s full potentialities. </blockquote><br /><br />(Hoffman, E., S. Kaneshiro, et al. \"<a href=\"http://jhp.sagepub.com/content/early/2012/01/23/0022167811433851.abstract\">Peak-Experiences Among Americans in Midlife</a>.\" <u>Journal of Humanistic Psychology</u>) <img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-332546684880415972?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447338,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-29T10:37:00.002+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets','8','A paper by Hoffman, E., S. Kaneshiro, et al, questions whether the common midlife experience really is one of creeping anxiety and turmoil - the midlife crisis... and they discover that, actually, we don&apos;t really know, as there has been no published research in this area. So they have gone ahead and asked people about a recent joyful experience and its subsequent impact on their outlook on life. All participants reported \"a personally meaningful, inspirational experience occurring during this life period\" (p.493). This is cheering - and no wonder, when we find that this is based on Maslow&apos;s positive psychology and especially the idea of &apos;peak experiences&apos;, which is a full part of the experience of being a self-actualised person. As the authors report:<br /><blockquote class=\"tr_bq\">Maslow offered repeated and trenchant criticism of mainstream psychoanalysis for fixating on the \"nasty . . . &apos;dark, dirty&apos;\" elements of human personality (Maslow, 1971, p. 310). For precisely this reason, Maslow helped launch what he called the \"Third Force\" of humanistic psychology, to transcend the reductionism of both behaviorism and psychoanalysis. Central to this focus was the investiga-tion of peak-experiences as a foundation of healthy psychological function-ing and optimization of one&apos;s full potentialities. </blockquote><br /><br />(Hoffman, E., S. Kaneshiro, et al. \"<a href=\"http://jhp.sagepub.com/content/early/2012/01/23/0022167811433851.abstract\">Peak-Experiences Among Americans in Midlife</a>.\" <u>Journal of Humanistic Psychology</u>) <img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-332546684880415972?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2,0,0,'Lack of empathy and free documentaries online','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/lack-of-empathy-and-free-documentaries.html','psychopath',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-29 09:53:04',19,'With my abiding interest in empathy as part of the person-centred approach, I watched a fascinating documentary on psychopathy - human beings who lack empathy&amp;nbsp;- called <a href=\"http://www.sprword.com/videos/ipsychopath/\">I, Psychopath</a>. I also learnt about &apos;Narcissistic personality disorder&apos;, which can be an overlapping condition (part of the sinisterly named <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_triad\">Dark Triad</a>), with a similar lack of empathy. However, it is worth remembering, as chilling as some of this seems - that this is not a life-choice that people just make, they are not deliberately &apos;bad&apos; or &apos;evil&apos; - this is something they are born with (or without, depending on how you look at it) - and the film clearly shows this, with the person with psychopathy having a brain scan and clearly showing no brain activity under emotional stimulation.&amp;nbsp; Clearly, there are implications for managing the condition in society, for&amp;nbsp;all of our benefit&amp;nbsp;- psychopaths are thought to be responsible for half of all reported crimes and to make up between 15% and 20% of the prison population - however, equally clearly an educational theory that depends significantly on shared empathy is not going to be very effective with people who lack that quality - and I also wonder what the wider person-centred therapeutic community make of persons who do not experience reciprocal emotions, how does that work in the therapy room..? I shall keep my eyes open for that one in my research.<br /><br />In the meantime, I shall soon be watching another free documentary which looks at the most recent research into the brains and behaviour of psychopaths and assesses the prospects for the treatment or containment of this group of people (some estimates are that 1% of all populations have psychopathy): <a href=\"http://topdocumentaryfilms.com/psychopath/\">Psychopath</a>. <br /><br />I would also like to share some links I have to free documentaries online - an amazing resource to really learn about aspects of the world and our human condition that you won&apos;t get on the tellie! <br /><h4>Free Documentary Sites: </h4><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.sprword.com/mustwatch.html\">http://www.sprword.com/mustwatch.html</a>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; </li><li><a href=\"http://freedocumentaries.org/\">http://freedocumentaries.org</a></li><li><a href=\"http://topdocumentaryfilms.com/\">http://topdocumentaryfilms.com/</a>&amp;nbsp;(this one courtesy <a href=\"http://dogsharon.com/\">http://dogsharon.com</a>)</li></ul>I&apos;ll add more if I find more.<br /><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6663576276199265626?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447338,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-29T09:53:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'With my abiding interest in empathy as part of the person-centred approach, I watched a fascinating documentary on psychopathy - human beings who lack empathy&amp;nbsp;- called <a href=\"http://www.sprword.com/videos/ipsychopath/\">I, Psychopath</a>. I also learnt about &apos;Narcissistic personality disorder&apos;, which can be an overlapping condition (part of the sinisterly named <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_triad\">Dark Triad</a>), with a similar lack of empathy. However, it is worth remembering, as chilling as some of this seems - that this is not a life-choice that people just make, they are not deliberately &apos;bad&apos; or &apos;evil&apos; - this is something they are born with (or without, depending on how you look at it) - and the film clearly shows this, with the person with psychopathy having a brain scan and clearly showing no brain activity under emotional stimulation.&amp;nbsp; Clearly, there are implications for managing the condition in society, for&amp;nbsp;all of our benefit&amp;nbsp;- psychopaths are thought to be responsible for half of all reported crimes and to make up between 15% and 20% of the prison population - however, equally clearly an educational theory that depends significantly on shared empathy is not going to be very effective with people who lack that quality - and I also wonder what the wider person-centred therapeutic community make of persons who do not experience reciprocal emotions, how does that work in the therapy room..? I shall keep my eyes open for that one in my research.<br /><br />In the meantime, I shall soon be watching another free documentary which looks at the most recent research into the brains and behaviour of psychopaths and assesses the prospects for the treatment or containment of this group of people (some estimates are that 1% of all populations have psychopathy): <a href=\"http://topdocumentaryfilms.com/psychopath/\">Psychopath</a>. <br /><br />I would also like to share some links I have to free documentaries online - an amazing resource to really learn about aspects of the world and our human condition that you won&apos;t get on the tellie! <br /><h4>Free Documentary Sites: </h4><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.sprword.com/mustwatch.html\">http://www.sprword.com/mustwatch.html</a>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; </li><li><a href=\"http://freedocumentaries.org/\">http://freedocumentaries.org</a></li><li><a href=\"http://topdocumentaryfilms.com/\">http://topdocumentaryfilms.com/</a>&amp;nbsp;(this one courtesy <a href=\"http://dogsharon.com/\">http://dogsharon.com</a>)</li></ul>I&apos;ll add more if I find more.<br /><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6663576276199265626?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(3,0,0,'Person-Centred Everything: Meetings','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/person-centred-everything-meetings.html','meetings',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-20 08:30:03',19,'The&amp;nbsp;beginnings here of person-centred meetings taken from a conversation with Rachel at the Temenos conference last year:<ol><li>Be real, trusting, empathic</li><li>Create a warm, welcoming, unconditional space</li><li>Sit in silence (it really is golden)</li><li>Don&apos;t have an agenda</li></ol><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8483763295340448268?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-20T08:30:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'The&amp;nbsp;beginnings here of person-centred meetings taken from a conversation with Rachel at the Temenos conference last year:<ol><li>Be real, trusting, empathic</li><li>Create a warm, welcoming, unconditional space</li><li>Sit in silence (it really is golden)</li><li>Don&apos;t have an agenda</li></ol><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8483763295340448268?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(4,0,0,'Person-Centred Everything: Presentations','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/person-centred-everything-presentations.html','presentation',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-17 14:24:25',19,'Because person-centredness is not a set of rules or techniques, but a way of being, then, as Carl Rogers pointed out, the approach can be &apos;applied&apos; to, well, everything. Here&apos;s how a person-centred presentation might look (might? HAS looked - I&apos;ve seen person-centred presenters overcome with emotion, and saw a presenter start dancing), showing more of the extent and variety of person-centredness: <ol><li>Be real, trusting, empathic</li><li>Take risks</li><li>Leave spaces in presentations for feedback, say at the start</li><li>Say how you are feeling â€“ if you are feeling nervous, passionate, emotional</li><li>Show how you are feeling â€“ laugh, cry...</li><li>Dance if you wish</li></ol><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-2813154352427119220?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-17T14:24:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'Because person-centredness is not a set of rules or techniques, but a way of being, then, as Carl Rogers pointed out, the approach can be &apos;applied&apos; to, well, everything. Here&apos;s how a person-centred presentation might look (might? HAS looked - I&apos;ve seen person-centred presenters overcome with emotion, and saw a presenter start dancing), showing more of the extent and variety of person-centredness: <ol><li>Be real, trusting, empathic</li><li>Take risks</li><li>Leave spaces in presentations for feedback, say at the start</li><li>Say how you are feeling â€“ if you are feeling nervous, passionate, emotional</li><li>Show how you are feeling â€“ laugh, cry...</li><li>Dance if you wish</li></ol><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-2813154352427119220?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(5,0,0,'Easier transcription of interviews','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/easier-transcription-of-interviews.html','transcription',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-17 10:37:17',19,'F4 is a fantastic piece of software for data transcription which allows you to permanently link &amp;amp; sync&amp;nbsp;your file (mp3, ogg, wma, wav, aif, avi and mpg) to the output file, allowing rechecking at a later date. The software is easy to use and features a short automatic rewind, which is a joy when trying to transcribe quickly and smoothly - when you play the data again, you hear the last two or three words. Playback speed can be altered too, so that those difficult to understand passages can be focused on. If you wish to find a particular part of the interview, pressing F3 and F5 allow you to hear the data when you&amp;nbsp;fast forward and rewind. Time-markers can be inserted (by you or automatically) in order to sync for proof-reading or analysis. Automatic backup (10 mins) means you won&apos;t lose data. <br /><br />You can download the software <a href=\"http://www.audiotranskription.de/english/home\">here</a>.<br /><br />And here are some <a href=\"file:///C:/Program%20Files%20(x86)/f4/tutorial/English/index.html\">really clear instructions</a> for this easy to use program (btw F4 is for Windows - F5 is the Apple version). <br /><br />Update - just discovered by accident that you can play the recording by double-clicking on any timestamp in the transcript, which is a REALLY helpful feature!<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-3586576917116021913?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-13T11:06:00.003+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'F4 is a fantastic piece of software for data transcription which allows you to permanently link &amp;amp; sync&amp;nbsp;your file (mp3, ogg, wma, wav, aif, avi and mpg) to the output file, allowing rechecking at a later date. The software is easy to use and features a short automatic rewind, which is a joy when trying to transcribe quickly and smoothly - when you play the data again, you hear the last two or three words. Playback speed can be altered too, so that those difficult to understand passages can be focused on. If you wish to find a particular part of the interview, pressing F3 and F5 allow you to hear the data when you&amp;nbsp;fast forward and rewind. Time-markers can be inserted (by you or automatically) in order to sync for proof-reading or analysis. Automatic backup (10 mins) means you won&apos;t lose data. <br /><br />You can download the software <a href=\"http://www.audiotranskription.de/english/home\">here</a>.<br /><br />And here are some <a href=\"file:///C:/Program%20Files%20(x86)/f4/tutorial/English/index.html\">really clear instructions</a> for this easy to use program (btw F4 is for Windows - F5 is the Apple version). <br /><br />Update - just discovered by accident that you can play the recording by double-clicking on any timestamp in the transcript, which is a REALLY helpful feature!<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-3586576917116021913?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(6,0,0,'Easy backup for your Google Calendars','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/easy-backup-for-your-google-calendars.html','Google',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-12 11:10:53',19,'<a href=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-e_i8stideEo/UCeAtTa3pGI/AAAAAAAAAKU/FxC81GgrFjA/s1600/backup-cartoon2.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"312\" src=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-e_i8stideEo/UCeAtTa3pGI/AAAAAAAAAKU/FxC81GgrFjA/s320/backup-cartoon2.jpg\" width=\"320\" /></a>I was just doing a quick backup and thought you may not know about this lovely little trick - just paste <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/exporticalzip\">https://www.google.com/calendar/exporticalzip</a>&amp;nbsp;into your browser and go - you will download a zip file&amp;nbsp;of all of your calendars. <br />That&apos;s it. <br />Neat.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6665724315029436692?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-12T11:10:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-e_i8stideEo/UCeAtTa3pGI/AAAAAAAAAKU/FxC81GgrFjA/s1600/backup-cartoon2.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"312\" src=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-e_i8stideEo/UCeAtTa3pGI/AAAAAAAAAKU/FxC81GgrFjA/s320/backup-cartoon2.jpg\" width=\"320\" /></a>I was just doing a quick backup and thought you may not know about this lovely little trick - just paste <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/exporticalzip\">https://www.google.com/calendar/exporticalzip</a>&amp;nbsp;into your browser and go - you will download a zip file&amp;nbsp;of all of your calendars. <br />That&apos;s it. <br />Neat.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6665724315029436692?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(7,0,0,'Person-Centred Research Methods: Cooperative Inquiry','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/we-want-to-work-withpeople-not-samples.html','cycle',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-11 11:42:46',19,'<blockquote class=\"tr_bq\">We want to work with people, not samples </blockquote>(Reason &amp;amp; Heron, 1986, 302)<br />John Heron and Peter Reason proposed a comprehensive person-centred research method in 1971, which is clearly expounded in \"Research with people: The paradigm of cooperative experiential inquiry.\" (I couldn&apos;t find a version online but there is <a href=\"http://peterreason.eu/Papers/Handbook_Co-operative_Inquiry.pdf\">a chapter from John Heron&apos;s Handbook of Action Research</a> that covers the same ground). <o:p></o:p><br /><br />The approach is called &apos;co-operative or experiential inquiry&apos; and the key idea is that it is not <b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">of</b> but <b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">with</b> persons, who are \"to some significant degree self-determining\" (293) â€“ excluding this would simply mean that it is not a claim of a science of persons. Therefore, all active participants are fully involved in research decisions as co-researchers: \"the self-directing person is the primary source of knowing\" (293)<o:p></o:p>Important issues stemming from this position are that \"...at a minimum everyone involved needs to be initiated into the inquiry process and give their free and informed assent to all decisions about process and outcome\" (294). This includes persons in the planning of the inquiry (294)<o:p></o:p><br /><br />Reason and Heron propose four phases of action and reflection as an iterative research cycle: <o:p></o:p><ol><li> Reflection - Group of co-researchers agree on area for inquiry/identify initial research propositions</li><li>Action â€“ Apply these procedures</li><li>Action â€“ Co-researchers fully immersed in this activity</li><li>Reflection â€“ Co-researchers reconsider original research propositions and hypothesise in the light of experience<o:p></o:p></li></ol>This &apos;research cycling&apos; should be repeated several times â€“ and has a bearing on empirical validity. <o:p></o:p><br /><br />The authors cite Strauss and Guba in an important discussion about the epistemological basis of the research method â€“ stating that cooperative inquiry goes further even than &apos;grounded&apos; or &apos;negotiated&apos; research because it embraces wholeness and is not reductive (296).<o:p></o:p>The paper concludes with a fantastic idea â€“ that of the Devil&apos;s Advocate, which presents a critical dialogue between the authors and \"a more orthodox Devil&apos;s Advocate, who expresses some of the objections of our critics.\" (301). This is worth reading alone and gives a wittily concise overview of the theory. <o:p></o:p><br /><br /><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">Reference</b>: Reason, P. and J. Heron (1986). \"Research with people: The paradigm of cooperative experiential inquiry.\" Person-Centered Review.<o:p></o:p><a href=\"http://www.jwelford.demon.co.uk/brainwaremap/heron.html\">John Heron</a>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; <br /><a href=\"http://www.peterreason.eu/\">Peter Reason</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8959297935168871611?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-11T10:34:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<blockquote class=\"tr_bq\">We want to work with people, not samples </blockquote>(Reason &amp;amp; Heron, 1986, 302)<br />John Heron and Peter Reason proposed a comprehensive person-centred research method in 1971, which is clearly expounded in \"Research with people: The paradigm of cooperative experiential inquiry.\" (I couldn&apos;t find a version online but there is <a href=\"http://peterreason.eu/Papers/Handbook_Co-operative_Inquiry.pdf\">a chapter from John Heron&apos;s Handbook of Action Research</a> that covers the same ground). <o:p></o:p><br /><br />The approach is called &apos;co-operative or experiential inquiry&apos; and the key idea is that it is not <b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">of</b> but <b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">with</b> persons, who are \"to some significant degree self-determining\" (293) â€“ excluding this would simply mean that it is not a claim of a science of persons. Therefore, all active participants are fully involved in research decisions as co-researchers: \"the self-directing person is the primary source of knowing\" (293)<o:p></o:p>Important issues stemming from this position are that \"...at a minimum everyone involved needs to be initiated into the inquiry process and give their free and informed assent to all decisions about process and outcome\" (294). This includes persons in the planning of the inquiry (294)<o:p></o:p><br /><br />Reason and Heron propose four phases of action and reflection as an iterative research cycle: <o:p></o:p><ol><li> Reflection - Group of co-researchers agree on area for inquiry/identify initial research propositions</li><li>Action â€“ Apply these procedures</li><li>Action â€“ Co-researchers fully immersed in this activity</li><li>Reflection â€“ Co-researchers reconsider original research propositions and hypothesise in the light of experience<o:p></o:p></li></ol>This &apos;research cycling&apos; should be repeated several times â€“ and has a bearing on empirical validity. <o:p></o:p><br /><br />The authors cite Strauss and Guba in an important discussion about the epistemological basis of the research method â€“ stating that cooperative inquiry goes further even than &apos;grounded&apos; or &apos;negotiated&apos; research because it embraces wholeness and is not reductive (296).<o:p></o:p>The paper concludes with a fantastic idea â€“ that of the Devil&apos;s Advocate, which presents a critical dialogue between the authors and \"a more orthodox Devil&apos;s Advocate, who expresses some of the objections of our critics.\" (301). This is worth reading alone and gives a wittily concise overview of the theory. <o:p></o:p><br /><br /><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">Reference</b>: Reason, P. and J. Heron (1986). \"Research with people: The paradigm of cooperative experiential inquiry.\" Person-Centered Review.<o:p></o:p><a href=\"http://www.jwelford.demon.co.uk/brainwaremap/heron.html\">John Heron</a>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; <br /><a href=\"http://www.peterreason.eu/\">Peter Reason</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8959297935168871611?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(8,0,0,'What&apos;s done and what&apos;s to do','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/whats-done-and-whats-to-do.html','independent study',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-11 10:19:50',19,'This title runs throughout the blog and it&apos;s really a way of me keeping tabs on where I am in the whole doctoral research process - however, I feel that it&apos;s also potentially useful to share as a way of showing the process itself...<br />What&apos;s done<ul><li>Started again on&amp;nbsp;my Independent Study Research Module (ISRM) work - this is a very large step on the way towards writing the doctorate itself - it is composed of four chapters, including introduction, literature review and methodology - this is what I&apos;ve done this week: </li></ul><blockquote><ul><li>clarified main aspects of literature review&amp;nbsp;</li></ul></blockquote><blockquote><ul><li>Wrote up research design framework&amp;nbsp;</li></ul></blockquote><blockquote><ul><li>began person-centred research methods</li></ul></blockquote><ul><li>Wrote up article about reflexivity (person-centred)</li><li>Updated a couple of refs in Endnote</li></ul>What&apos;s to do<ul><li>Analyse questionnaire results</li><li>Transcribe interview and analyse</li><li>Write both up</li><li>Write up Person-Centred Research Methods</li><li>Evaluate person-centred graduate education book</li><li>Start clearing and incorporating google tasks for ISRM </li><li>Incorporate work done on ethical review</li><li>Enter notes taken previously to ISRM</li><li>Read read read (well, that&apos;s a given - but it&apos;s always worth reminding myself to put the quality time aside for reading). </li></ul><a href=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-W7Jtksl3YtI/Tg85uRJ6-1I/AAAAAAAADfo/RmY0_riqOLE/s1600/Jerry-Daily-To-Do-List.png\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"54\" src=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-W7Jtksl3YtI/Tg85uRJ6-1I/AAAAAAAADfo/RmY0_riqOLE/s200/Jerry-Daily-To-Do-List.png\" style=\"cursor: move;\" width=\"200\" /></a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8481324170410961326?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-11T10:19:00.001+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'This title runs throughout the blog and it&apos;s really a way of me keeping tabs on where I am in the whole doctoral research process - however, I feel that it&apos;s also potentially useful to share as a way of showing the process itself...<br />What&apos;s done<ul><li>Started again on&amp;nbsp;my Independent Study Research Module (ISRM) work - this is a very large step on the way towards writing the doctorate itself - it is composed of four chapters, including introduction, literature review and methodology - this is what I&apos;ve done this week: </li></ul><blockquote><ul><li>clarified main aspects of literature review&amp;nbsp;</li></ul></blockquote><blockquote><ul><li>Wrote up research design framework&amp;nbsp;</li></ul></blockquote><blockquote><ul><li>began person-centred research methods</li></ul></blockquote><ul><li>Wrote up article about reflexivity (person-centred)</li><li>Updated a couple of refs in Endnote</li></ul>What&apos;s to do<ul><li>Analyse questionnaire results</li><li>Transcribe interview and analyse</li><li>Write both up</li><li>Write up Person-Centred Research Methods</li><li>Evaluate person-centred graduate education book</li><li>Start clearing and incorporating google tasks for ISRM </li><li>Incorporate work done on ethical review</li><li>Enter notes taken previously to ISRM</li><li>Read read read (well, that&apos;s a given - but it&apos;s always worth reminding myself to put the quality time aside for reading). </li></ul><a href=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-W7Jtksl3YtI/Tg85uRJ6-1I/AAAAAAAADfo/RmY0_riqOLE/s1600/Jerry-Daily-To-Do-List.png\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"54\" src=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-W7Jtksl3YtI/Tg85uRJ6-1I/AAAAAAAADfo/RmY0_riqOLE/s200/Jerry-Daily-To-Do-List.png\" style=\"cursor: move;\" width=\"200\" /></a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8481324170410961326?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(9,0,0,'Person-Centred Research Methods: Reflexivity','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/08/person-centred-research-methods.html','reflexivity',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-09 15:57:51',19,'In a pioneering article (<a href=\"http://www.utsc.utoronto.ca/~kmacd/IDSC10/Readings/Positionality/reflex-2.pdf\">Negotiating the swamp: the opportunity and challenge of reflexivity in research practice</a>), Linda Finlay of the Open University looks at how &apos;researcher-explorers&apos; from a range of research traditions have negotiated the perils of &apos;the swamp&apos; of reflexive analysis.&amp;nbsp; <o:p></o:p><br /> <br />Why use the word &apos;pioneering&apos;? For me, the innovative aspect of this paper is the use of italics, which Finlay uses intermittently throughout as a &apos;meta-reflexive voice&apos; to help tease out the critical issues at stake. <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">Coming from the person-centred approach, I think this is a neat way to square the circle of being my authentic self in my writing whilst also writing &apos;objectively&apos;in the third person for the purposes of academic convention. I would much rather simply include my reflexivity in the text, rather than segregating it â€“ and, certainly, later in his career, Carl Rogers wrote as &apos;himself&apos;, in the first person, as he clearly understood the nonsense of third person writing â€“ however, he was a highly respected and internationally famous psychologicst and I&apos;m just a worm, an insect... some kind of crawling, disgusting, creeping little vermin! You know, you can stop me! (how did Woody Allen get in there? I guess that&apos;s the sometime randomness of reflexivity, too, which also has a place as this is about our creative thinking processes which are &amp;nbsp;notoriously difficult to marshal and the text might well reflect that aspect...)</i>So, back to the article. Finlay first of all presents a brief history of reflexivity, showing how it has a firm place within the qualitative research agenda. She argues for &amp;nbsp;the researcher as \"a central figure who influences if not actively constructs, the collection, selection and interpretation of data\", going on to state that \"researchers no longer question the need for reflexivity: the question is how to do it\" (2002, 212). And there is a &apos;how&apos;, as she offers five maps of different variants of reflexivity as:<ol><li>Introspection</li><li>intersubjective reflection</li><li>mutual collaboration</li><li>social critique</li><li>ironic deconstruction<o:p></o:p></li></ol><h3> 1.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Reflexivity as introspection<o:p></o:p></h3>The terrain here is of personal revelation, not as an end in itself, but as a springboard for more general insight and interpretations â€“ Finlay quotes Maslow (1966), who asserted &apos;\"there is no substitute for experience, none at all\", pointing researchers towards the value of self-dialogue and discovery. <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">I also wonder if there might be a place for creative expression in research, too â€“ what might be the place of a short fiction or a poem to express the reflexive standpoint of a person, especially with something as elusive as introspection? I&apos;m also pleased to see a discussion of the work of Moustakas (1990), who is a significant writer in the person-centred approach. <o:p></o:p></i><br /> <br /><h3>2.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Reflexivity as intersubjective reflection </h3>This is where researchers explore the mutual meanings emerging within the research relationship, focusing on the situated and negotiated nature of the research encounter. Highly significant here are the attitudes and demeanour of the researcher, highlighting the danger of limited participation in the research due to the researcher being perceived as an authority figure(216). <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">This resonates beautifully with the person-centred approach, which emphasises realness on the part of the facilitator/therapist/researcher, a down-playing of roles, a relinquishing of authority.</i> <o:p></o:p>This type of reflexivity goes beyond an examination of self towards that of self-in-relation-to-others. Linda moves to italics to profess her own ease with this type of reflexivity, where, as a therapist,&amp;nbsp; \"it is second nature to examine my own motivations as a way of understanding another\" (218). The danger here is that such complex dynamics and unconscious motivations can be accessed in the first place. <br /><br /><h3>3.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Reflexivity as Mutual Collaboration</h3>This type of reflexivity centrally enlists researchers as co-participants. <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">This is my favourite, and one I&apos;ve tried, as it doesn&apos;t come more person-centred than this â€“ research &apos;with&apos; people rather than &apos;on&apos; people.</i> The key point here is the recognition of research participants as reflexive beings themselves â€“ and so co-researchers who are involved in a reflexive dialogue during data analysis or evaluation. &amp;nbsp;It&apos;s worth quoting Finlay&apos;s â€“ <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">it feels so, well, RUDE to not refer to &apos;Linda&apos;, but I&apos;m trying to maintain that academic register, as well as, I guess, not assuming an intimacy I don&apos;t have with the author</i> â€“ summary of this style:<blockquote class=\"tr_bq\">\"Collaborative reflexivity offers the opportunity to hear, and take into account, multiple voices and conflicting positions. While the notion of shared realities finds favour with many researchers, some still challenge an egalitarian rhetoric where it disguises essentially unequal relationships.\" (220) </blockquote><h3>4.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Reflexivity as Social Critique</h3>It is that last issue of unequal power relationships which is taken up in the fourth variant of reflexivity, which openly acknowledges tensions arising from different social positions, for instance, class, gender and race. This kind of analysis is rooted in strong theoretical frameworks about the social construction of power. <o:p></o:p><h3>5.   Reflexivity as Discursive Deconstruction</h3>This final variant would accuse the previous two as claiming even more authority by saying you&apos;ve attended to the power dimension. Instead, reflexivity here pays attention to the ambiguity of meanings in language used and to how this impacts on modes of presentation.&amp;nbsp; \"Researchers for this tradition would notice how both participants and researchers are engaged in an exercise of &apos;presenting&apos; themselves to each other â€“ and to the wider community which is to receive the research.\" (223)So, these are the various maps â€“ Finlay goes on to show the value of reflexivity taken as a whole:<ul><li>&amp;nbsp;examine the impact of the position, perspective and presence of the researcher</li><li>&amp;nbsp;promote rich insight through examining personal responses and interpersonal dynamics</li><li>&amp;nbsp;open up unconscious motivations and implicit biases in the researcher&apos;s approach </li><li>&amp;nbsp;empower others by opening up a more radical consciousness</li><li>&amp;nbsp;evaluate the research process, method and outcomes</li><li>&amp;nbsp;enable public scrutiny of the integrity of the research through offering a methodological log of research decisions.</li></ul>(Finlay, 2002)<o:p></o:p><br /><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">Reference</b>: Finlay, L. (2002). \"Negotiating the swamp: the opportunity and challenge of reflexivity in research practice.\" Qualitative Research 2(2): 209-230.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6292759521316193491?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-09T15:57:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'In a pioneering article (<a href=\"http://www.utsc.utoronto.ca/~kmacd/IDSC10/Readings/Positionality/reflex-2.pdf\">Negotiating the swamp: the opportunity and challenge of reflexivity in research practice</a>), Linda Finlay of the Open University looks at how &apos;researcher-explorers&apos; from a range of research traditions have negotiated the perils of &apos;the swamp&apos; of reflexive analysis.&amp;nbsp; <o:p></o:p><br /> <br />Why use the word &apos;pioneering&apos;? For me, the innovative aspect of this paper is the use of italics, which Finlay uses intermittently throughout as a &apos;meta-reflexive voice&apos; to help tease out the critical issues at stake. <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">Coming from the person-centred approach, I think this is a neat way to square the circle of being my authentic self in my writing whilst also writing &apos;objectively&apos;in the third person for the purposes of academic convention. I would much rather simply include my reflexivity in the text, rather than segregating it â€“ and, certainly, later in his career, Carl Rogers wrote as &apos;himself&apos;, in the first person, as he clearly understood the nonsense of third person writing â€“ however, he was a highly respected and internationally famous psychologicst and I&apos;m just a worm, an insect... some kind of crawling, disgusting, creeping little vermin! You know, you can stop me! (how did Woody Allen get in there? I guess that&apos;s the sometime randomness of reflexivity, too, which also has a place as this is about our creative thinking processes which are &amp;nbsp;notoriously difficult to marshal and the text might well reflect that aspect...)</i>So, back to the article. Finlay first of all presents a brief history of reflexivity, showing how it has a firm place within the qualitative research agenda. She argues for &amp;nbsp;the researcher as \"a central figure who influences if not actively constructs, the collection, selection and interpretation of data\", going on to state that \"researchers no longer question the need for reflexivity: the question is how to do it\" (2002, 212). And there is a &apos;how&apos;, as she offers five maps of different variants of reflexivity as:<ol><li>Introspection</li><li>intersubjective reflection</li><li>mutual collaboration</li><li>social critique</li><li>ironic deconstruction<o:p></o:p></li></ol><h3> 1.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Reflexivity as introspection<o:p></o:p></h3>The terrain here is of personal revelation, not as an end in itself, but as a springboard for more general insight and interpretations â€“ Finlay quotes Maslow (1966), who asserted &apos;\"there is no substitute for experience, none at all\", pointing researchers towards the value of self-dialogue and discovery. <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">I also wonder if there might be a place for creative expression in research, too â€“ what might be the place of a short fiction or a poem to express the reflexive standpoint of a person, especially with something as elusive as introspection? I&apos;m also pleased to see a discussion of the work of Moustakas (1990), who is a significant writer in the person-centred approach. <o:p></o:p></i><br /> <br /><h3>2.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Reflexivity as intersubjective reflection </h3>This is where researchers explore the mutual meanings emerging within the research relationship, focusing on the situated and negotiated nature of the research encounter. Highly significant here are the attitudes and demeanour of the researcher, highlighting the danger of limited participation in the research due to the researcher being perceived as an authority figure(216). <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">This resonates beautifully with the person-centred approach, which emphasises realness on the part of the facilitator/therapist/researcher, a down-playing of roles, a relinquishing of authority.</i> <o:p></o:p>This type of reflexivity goes beyond an examination of self towards that of self-in-relation-to-others. Linda moves to italics to profess her own ease with this type of reflexivity, where, as a therapist,&amp;nbsp; \"it is second nature to examine my own motivations as a way of understanding another\" (218). The danger here is that such complex dynamics and unconscious motivations can be accessed in the first place. <br /><br /><h3>3.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Reflexivity as Mutual Collaboration</h3>This type of reflexivity centrally enlists researchers as co-participants. <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">This is my favourite, and one I&apos;ve tried, as it doesn&apos;t come more person-centred than this â€“ research &apos;with&apos; people rather than &apos;on&apos; people.</i> The key point here is the recognition of research participants as reflexive beings themselves â€“ and so co-researchers who are involved in a reflexive dialogue during data analysis or evaluation. &amp;nbsp;It&apos;s worth quoting Finlay&apos;s â€“ <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">it feels so, well, RUDE to not refer to &apos;Linda&apos;, but I&apos;m trying to maintain that academic register, as well as, I guess, not assuming an intimacy I don&apos;t have with the author</i> â€“ summary of this style:<blockquote class=\"tr_bq\">\"Collaborative reflexivity offers the opportunity to hear, and take into account, multiple voices and conflicting positions. While the notion of shared realities finds favour with many researchers, some still challenge an egalitarian rhetoric where it disguises essentially unequal relationships.\" (220) </blockquote><h3>4.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Reflexivity as Social Critique</h3>It is that last issue of unequal power relationships which is taken up in the fourth variant of reflexivity, which openly acknowledges tensions arising from different social positions, for instance, class, gender and race. This kind of analysis is rooted in strong theoretical frameworks about the social construction of power. <o:p></o:p><h3>5.   Reflexivity as Discursive Deconstruction</h3>This final variant would accuse the previous two as claiming even more authority by saying you&apos;ve attended to the power dimension. Instead, reflexivity here pays attention to the ambiguity of meanings in language used and to how this impacts on modes of presentation.&amp;nbsp; \"Researchers for this tradition would notice how both participants and researchers are engaged in an exercise of &apos;presenting&apos; themselves to each other â€“ and to the wider community which is to receive the research.\" (223)So, these are the various maps â€“ Finlay goes on to show the value of reflexivity taken as a whole:<ul><li>&amp;nbsp;examine the impact of the position, perspective and presence of the researcher</li><li>&amp;nbsp;promote rich insight through examining personal responses and interpersonal dynamics</li><li>&amp;nbsp;open up unconscious motivations and implicit biases in the researcher&apos;s approach </li><li>&amp;nbsp;empower others by opening up a more radical consciousness</li><li>&amp;nbsp;evaluate the research process, method and outcomes</li><li>&amp;nbsp;enable public scrutiny of the integrity of the research through offering a methodological log of research decisions.</li></ul>(Finlay, 2002)<o:p></o:p><br /><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">Reference</b>: Finlay, L. (2002). \"Negotiating the swamp: the opportunity and challenge of reflexivity in research practice.\" Qualitative Research 2(2): 209-230.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6292759521316193491?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(10,0,0,'11 Days in July - Google Power Searching','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/07/11-days-in-july-google-power-searching.html','Google',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-22 11:13:42',19,'I started the Google Power Searching course 11 days ago - and just now took the test at the end (passed - getting a certificate!), which was quite tough and did manage to reinforce much of the stuff I&apos;d been learning. I really enjoyed the challenge of taking the course, which was at quite a hectic pace, but it was really well organised and the course host has a fabulous relaxed style of presentation that was very easy to sit through. All in all, a fantastically enjoyable learning experience that will serve me well in all the searches I do from now on. There was an extra &apos;question&apos; at the end that didn&apos;t count to my score, but a nice idea for feedback - choose the five mose useful or exciting things you&apos;ve studied - mine were: <br /><ul><li> Use Google Books to help verify a particular type of answer</li><li>What matters in a query (word order does, but not capitalization or most punctuation)</li><li>WhoIs</li><li>Search by Image</li><li>site:</li></ul>Unfortunately, registration is now closed for the course. However, although you will no longer be able to earn a certificate, you&apos;ll still be able to <a href=\"http://www.google.com/insidesearch/landing/powersearching.html\">view the videos and do the online activities</a> on your own starting July 24, 2012.<br /><br />You could also pick up a lot of tips from&amp;nbsp;<a href=\"http://support.google.com/websearch/?hl=en\">Inside Search</a> this video gives a quick overview of some of the main search features used...<br /><br /><object width=\"320\" height=\"266\" class=\"BLOGGER-youtube-video\" classid=\"clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000\" codebase=\"http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0\" data-thumbnail-src=\"http://2.gvt0.com/vi/y3ao7QXMhC4/0.jpg\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/y3ao7QXMhC4&amp;fs=1&amp;source=uds\" /><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\" /><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\" /><embed width=\"320\" height=\"266\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/y3ao7QXMhC4&amp;fs=1&amp;source=uds\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" allowfullscreen=\"true\"></embed></object><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-5309604917224646384?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-22T11:13:00.003+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'I started the Google Power Searching course 11 days ago - and just now took the test at the end (passed - getting a certificate!), which was quite tough and did manage to reinforce much of the stuff I&apos;d been learning. I really enjoyed the challenge of taking the course, which was at quite a hectic pace, but it was really well organised and the course host has a fabulous relaxed style of presentation that was very easy to sit through. All in all, a fantastically enjoyable learning experience that will serve me well in all the searches I do from now on. There was an extra &apos;question&apos; at the end that didn&apos;t count to my score, but a nice idea for feedback - choose the five mose useful or exciting things you&apos;ve studied - mine were: <br /><ul><li> Use Google Books to help verify a particular type of answer</li><li>What matters in a query (word order does, but not capitalization or most punctuation)</li><li>WhoIs</li><li>Search by Image</li><li>site:</li></ul>Unfortunately, registration is now closed for the course. However, although you will no longer be able to earn a certificate, you&apos;ll still be able to <a href=\"http://www.google.com/insidesearch/landing/powersearching.html\">view the videos and do the online activities</a> on your own starting July 24, 2012.<br /><br />You could also pick up a lot of tips from&amp;nbsp;<a href=\"http://support.google.com/websearch/?hl=en\">Inside Search</a> this video gives a quick overview of some of the main search features used...<br /><br /><object width=\"320\" height=\"266\" class=\"BLOGGER-youtube-video\" classid=\"clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000\" codebase=\"http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0\" data-thumbnail-src=\"http://2.gvt0.com/vi/y3ao7QXMhC4/0.jpg\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/y3ao7QXMhC4&amp;fs=1&amp;source=uds\" /><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\" /><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\" /><embed width=\"320\" height=\"266\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/y3ao7QXMhC4&amp;fs=1&amp;source=uds\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" allowfullscreen=\"true\"></embed></object><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-5309604917224646384?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(11,0,0,'Record from your WebCam','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/07/record-from-your-webcam.html','editing',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-21 15:13:09',19,'For some reason (a really dull one to do with&amp;nbsp;updating systems etc)&amp;nbsp;I found myself with the wrong kind of software for making a simple webcam recording yesterday. So, I played around for a while with one of the industry standard pro recording tools, which would have easily helped me make a fabulous picture in picture video of my screen, a PowerPoint presentation and me all together - but I could not find a straightforward way to just record me talking to the webcam (that isn&apos;t to say it&apos;s not there, but that it wasn&apos;t obvious). So, I looked around a couple of forums and somebody suggested <a href=\"http://www.nchsoftware.com/capture/index.html\">Debut</a>, which is free to download for non-commercial use...<br />...and it&apos;s brilliant! I was overjoyed after trying to get the bells and whistles software to do something simple for me and this is simply - install, open,&amp;nbsp;talk to the camera, save - oh, joy! <br /><br />On top of which, as I just wanted to clip the end off the video, I clicked on &apos;edit&apos; and it downloaded a really nice (again free for non-commercial use) bit of software called <a href=\"http://www.nchsoftware.com/videopad/index.html\">VideoPad Video Editor</a>. <br /><br />Well done and thanks to <a href=\"http://www.nchsoftware.com/index.html\">NCH software</a> for helping out with their excellent and intuitive stuff :-)<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-1050960580432602271?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-21T15:12:00.002+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'For some reason (a really dull one to do with&amp;nbsp;updating systems etc)&amp;nbsp;I found myself with the wrong kind of software for making a simple webcam recording yesterday. So, I played around for a while with one of the industry standard pro recording tools, which would have easily helped me make a fabulous picture in picture video of my screen, a PowerPoint presentation and me all together - but I could not find a straightforward way to just record me talking to the webcam (that isn&apos;t to say it&apos;s not there, but that it wasn&apos;t obvious). So, I looked around a couple of forums and somebody suggested <a href=\"http://www.nchsoftware.com/capture/index.html\">Debut</a>, which is free to download for non-commercial use...<br />...and it&apos;s brilliant! I was overjoyed after trying to get the bells and whistles software to do something simple for me and this is simply - install, open,&amp;nbsp;talk to the camera, save - oh, joy! <br /><br />On top of which, as I just wanted to clip the end off the video, I clicked on &apos;edit&apos; and it downloaded a really nice (again free for non-commercial use) bit of software called <a href=\"http://www.nchsoftware.com/videopad/index.html\">VideoPad Video Editor</a>. <br /><br />Well done and thanks to <a href=\"http://www.nchsoftware.com/index.html\">NCH software</a> for helping out with their excellent and intuitive stuff :-)<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-1050960580432602271?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(12,0,0,'Coursera - now, that&apos;s disruption!','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/07/coursera-now-thats-disruption.html','elearning',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-18 10:31:08',19,'<a href=\"http://www.returnonreputation.com/files/2011/07/disruption1.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"119\" src=\"http://www.returnonreputation.com/files/2011/07/disruption1.jpg\" width=\"200\" /></a>A couple of years ago, Katrina A. Meyer wrote about <a href=\"http://www.educause.edu/ero/article/role-disruptive-technology-future-higher-education\">The Role of Disruptive Technology in the Future of Higher Education</a>&amp;nbsp;and said that \"Disruption takes upsetting the status quo, focusing on student-centered learning, changing relationships, sharpening our insight, and designing instruction to increase learning and lower costs.\" Have a look at <a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/\">Coursera</a> and see if you think these six criteria apply - I think they do. <br /><br />I especially believe that this beautifully designed and well-supported <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massive_open_online_course\">MOOC</a> might well signal the beginning of the end of nightmarishly large and evidentially inneffective lectures, as Universities really start to see the possibilities of using academics&apos; time in much more fruitful one-to-one and small group settings. And I love that Coursera are deadly serious about peer asssessment - I absolutely agree (<a href=\"http://moreorlessbunk.wordpress.com/2012/07/17/comments-you-dont-need-no-stinkin-comments-this-is-a-mooc/\">not everybody does</a>) with Coursera&apos;s Daphne Koller that if students are provided with&amp;nbsp;clear enough criteria, they are just as capable of applying those criteria to each others&apos; work as their tutor. <br /><br /><br />Amongst other pertinent questions, Audrey Watters asks \"How will a partnership with Coursera change universities&apos; other online course offerings?\" - We&apos;ll have to wait and see, I suppose, but the question itself presupposes that change there will certainly be. <br /><br />Anyway, I&apos;ve signed up for three courses and can tell you I&apos;m really looking forward to it - here&apos;s the course list, which is pretty impressive at the moment and which should grow over time: <a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/courses\">https://www.coursera.org/courses</a><br /><br />Read more:<br /><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/2012/jul/17/top-universities-free-online-classes\">http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/2012/jul/17/top-universities-free-online-classes</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.hackeducation.com/2012/07/17/considering-courseras-expansion/?\">http://www.hackeducation.com/2012/07/17/considering-courseras-expansion/?</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/georgeanders/2012/07/17/coursera-boom/\">http://www.forbes.com/sites/georgeanders/2012/07/17/coursera-boom/</a></li></ul><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8820562614699245056?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447340,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-18T10:31:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"http://www.returnonreputation.com/files/2011/07/disruption1.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"119\" src=\"http://www.returnonreputation.com/files/2011/07/disruption1.jpg\" width=\"200\" /></a>A couple of years ago, Katrina A. Meyer wrote about <a href=\"http://www.educause.edu/ero/article/role-disruptive-technology-future-higher-education\">The Role of Disruptive Technology in the Future of Higher Education</a>&amp;nbsp;and said that \"Disruption takes upsetting the status quo, focusing on student-centered learning, changing relationships, sharpening our insight, and designing instruction to increase learning and lower costs.\" Have a look at <a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/\">Coursera</a> and see if you think these six criteria apply - I think they do. <br /><br />I especially believe that this beautifully designed and well-supported <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massive_open_online_course\">MOOC</a> might well signal the beginning of the end of nightmarishly large and evidentially inneffective lectures, as Universities really start to see the possibilities of using academics&apos; time in much more fruitful one-to-one and small group settings. And I love that Coursera are deadly serious about peer asssessment - I absolutely agree (<a href=\"http://moreorlessbunk.wordpress.com/2012/07/17/comments-you-dont-need-no-stinkin-comments-this-is-a-mooc/\">not everybody does</a>) with Coursera&apos;s Daphne Koller that if students are provided with&amp;nbsp;clear enough criteria, they are just as capable of applying those criteria to each others&apos; work as their tutor. <br /><br /><br />Amongst other pertinent questions, Audrey Watters asks \"How will a partnership with Coursera change universities&apos; other online course offerings?\" - We&apos;ll have to wait and see, I suppose, but the question itself presupposes that change there will certainly be. <br /><br />Anyway, I&apos;ve signed up for three courses and can tell you I&apos;m really looking forward to it - here&apos;s the course list, which is pretty impressive at the moment and which should grow over time: <a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/courses\">https://www.coursera.org/courses</a><br /><br />Read more:<br /><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/2012/jul/17/top-universities-free-online-classes\">http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/2012/jul/17/top-universities-free-online-classes</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.hackeducation.com/2012/07/17/considering-courseras-expansion/?\">http://www.hackeducation.com/2012/07/17/considering-courseras-expansion/?</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/georgeanders/2012/07/17/coursera-boom/\">http://www.forbes.com/sites/georgeanders/2012/07/17/coursera-boom/</a></li></ul><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8820562614699245056?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(13,0,0,'The brain and learning','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/07/brain-and-learning.html','brain',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-16 20:59:39',19,'Great post over at <a href=\"http://learnercenteredteaching.wordpress.com/\">Learner Centered Teaching</a> discussing our human survival need for control over our actions and environment and how this impacts on the learning process - where the point is made that the student who feels no control over the learning process may exert their control by not taking part... after which, a number of very pertinent questions are asked about &apos;who controls the learning process in your classroom?&apos;:<br />Who sets the curriculum?<ul><li>Who designs the learning outcomes?</li><li>Who designs the learning environment?</li><li>Who set the attendance, late work or late for class policies?</li><li>Who chooses the textbook?</li><li>Who sets the pace of learning?</li><li>Who determines what feedback is given?</li><li>Who determines the grading system?</li><li>Who determines how information will be taught?</li></ul>Is the answer to any of these questions the students?<br /><br /><a href=\"http://learnercenteredteaching.wordpress.com/teaching-resources/brain-research/brain-research-and-learning/\">More</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-5207947082313498029?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447340,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-16T20:22:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'Great post over at <a href=\"http://learnercenteredteaching.wordpress.com/\">Learner Centered Teaching</a> discussing our human survival need for control over our actions and environment and how this impacts on the learning process - where the point is made that the student who feels no control over the learning process may exert their control by not taking part... after which, a number of very pertinent questions are asked about &apos;who controls the learning process in your classroom?&apos;:<br />Who sets the curriculum?<ul><li>Who designs the learning outcomes?</li><li>Who designs the learning environment?</li><li>Who set the attendance, late work or late for class policies?</li><li>Who chooses the textbook?</li><li>Who sets the pace of learning?</li><li>Who determines what feedback is given?</li><li>Who determines the grading system?</li><li>Who determines how information will be taught?</li></ul>Is the answer to any of these questions the students?<br /><br /><a href=\"http://learnercenteredteaching.wordpress.com/teaching-resources/brain-research/brain-research-and-learning/\">More</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-5207947082313498029?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(14,0,0,'Power Searching with Google','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/07/power-searching-with-google.html','Google',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-11 09:08:23',19,'<a href=\"http://www.brandignity.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/google-power-search.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"112\" src=\"http://www.brandignity.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/google-power-search.jpg\" width=\"200\" /></a>I&apos;m taking this excellent Google course that helps us to use Google to full advantage - learning how google works to become a better searcher. The course is broken up into six different classes, each with a set of lessons which begin with a short video. There are also activities to practice and test understanding. Being able to find knowledge more efficiently, saving time on every activity that we do (online - although note that some of this doesn&apos;t apply on tablets)... for instance, I&apos;ve just done lesson two in class one and I had NO IDEA that it is possible to filter images by colour (sic) - white background is of course very useful for repurposing images. Colour also implies context - so using the &apos;black and white&apos; filter will return mainly old photos or diagrams (which usually have white backgrounds). File under REALLY useful!<br />Sign up to the course here: <a href=\"http://www.google.com/insidesearch/landing/powersearching.html\">http://www.google.com/insidesearch/landing/powersearching.html</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-972365729696807188?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447340,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-11T09:08:00.001+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"http://www.brandignity.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/google-power-search.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"112\" src=\"http://www.brandignity.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/google-power-search.jpg\" width=\"200\" /></a>I&apos;m taking this excellent Google course that helps us to use Google to full advantage - learning how google works to become a better searcher. The course is broken up into six different classes, each with a set of lessons which begin with a short video. There are also activities to practice and test understanding. Being able to find knowledge more efficiently, saving time on every activity that we do (online - although note that some of this doesn&apos;t apply on tablets)... for instance, I&apos;ve just done lesson two in class one and I had NO IDEA that it is possible to filter images by colour (sic) - white background is of course very useful for repurposing images. Colour also implies context - so using the &apos;black and white&apos; filter will return mainly old photos or diagrams (which usually have white backgrounds). File under REALLY useful!<br />Sign up to the course here: <a href=\"http://www.google.com/insidesearch/landing/powersearching.html\">http://www.google.com/insidesearch/landing/powersearching.html</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-972365729696807188?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(15,0,0,'Try a new pdf reader','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/07/try-new-pdf-reader.html','review',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-10 15:47:56',19,'<a href=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-oeEZb2C9738/T_w-GFsVcuI/AAAAAAAAAIw/hpGu-qKEXTA/s1600/20070307-foxit.JPG\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"154\" src=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-oeEZb2C9738/T_w-GFsVcuI/AAAAAAAAAIw/hpGu-qKEXTA/s200/20070307-foxit.JPG\" width=\"200\" /></a>I&apos;ve been having &apos;issues&apos; with adobe reader for quite a while now, including installation problems with upgrades and so on. Frankly, I just don&apos;t like using it. Today I wanted to make some notes and comments and use a highlighter on a pdf and I was annoyed that I couldn&apos;t - why not? It may be that adobe reader x works in this way... but I&apos;m just having trouble installing it, as I say! So, a quick Google search brought me to Foxit Reader, which is a revelation - it&apos;s fast, light and with a pleasant interface&amp;nbsp;- it also lets me make notes and comments, highlight areas,&amp;nbsp;open multiple pdfs in tabs - I&apos;m sure there&apos;s more, but that&apos;ll do me for now. If something works it just works and I thought I&apos;d share it with you. <br /><a href=\"http://www.foxitsoftware.com/Secure_PDF_Reader/\">Download Foxit Here</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-434318757241247324?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447340,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-10T15:45:00.001+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-oeEZb2C9738/T_w-GFsVcuI/AAAAAAAAAIw/hpGu-qKEXTA/s1600/20070307-foxit.JPG\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"154\" src=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-oeEZb2C9738/T_w-GFsVcuI/AAAAAAAAAIw/hpGu-qKEXTA/s200/20070307-foxit.JPG\" width=\"200\" /></a>I&apos;ve been having &apos;issues&apos; with adobe reader for quite a while now, including installation problems with upgrades and so on. Frankly, I just don&apos;t like using it. Today I wanted to make some notes and comments and use a highlighter on a pdf and I was annoyed that I couldn&apos;t - why not? It may be that adobe reader x works in this way... but I&apos;m just having trouble installing it, as I say! So, a quick Google search brought me to Foxit Reader, which is a revelation - it&apos;s fast, light and with a pleasant interface&amp;nbsp;- it also lets me make notes and comments, highlight areas,&amp;nbsp;open multiple pdfs in tabs - I&apos;m sure there&apos;s more, but that&apos;ll do me for now. If something works it just works and I thought I&apos;d share it with you. <br /><a href=\"http://www.foxitsoftware.com/Secure_PDF_Reader/\">Download Foxit Here</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-434318757241247324?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(16,0,0,'Creating Videos for Business','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/07/creating-videos-for-business.html','elearning',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-20 17:03:32',19,'Linda Sedloff Orton from <a href=\"http://www.intelligentvideosolutions.com/\">http://www.intelligentvideosolutions.com</a> has written an excellent article entitled <a href=\"http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/223875\">Tips for Creating Business Videos That Customers Will Watch</a>. I&apos;ve used it to help make <a href=\"http://www.wonderful-learning.com/home\">this video</a> and I&apos;ve added a few extra notes about the process here, mingling Linda&apos;s thoughts with some of my own (trusting she&apos;s okay with my cheek!). I would love to see comments on my video, how it might be improved â€“ it is completely diy because that&apos;s my philosophy, but I&apos;m also after it being well-crafted and well-targeted so that it might encourage potential customers to engage further.<br />Content<ul><li>tell a creative story and include a call to action (&apos;get in touch for a free 30 minute online consultation&apos; â€“ or you could simply ask people to visit your website)</li><li>make it informative and clever, show what makes your company and its services distinctive. </li><li>hook viewers in from the start</li><li>keep it short - 1-2 minutes (youtube is a short form content space) - note that half to three-quarters of a page of text will take around 2 minutes so don&apos;t overdo your written content!</li></ul>Process<br /><ul><li>movement is what really attracts about video, so keep it moving, shake it up a bit â€“ perhaps use some animation from something as simple and easy to use as PowerPoint, which now exports as video (and which you can edit easily in MovieMaker or Garage Band).&amp;nbsp;</li><li>add text to reinforce - especially give the website, blog and twitter links at end â€“ but remember that you should only ever have one communication channel available at a time, not listening AND reading at the same time (if it&apos;s important)</li><li>use music and sound to engage and set a mood (you can search for &apos;royalty-free music&apos; or go to this site for some good places to go - <a href=\"http://socialtimes.com/royalty-free-music_b37470\">10 Royalty Free Music Sites Every Online Video Creator Should Know</a> - and make sure you give full attribution to the wonderful people that are sharing their good stuff with the world â€“ for instance, the track I&apos;ve used is &apos;Acid Trumpet&apos; by Kevin MacLeod found <a href=\"http://incompetech.com/m/c/royalty-free/index.html?genre=Jazz&amp;amp;page=2\">here</a>. </li></ul>Equipment<br />Linda talks of professional quality videos in her article, but she also gives a nice link to the best &apos;prosumer&apos; video cameras â€“ my own diy ethic has given me a slightly different slant in that I upgraded my android smart phone just a little and got the HE Sensation XE, which records 1080p HD video at 30fps. I don&apos;t know what that means either, but â€“ well, what do you think of the quality on the vid? I&apos;m really happy with it! (mind, if I could change that landing thumbnail...).MarketingI&apos;ve nothing to add to Linda&apos;s excellent tips â€“ here they are in full... YouTube, of course, can be key to any video marketing strategy. Be sure your videos are properly titled, described and tagged on YouTube so they&apos;ll show up in Google and other search engines. Also post and publicize your videos through your social media channels, where you can encourage sharing and discuss the content.Some more useful links about making videos for business here: <a href=\"http://www.entrepreneur.com/tag/1676\">http://www.entrepreneur.com/tag/1676</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6890005659776451128?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447341,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-05T16:50:00.001+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'Linda Sedloff Orton from <a href=\"http://www.intelligentvideosolutions.com/\">http://www.intelligentvideosolutions.com</a> has written an excellent article entitled <a href=\"http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/223875\">Tips for Creating Business Videos That Customers Will Watch</a>. I&apos;ve used it to help make <a href=\"http://www.wonderful-learning.com/home\">this video</a> and I&apos;ve added a few extra notes about the process here, mingling Linda&apos;s thoughts with some of my own (trusting she&apos;s okay with my cheek!). I would love to see comments on my video, how it might be improved â€“ it is completely diy because that&apos;s my philosophy, but I&apos;m also after it being well-crafted and well-targeted so that it might encourage potential customers to engage further.<br />Content<ul><li>tell a creative story and include a call to action (&apos;get in touch for a free 30 minute online consultation&apos; â€“ or you could simply ask people to visit your website)</li><li>make it informative and clever, show what makes your company and its services distinctive. </li><li>hook viewers in from the start</li><li>keep it short - 1-2 minutes (youtube is a short form content space) - note that half to three-quarters of a page of text will take around 2 minutes so don&apos;t overdo your written content!</li></ul>Process<br /><ul><li>movement is what really attracts about video, so keep it moving, shake it up a bit â€“ perhaps use some animation from something as simple and easy to use as PowerPoint, which now exports as video (and which you can edit easily in MovieMaker or Garage Band).&amp;nbsp;</li><li>add text to reinforce - especially give the website, blog and twitter links at end â€“ but remember that you should only ever have one communication channel available at a time, not listening AND reading at the same time (if it&apos;s important)</li><li>use music and sound to engage and set a mood (you can search for &apos;royalty-free music&apos; or go to this site for some good places to go - <a href=\"http://socialtimes.com/royalty-free-music_b37470\">10 Royalty Free Music Sites Every Online Video Creator Should Know</a> - and make sure you give full attribution to the wonderful people that are sharing their good stuff with the world â€“ for instance, the track I&apos;ve used is &apos;Acid Trumpet&apos; by Kevin MacLeod found <a href=\"http://incompetech.com/m/c/royalty-free/index.html?genre=Jazz&amp;amp;page=2\">here</a>. </li></ul>Equipment<br />Linda talks of professional quality videos in her article, but she also gives a nice link to the best &apos;prosumer&apos; video cameras â€“ my own diy ethic has given me a slightly different slant in that I upgraded my android smart phone just a little and got the HE Sensation XE, which records 1080p HD video at 30fps. I don&apos;t know what that means either, but â€“ well, what do you think of the quality on the vid? I&apos;m really happy with it! (mind, if I could change that landing thumbnail...).MarketingI&apos;ve nothing to add to Linda&apos;s excellent tips â€“ here they are in full... YouTube, of course, can be key to any video marketing strategy. Be sure your videos are properly titled, described and tagged on YouTube so they&apos;ll show up in Google and other search engines. Also post and publicize your videos through your social media channels, where you can encourage sharing and discuss the content.Some more useful links about making videos for business here: <a href=\"http://www.entrepreneur.com/tag/1676\">http://www.entrepreneur.com/tag/1676</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6890005659776451128?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(17,0,0,'Videos about Person Centred Approach','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/05/im-unfamiliar-with-blogging-platform.html','conditions',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-05-09 11:59:20',19,'I&apos;m unfamiliar with the blogging platform, Tumblr, but I discovered <a href=\"http://aboutpca.tumblr.com/\">this pretty amazing layout of a set of videos</a> explaining key principles and offering an overview of the Person Centred Approach - and I just love the presentation, really neat and well worth spending a little time exploring...<br /><br />Here&apos;s an example of one about &apos;unconditional positive regard&apos; - or &apos;acceptance&apos; or &apos;prizing&apos; - referring to the therapy relationship, but this is also one of the (three) attitudes that the facilitator should take towards learners in creating an environment in which learners can flourish:<br /><br /><object class=\"BLOGGER-youtube-video\" classid=\"clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000\" codebase=\"http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0\" data-thumbnail-src=\"http://0.gvt0.com/vi/9gbziXBIppQ/0.jpg\" height=\"266\" width=\"320\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/9gbziXBIppQ&amp;fs=1&amp;source=uds\" /> <param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\" /> <embed width=\"320\" height=\"266\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/9gbziXBIppQ&amp;fs=1&amp;source=uds\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"></embed></object><br />I&apos;ve subscribed to the blog, although I don&apos;t expect updates any day soon, as each video has the ominous &apos;1 Year Ago&apos; beneath it, showing when content was last posted.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8842934978480054103?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447341,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-05-09T11:57:00.001+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'I&apos;m unfamiliar with the blogging platform, Tumblr, but I discovered <a href=\"http://aboutpca.tumblr.com/\">this pretty amazing layout of a set of videos</a> explaining key principles and offering an overview of the Person Centred Approach - and I just love the presentation, really neat and well worth spending a little time exploring...<br /><br />Here&apos;s an example of one about &apos;unconditional positive regard&apos; - or &apos;acceptance&apos; or &apos;prizing&apos; - referring to the therapy relationship, but this is also one of the (three) attitudes that the facilitator should take towards learners in creating an environment in which learners can flourish:<br /><br /><object class=\"BLOGGER-youtube-video\" classid=\"clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000\" codebase=\"http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0\" data-thumbnail-src=\"http://0.gvt0.com/vi/9gbziXBIppQ/0.jpg\" height=\"266\" width=\"320\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/9gbziXBIppQ&amp;fs=1&amp;source=uds\" /> <param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\" /> <embed width=\"320\" height=\"266\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/9gbziXBIppQ&amp;fs=1&amp;source=uds\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"></embed></object><br />I&apos;ve subscribed to the blog, although I don&apos;t expect updates any day soon, as each video has the ominous &apos;1 Year Ago&apos; beneath it, showing when content was last posted.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8842934978480054103?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(18,0,0,'On strangling the holy curiosity of inquiry','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/05/few-months-ago-i-chanced-upon-new-to-me.html','rogers',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-06-28 15:17:02',19,'A few months ago, I chanced upon a new (to me, although it&apos;s been around for 25 years) and quite lively eLearning network called... the <a href=\"http://www.elearningnetwork.org/\">eLearning Network.</a> As I&apos;m in eLearning and as I&apos;m making some changes in my professional life, I joined and attended an event by the network, which was mighty fine (blogged previously). Whilst there, I picked up their associated publication, <a href=\"http://www.elearningage.co.uk/magazine.aspx\">e-learning age</a>&amp;nbsp;and was pretty excited to see ON THE COVER a <a href=\"http://www.elearningage.co.uk/magazine/learningonthecouch.aspx\">key article about rehumanising learning</a>: right up my street, I thought! <br /><br />Not to be - this article was badly misinformed about the person-centred approach and&amp;nbsp;parodied the approach in the most heinous manner (admittedly, this was not the main thrust of the article in question, which itself made some fair points). Anyway, outraged I sat down and worked up a response - which I&apos;m glad to say has been published in this month&apos;s magazine, so I thought I&apos;d reproduce it here for wider perusal and comment. <br /><br />As an eLearning professional who is deeply interested in person-centred approaches to learning, I was really excited to see the cover feature in the December/January issue devoted to &apos;rehumanising the personal learning experience&apos;. Tim Gibson&apos;s entertaining article takes a nicely imaginative scenario relating to the therapy room â€“ however, Tim is misinformed about what he calls the &apos;Rogerian, or non-directive, psychiatry&apos;. I can illustrate just how wrong by taking direct issue with that definition:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Rogerian â€“ this refers to Carl Rogers, who is best known as the founder of client-centred therapy, but Rogers in fact refused to recognise the burgeoning &apos;movement&apos; of &apos;Rogerians&apos; in his lifetime because his whole point was for human beings not to give up their being to some other person (or computer...). <o:p></o:p><br />Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Non-directive â€“ Rogers moved away from that definition and towards &apos;person-centred&apos; because it was more about the human being at the centre than about the process of therapy itself.<o:p></o:p><br />Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Psychiatry â€“ Carl Rogers was a psychologist, and although the distinction is not easy to make on a surface, non-practitioner level, it is important. The strong, central (and magazine cover) image of the psychiatrist&apos;s couch refers more to that Freudian psycho-analytical model where the psychiatrist is the one who gets to tell the &apos;patient&apos; what their dreams mean and how they should solve their problems. Carl Rogers broke decisively with this tradition and trusted his &apos;clients&apos; to find their own way towards growth and learning. Why does this matter? Tim clearly acknowledges the skit as parody, <a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=3680182410838117036#_edn1\" name=\"_ednref1\" style=\"mso-endnote-id: edn1;\" title=\"\">OPENBLOCKiCLOSEBLOCK</a>but, he also talks about Pygmalion&apos;s Eliza pretending to be something she is not and this, I think, is the central point â€“ if we really wish to rehumanise learning, including eLearning, then we have to provide an environment where human beings can feel, well...&amp;nbsp; human. As it happens, the choice of Carl Rogers&apos; approach is serendipitous when considering rehumanising the personal learning experience. Rogers took the central principles of his theory and applied them to contexts other than the therapy room â€“ including, to education.<a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=3680182410838117036#_edn2\" name=\"_ednref2\" style=\"mso-endnote-id: edn2;\" title=\"\">OPENBLOCKiiCLOSEBLOCK</a> Rogers shows how learning can involve a change in our perception of self and so can very often be perceived as threatening - and so, resisted. I guess readers are very familiar with this when technology is added to the mix. Therefore, to make learning possible, external threats must be minimised so that significant learning can take place. This means a change in roles as we have understood them in &apos;formal&apos; education and in the power-relations that are often the context for &apos;informal&apos; workplace learning:Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The learner needs to be empowered and have control over the learning processÂ·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The teacher gives up much of their authority and becomes a facilitator. This is not an easy task. However, Rogers has given us the means by focusing on the facilitator, whose main task is to create a warm, welcoming, unconditional space in which learners feel they have the freedom to be themselves, take ownership of their learning, and work creatively and collaboratively with other learners. The most important element is the attitudes the facilitator takes, how s/he is existentially - and these are:Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Be a real person, Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Empathise with learners (understand their point of view), Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Trust (or prize) learners. The goal of a person-centred approach to learning is to create an atmosphere that promotes a person&apos;s inherent self-actualising tendency so that learners wish to learn, want to grow, and desire to create. I finish with the same quote from Albert Einstein that Rogers uses to front <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">Freedom to Learn</i>: \"It is in fact nothing short of a miracle that the modern methods of instruction have not yet entirely strangled the holy curiosity of inquiry; for this delicate little plant, aside from stimulation, stands mainly in need of freedom; without this it goes to wrack and ruin without fail.\" I&apos;m certainly not going to argue with Einstein. <hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" /><br /><a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=3680182410838117036#_ednref1\" name=\"_edn1\" style=\"mso-endnote-id: edn1;\" title=\"\">OPENBLOCKiCLOSEBLOCK</a> Like any simple idea, it is easy to parody and, indeed, there was an even harsher parody from the 1940s where a suicidal &apos;patient&apos; in therapy eventually says \"I&apos;m opening the window Dr Rogers\"/\"I see, you&apos;re opening the window\"/\"I&apos;m about to jump\"/U-uhm. You&apos;re about to jump.\"/\"Here I goooo...\"/ \"There you go.\"<o:p></o:p><a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=3680182410838117036#_ednref2\" name=\"_edn2\" style=\"mso-endnote-id: edn2;\" title=\"\">OPENBLOCKiiCLOSEBLOCK</a> Tim acknowledges the power of an older text and so shall I. Carl Rogers&apos; Freedom To Learn for the 80s (1983, Columbus: Merrill) is a passionate and very human book which has helped move (some) education into a more person-centred approach â€“ it&apos;s a must-read for committed learning developers...<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-4193607293332189623?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447341,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-05-08T11:13:00.001+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'A few months ago, I chanced upon a new (to me, although it&apos;s been around for 25 years) and quite lively eLearning network called... the <a href=\"http://www.elearningnetwork.org/\">eLearning Network.</a> As I&apos;m in eLearning and as I&apos;m making some changes in my professional life, I joined and attended an event by the network, which was mighty fine (blogged previously). Whilst there, I picked up their associated publication, <a href=\"http://www.elearningage.co.uk/magazine.aspx\">e-learning age</a>&amp;nbsp;and was pretty excited to see ON THE COVER a <a href=\"http://www.elearningage.co.uk/magazine/learningonthecouch.aspx\">key article about rehumanising learning</a>: right up my street, I thought! <br /><br />Not to be - this article was badly misinformed about the person-centred approach and&amp;nbsp;parodied the approach in the most heinous manner (admittedly, this was not the main thrust of the article in question, which itself made some fair points). Anyway, outraged I sat down and worked up a response - which I&apos;m glad to say has been published in this month&apos;s magazine, so I thought I&apos;d reproduce it here for wider perusal and comment. <br /><br />As an eLearning professional who is deeply interested in person-centred approaches to learning, I was really excited to see the cover feature in the December/January issue devoted to &apos;rehumanising the personal learning experience&apos;. Tim Gibson&apos;s entertaining article takes a nicely imaginative scenario relating to the therapy room â€“ however, Tim is misinformed about what he calls the &apos;Rogerian, or non-directive, psychiatry&apos;. I can illustrate just how wrong by taking direct issue with that definition:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Rogerian â€“ this refers to Carl Rogers, who is best known as the founder of client-centred therapy, but Rogers in fact refused to recognise the burgeoning &apos;movement&apos; of &apos;Rogerians&apos; in his lifetime because his whole point was for human beings not to give up their being to some other person (or computer...). <o:p></o:p><br />Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Non-directive â€“ Rogers moved away from that definition and towards &apos;person-centred&apos; because it was more about the human being at the centre than about the process of therapy itself.<o:p></o:p><br />Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Psychiatry â€“ Carl Rogers was a psychologist, and although the distinction is not easy to make on a surface, non-practitioner level, it is important. The strong, central (and magazine cover) image of the psychiatrist&apos;s couch refers more to that Freudian psycho-analytical model where the psychiatrist is the one who gets to tell the &apos;patient&apos; what their dreams mean and how they should solve their problems. Carl Rogers broke decisively with this tradition and trusted his &apos;clients&apos; to find their own way towards growth and learning. Why does this matter? Tim clearly acknowledges the skit as parody, <a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=3680182410838117036#_edn1\" name=\"_ednref1\" style=\"mso-endnote-id: edn1;\" title=\"\">OPENBLOCKiCLOSEBLOCK</a>but, he also talks about Pygmalion&apos;s Eliza pretending to be something she is not and this, I think, is the central point â€“ if we really wish to rehumanise learning, including eLearning, then we have to provide an environment where human beings can feel, well...&amp;nbsp; human. As it happens, the choice of Carl Rogers&apos; approach is serendipitous when considering rehumanising the personal learning experience. Rogers took the central principles of his theory and applied them to contexts other than the therapy room â€“ including, to education.<a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=3680182410838117036#_edn2\" name=\"_ednref2\" style=\"mso-endnote-id: edn2;\" title=\"\">OPENBLOCKiiCLOSEBLOCK</a> Rogers shows how learning can involve a change in our perception of self and so can very often be perceived as threatening - and so, resisted. I guess readers are very familiar with this when technology is added to the mix. Therefore, to make learning possible, external threats must be minimised so that significant learning can take place. This means a change in roles as we have understood them in &apos;formal&apos; education and in the power-relations that are often the context for &apos;informal&apos; workplace learning:Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The learner needs to be empowered and have control over the learning processÂ·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The teacher gives up much of their authority and becomes a facilitator. This is not an easy task. However, Rogers has given us the means by focusing on the facilitator, whose main task is to create a warm, welcoming, unconditional space in which learners feel they have the freedom to be themselves, take ownership of their learning, and work creatively and collaboratively with other learners. The most important element is the attitudes the facilitator takes, how s/he is existentially - and these are:Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Be a real person, Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Empathise with learners (understand their point of view), Â·&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Trust (or prize) learners. The goal of a person-centred approach to learning is to create an atmosphere that promotes a person&apos;s inherent self-actualising tendency so that learners wish to learn, want to grow, and desire to create. I finish with the same quote from Albert Einstein that Rogers uses to front <i style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\">Freedom to Learn</i>: \"It is in fact nothing short of a miracle that the modern methods of instruction have not yet entirely strangled the holy curiosity of inquiry; for this delicate little plant, aside from stimulation, stands mainly in need of freedom; without this it goes to wrack and ruin without fail.\" I&apos;m certainly not going to argue with Einstein. <hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" /><br /><a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=3680182410838117036#_ednref1\" name=\"_edn1\" style=\"mso-endnote-id: edn1;\" title=\"\">OPENBLOCKiCLOSEBLOCK</a> Like any simple idea, it is easy to parody and, indeed, there was an even harsher parody from the 1940s where a suicidal &apos;patient&apos; in therapy eventually says \"I&apos;m opening the window Dr Rogers\"/\"I see, you&apos;re opening the window\"/\"I&apos;m about to jump\"/U-uhm. You&apos;re about to jump.\"/\"Here I goooo...\"/ \"There you go.\"<o:p></o:p><a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=3680182410838117036#_ednref2\" name=\"_edn2\" style=\"mso-endnote-id: edn2;\" title=\"\">OPENBLOCKiiCLOSEBLOCK</a> Tim acknowledges the power of an older text and so shall I. Carl Rogers&apos; Freedom To Learn for the 80s (1983, Columbus: Merrill) is a passionate and very human book which has helped move (some) education into a more person-centred approach â€“ it&apos;s a must-read for committed learning developers...<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-4193607293332189623?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(19,0,0,'Virtual Conference Tomorrow (May 2nd)','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/05/virtual-conference-tomorrow-may-2nd.html','hangout',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-05-01 12:53:48',19,'<a href=\"https://sites.google.com/site/eduonair/_/rsrc/1333549879549/config/customLogo.gif?revision=32\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"61\" src=\"https://sites.google.com/site/eduonair/_/rsrc/1333549879549/config/customLogo.gif?revision=32\" width=\"400\" /></a> Google Education are presenting (what I think is the first) &apos;On Air&apos;, an online conference using Google+ Hangouts (which is, btw, a fabulous conferencing/webcasting tool). There are half a dozen topics to choose from in six different categories, covering the educational purposes and uses of Google Apps, Youtube, the Cloud, Digital Literacy, portfolios... well, it&apos;s a long list, so here&apos;s the very first, which is titled &apos;Hot Topics in Educational Technology&apos;:<ul><li>&amp;nbsp;2pm&amp;nbsp;PD Now!</li><li>&amp;nbsp;3pm&amp;nbsp;Blended Learning </li><li>&amp;nbsp;4pm&amp;nbsp;Digital Literacy &amp;amp; Citizenship </li><li>&amp;nbsp;5pm&amp;nbsp;Teachers as Innovators and Entrepreneurs</li><li>&amp;nbsp;6pm&amp;nbsp;Digital Natives at The Gates: Giving in to 21st Century Learners is Not the Same as Giving Up </li><li>&amp;nbsp;8pm&amp;nbsp;Building Tomorrow&apos;s Innovators and Leaders with Robotics </li></ul>And here are the rest of the sessions: <a href=\"https://sites.google.com/site/eduonair/conference-sessions\">https://sites.google.com/site/eduonair/conference-sessions</a><br /><br />Times are for Eastern time, so add 4 hours for UK time.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-9118540459526684482?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447342,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-05-01T12:53:00.001+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"https://sites.google.com/site/eduonair/_/rsrc/1333549879549/config/customLogo.gif?revision=32\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"61\" src=\"https://sites.google.com/site/eduonair/_/rsrc/1333549879549/config/customLogo.gif?revision=32\" width=\"400\" /></a> Google Education are presenting (what I think is the first) &apos;On Air&apos;, an online conference using Google+ Hangouts (which is, btw, a fabulous conferencing/webcasting tool). There are half a dozen topics to choose from in six different categories, covering the educational purposes and uses of Google Apps, Youtube, the Cloud, Digital Literacy, portfolios... well, it&apos;s a long list, so here&apos;s the very first, which is titled &apos;Hot Topics in Educational Technology&apos;:<ul><li>&amp;nbsp;2pm&amp;nbsp;PD Now!</li><li>&amp;nbsp;3pm&amp;nbsp;Blended Learning </li><li>&amp;nbsp;4pm&amp;nbsp;Digital Literacy &amp;amp; Citizenship </li><li>&amp;nbsp;5pm&amp;nbsp;Teachers as Innovators and Entrepreneurs</li><li>&amp;nbsp;6pm&amp;nbsp;Digital Natives at The Gates: Giving in to 21st Century Learners is Not the Same as Giving Up </li><li>&amp;nbsp;8pm&amp;nbsp;Building Tomorrow&apos;s Innovators and Leaders with Robotics </li></ul>And here are the rest of the sessions: <a href=\"https://sites.google.com/site/eduonair/conference-sessions\">https://sites.google.com/site/eduonair/conference-sessions</a><br /><br />Times are for Eastern time, so add 4 hours for UK time.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-9118540459526684482?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(20,0,0,'A Fresh Look at eLearning','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/04/fresh-look-at-elearning.html','effective',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-23 10:24:43',19,'<a href=\"http://www.saffroninteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/elearning-network.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" src=\"http://www.saffroninteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/elearning-network.jpg\" /></a>This was the eLearning Network&apos;s first&amp;nbsp;event of the year (23rd March, and I&apos;ve only just got round to writing it up - might be better doing it there and then, in truth...) - focus on what makes eLearning effective. Here are a few of the highlights for me. <br /><br /><strong>Laura Overton, Towards Maturity</strong>: <em>The 6 characteristics of top performing learning organisations</em>.&amp;nbsp;What&apos;s worked and what hasn&apos;t. A very good presentation, underpinned by <a href=\"http://towardsmaturity.org/\">Toward&apos;s Maturity&apos;s own excellent research&amp;nbsp;base</a>. Laura spoke of:<br /><ul><li>the hunger for technology and learning to deliver business agility, </li><li>how to align elearning with company strategy (more mature organisations set measurable targets)</li><li>whether what companies do with technology supports skills and development, </li><li>the need for a personalised learning experience that is relevant to people </li><li>the need&amp;nbsp;to support staff career aspirations with learning technologies and to support talent management</li><li>the importance of aligning to need and&amp;nbsp;delivering impact</li></ul><o:p><strong>Ben Betts, HT2</strong>: <em>Five big trends for the next five years. </em>The core theories of learning and the potential impact that Social and Games-based learning technology has on each.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Absorbing presentation began with discussion of&amp;nbsp;</o:p><o:p>social learning - is it fad? what does it mean? there&apos;s nothing sadder than an empty forum... So...</o:p><br /><ol><li><o:p>what is known about the role of social interaction in a learning environment? social constructivism, action learning, communities of practice - Bandura&apos;s Social Learning Theory. </o:p></li><li><o:p>what is social software and how has it impacted society at large? social software can only be used in conjunction with other people. content is now being made in greater quantities than any other time in history - digital natives not good, but digital residents vs digital visitors is more compelling - it&apos;s a continuum - </o:p><o:p>residents happy to spend their lives online - </o:p>visitors get a tool out of the shed, job done.</li><li>How might social software impact the pedagogical approaches available to online teaching?</li><li>Motivation? intrinsic - macro theory (self-determination theory) - three innate psychological needs:&amp;nbsp; 1.&amp;nbsp;competence&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; 2.&amp;nbsp;autonomy&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; 3.&amp;nbsp;relatedness</li></ol><o:p>Curator software (Ben&apos;s own) development revealed 5 key themes (these are the five big trends):</o:p><ol><li>content is everywhere - curation is king (do we really need to develop another leadership course?), not content</li><li>gamification works - don&apos;t knock it till u&apos;ve tried it - when it&apos;s done properly it&apos;s extremely effective - example, make a comment to get points</li><li>social is enormously important and yet has barely yet begun (every second, one hour of video is uploaded to youtube)</li><li>interfaces are evolving - touch, gesture and voice</li><li>byot is going to be huge (bring your own technology)</li></ol><strong>&amp;nbsp;Julie Wedgwood, Productive Ltd</strong>: <em>How to enable learning anywhere</em>. Julie&apos;s energised session showed and shared a few learning technology tools that can be easily used to engage and encourage. and not&amp;nbsp;turn people off: <ul><li><a href=\"http://shakespeak.com/en/home/\">shakespeak</a> - voting on sms, website or twitter -&amp;nbsp;use a word cloud in wordle after, cut and past file info - also start with learners choosing which link from powerpoint </li><li><a href=\"http://en.linoit.com/\">Linoit</a> - web-based postit notes, can also be private, great for brainstorming, sharing teaching - have a backchannel on the board - then todaysmeet - create a room </li><li><a href=\"http://quizlet.com/\">Quizlet</a> - flash cards - quick quizzes</li><li><a href=\"http://www.xtranormal.com/\">www.xtranormal.com</a> - give to learners to play with - text to movie</li></ul><br /><br /><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8279117688822056675?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447342,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-23T10:24:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"http://www.saffroninteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/elearning-network.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" src=\"http://www.saffroninteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/elearning-network.jpg\" /></a>This was the eLearning Network&apos;s first&amp;nbsp;event of the year (23rd March, and I&apos;ve only just got round to writing it up - might be better doing it there and then, in truth...) - focus on what makes eLearning effective. Here are a few of the highlights for me. <br /><br /><strong>Laura Overton, Towards Maturity</strong>: <em>The 6 characteristics of top performing learning organisations</em>.&amp;nbsp;What&apos;s worked and what hasn&apos;t. A very good presentation, underpinned by <a href=\"http://towardsmaturity.org/\">Toward&apos;s Maturity&apos;s own excellent research&amp;nbsp;base</a>. Laura spoke of:<br /><ul><li>the hunger for technology and learning to deliver business agility, </li><li>how to align elearning with company strategy (more mature organisations set measurable targets)</li><li>whether what companies do with technology supports skills and development, </li><li>the need for a personalised learning experience that is relevant to people </li><li>the need&amp;nbsp;to support staff career aspirations with learning technologies and to support talent management</li><li>the importance of aligning to need and&amp;nbsp;delivering impact</li></ul><o:p><strong>Ben Betts, HT2</strong>: <em>Five big trends for the next five years. </em>The core theories of learning and the potential impact that Social and Games-based learning technology has on each.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Absorbing presentation began with discussion of&amp;nbsp;</o:p><o:p>social learning - is it fad? what does it mean? there&apos;s nothing sadder than an empty forum... So...</o:p><br /><ol><li><o:p>what is known about the role of social interaction in a learning environment? social constructivism, action learning, communities of practice - Bandura&apos;s Social Learning Theory. </o:p></li><li><o:p>what is social software and how has it impacted society at large? social software can only be used in conjunction with other people. content is now being made in greater quantities than any other time in history - digital natives not good, but digital residents vs digital visitors is more compelling - it&apos;s a continuum - </o:p><o:p>residents happy to spend their lives online - </o:p>visitors get a tool out of the shed, job done.</li><li>How might social software impact the pedagogical approaches available to online teaching?</li><li>Motivation? intrinsic - macro theory (self-determination theory) - three innate psychological needs:&amp;nbsp; 1.&amp;nbsp;competence&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; 2.&amp;nbsp;autonomy&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; 3.&amp;nbsp;relatedness</li></ol><o:p>Curator software (Ben&apos;s own) development revealed 5 key themes (these are the five big trends):</o:p><ol><li>content is everywhere - curation is king (do we really need to develop another leadership course?), not content</li><li>gamification works - don&apos;t knock it till u&apos;ve tried it - when it&apos;s done properly it&apos;s extremely effective - example, make a comment to get points</li><li>social is enormously important and yet has barely yet begun (every second, one hour of video is uploaded to youtube)</li><li>interfaces are evolving - touch, gesture and voice</li><li>byot is going to be huge (bring your own technology)</li></ol><strong>&amp;nbsp;Julie Wedgwood, Productive Ltd</strong>: <em>How to enable learning anywhere</em>. Julie&apos;s energised session showed and shared a few learning technology tools that can be easily used to engage and encourage. and not&amp;nbsp;turn people off: <ul><li><a href=\"http://shakespeak.com/en/home/\">shakespeak</a> - voting on sms, website or twitter -&amp;nbsp;use a word cloud in wordle after, cut and past file info - also start with learners choosing which link from powerpoint </li><li><a href=\"http://en.linoit.com/\">Linoit</a> - web-based postit notes, can also be private, great for brainstorming, sharing teaching - have a backchannel on the board - then todaysmeet - create a room </li><li><a href=\"http://quizlet.com/\">Quizlet</a> - flash cards - quick quizzes</li><li><a href=\"http://www.xtranormal.com/\">www.xtranormal.com</a> - give to learners to play with - text to movie</li></ul><br /><br /><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-8279117688822056675?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(21,0,0,'PowerPoint Masterclass: Visualisation','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/04/powerpoint-masterclass-visualisation.html','presentation',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-21 13:28:50',19,'<a href=\"http://www.brightcarbon.com/\">Brightcarbon</a> have been delivering some rather impressive webinars on approaches to PowerPoint presentations. The first one was on &apos;Visualisation&apos; and this is a quick summary of the main points. <br /><br />Slides which are packed with information cause audiences to disengage - thus making the presentation a complete waste of time for both presenter and audience as no information is communicated and retained. Recent research* reveals that slide design is critical. <br /><br />People recall more information from somebody talking without visual aids than from somebody with a packed slide. Also, the presenter is tuned out in favour of the information on the slide itself, which is seen as more important. If that slide is then made simpler, an audience will remember more because the presenter can then add more value to the presentation.<br /><br />It&apos;s impossible to listen and read at the same time, so audiences have to simply switch their attention between the slides and the presenter, which is both tiring and confusing, and people will just pick one and ignore the other. When the presenter and the slides are working in synch, audiences pay most attention and remember the most.<br /><br />What to do? Well, recent neurological research** shows that vision is the most important sense in humans, and as presentations are a visual channel of communication, we should:<br /><ul><li>reduce text as far as possible (put text in the speaker notes instead of on the slides)</li><li>look at the story behind the slide and use pictures, diagrams and graphs that help you tell that story</li><li>not worry if those pictures are not completely self-explanatory, or they build up or change - then the audience is more motivated towards the presenter&apos;s explanation</li></ul>This means that the same message is delivered consistently across two channels and the audience doesn&apos;t need to switch their attention because they are getting visual information from the slides and verbal information from the presenter. <br /><br />So, Visualisation means giving the audience something that can be easily understood and which reinforces your point.<br /><br />There is one more webinar to go, so if you&apos;re interested, here are the details - it&apos;s well worth half an hour of your time: <a href=\"http://www.brightcarbon.com/events/online-powerpoint-\">Online PowerPoint Masterclass â€“ 25th April 2012 @ 1pm (BST)</a> <br /><br />* Wecker, Christof (2012) \"Slidepresentations as speechsuppressors: When and why learners miss oral information\" in Computers &amp;amp; Education Volume 59, Issue 2, September 2012, Pages 260â€“273&amp;nbsp;** Wandell, Dumoulin &amp;amp; Brewer (2007) \"Visual Field Maps in Human Cortex\" in Neuron, Volume 56, Issue 2, 25 October 2007, Pages 366â€“383<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-4242617252701435889?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447342,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-21T13:28:00.000+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"http://www.brightcarbon.com/\">Brightcarbon</a> have been delivering some rather impressive webinars on approaches to PowerPoint presentations. The first one was on &apos;Visualisation&apos; and this is a quick summary of the main points. <br /><br />Slides which are packed with information cause audiences to disengage - thus making the presentation a complete waste of time for both presenter and audience as no information is communicated and retained. Recent research* reveals that slide design is critical. <br /><br />People recall more information from somebody talking without visual aids than from somebody with a packed slide. Also, the presenter is tuned out in favour of the information on the slide itself, which is seen as more important. If that slide is then made simpler, an audience will remember more because the presenter can then add more value to the presentation.<br /><br />It&apos;s impossible to listen and read at the same time, so audiences have to simply switch their attention between the slides and the presenter, which is both tiring and confusing, and people will just pick one and ignore the other. When the presenter and the slides are working in synch, audiences pay most attention and remember the most.<br /><br />What to do? Well, recent neurological research** shows that vision is the most important sense in humans, and as presentations are a visual channel of communication, we should:<br /><ul><li>reduce text as far as possible (put text in the speaker notes instead of on the slides)</li><li>look at the story behind the slide and use pictures, diagrams and graphs that help you tell that story</li><li>not worry if those pictures are not completely self-explanatory, or they build up or change - then the audience is more motivated towards the presenter&apos;s explanation</li></ul>This means that the same message is delivered consistently across two channels and the audience doesn&apos;t need to switch their attention because they are getting visual information from the slides and verbal information from the presenter. <br /><br />So, Visualisation means giving the audience something that can be easily understood and which reinforces your point.<br /><br />There is one more webinar to go, so if you&apos;re interested, here are the details - it&apos;s well worth half an hour of your time: <a href=\"http://www.brightcarbon.com/events/online-powerpoint-\">Online PowerPoint Masterclass â€“ 25th April 2012 @ 1pm (BST)</a> <br /><br />* Wecker, Christof (2012) \"Slidepresentations as speechsuppressors: When and why learners miss oral information\" in Computers &amp;amp; Education Volume 59, Issue 2, September 2012, Pages 260â€“273&amp;nbsp;** Wandell, Dumoulin &amp;amp; Brewer (2007) \"Visual Field Maps in Human Cortex\" in Neuron, Volume 56, Issue 2, 25 October 2007, Pages 366â€“383<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-4242617252701435889?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(22,0,0,'Open Clip Art Library','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/04/open-clip-art-library.html','graphics',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-18 16:18:43',19,'<a href=\"https://twimg0-a.akamaihd.net/profile_images/733501598/OCL-logo_plus_2_reasonably_small.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" src=\"https://twimg0-a.akamaihd.net/profile_images/733501598/OCL-logo_plus_2_reasonably_small.jpg\" /></a>I was searching around for an image to use on a quick draft website and found this: <a href=\"http://openclipart.org/\">http://openclipart.org</a> <br />They say: \"The Open Clipart Library (OCAL) is the Largest Collaboration Community that creates, shares and remixes clipart. All clipart is released to the public domain and may be used in any project for free and with no restrictions.\"  <br /><br />I say: wow! thank you so much for providing such an amazing resource and it&apos;s a fantastic example of generosity and collaboration on our open worldwide web. Go there, use stuff - and also consider making stuff for the site. <br /><br />And you can follow on Twitter: <a href=\"https://twitter.com/openclipart\">https://twitter.com/openclipart</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-5631272098712768448?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447343,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-18T16:18:00.001+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"https://twimg0-a.akamaihd.net/profile_images/733501598/OCL-logo_plus_2_reasonably_small.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" src=\"https://twimg0-a.akamaihd.net/profile_images/733501598/OCL-logo_plus_2_reasonably_small.jpg\" /></a>I was searching around for an image to use on a quick draft website and found this: <a href=\"http://openclipart.org/\">http://openclipart.org</a> <br />They say: \"The Open Clipart Library (OCAL) is the Largest Collaboration Community that creates, shares and remixes clipart. All clipart is released to the public domain and may be used in any project for free and with no restrictions.\"  <br /><br />I say: wow! thank you so much for providing such an amazing resource and it&apos;s a fantastic example of generosity and collaboration on our open worldwide web. Go there, use stuff - and also consider making stuff for the site. <br /><br />And you can follow on Twitter: <a href=\"https://twitter.com/openclipart\">https://twitter.com/openclipart</a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-5631272098712768448?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(23,0,0,'Open Access Educational Technology journals','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/04/open-access-educational-technology.html','elearning',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-16 14:53:31',19,'<a href=\"http://openreflections.files.wordpress.com/2010/01/open20access-seal.gif\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"200\" src=\"http://openreflections.files.wordpress.com/2010/01/open20access-seal.gif\" width=\"200\" /></a>Thanks so much to George Veletsianos (at his blog at <a href=\"http://www.veletsianos.com/\">http://www.veletsianos.com/</a>) for compiling and then generously sharing a truly immense listing of open access journals ranging across technology and education. Perhaps with a playful nod to less altruistic practitioners and academics, George says it would \"obviously\" be plain silly to develop such a resource and not share it openly - so, come on you slowcoach teachers, hurry up and share your good stuff,&amp;nbsp;you foot-dragging institutions...<br /><br />Ahem. Anyway, you&apos;ll find the resource <a href=\"https://spreadsheets.google.com/pub?key=tfNCoAf3QgerKQnhd0ZgqTg&amp;amp;single=true&amp;amp;gid=0&amp;amp;output=html\">as a web page</a> and <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AhItXt_TNLlRdGZOQ29BZjNRZ2VyS1FuaGQwWmdxVGc#gid=0\">as a spreadsheet</a> (if you have a google account - and note, that this is editable too, so you can add your own journal by using <a href=\"https://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=dGZOQ29BZjNRZ2VyS1FuaGQwWmdxVGc6MA..\">this form</a>). <br /><br />A fantastic and generous spirited idea, thanks George!<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6897357182476859168?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447343,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-16T14:53:00.002+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'<a href=\"http://openreflections.files.wordpress.com/2010/01/open20access-seal.gif\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;\"><img border=\"0\" height=\"200\" src=\"http://openreflections.files.wordpress.com/2010/01/open20access-seal.gif\" width=\"200\" /></a>Thanks so much to George Veletsianos (at his blog at <a href=\"http://www.veletsianos.com/\">http://www.veletsianos.com/</a>) for compiling and then generously sharing a truly immense listing of open access journals ranging across technology and education. Perhaps with a playful nod to less altruistic practitioners and academics, George says it would \"obviously\" be plain silly to develop such a resource and not share it openly - so, come on you slowcoach teachers, hurry up and share your good stuff,&amp;nbsp;you foot-dragging institutions...<br /><br />Ahem. Anyway, you&apos;ll find the resource <a href=\"https://spreadsheets.google.com/pub?key=tfNCoAf3QgerKQnhd0ZgqTg&amp;amp;single=true&amp;amp;gid=0&amp;amp;output=html\">as a web page</a> and <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AhItXt_TNLlRdGZOQ29BZjNRZ2VyS1FuaGQwWmdxVGc#gid=0\">as a spreadsheet</a> (if you have a google account - and note, that this is editable too, so you can add your own journal by using <a href=\"https://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=dGZOQ29BZjNRZ2VyS1FuaGQwWmdxVGc6MA..\">this form</a>). <br /><br />A fantastic and generous spirited idea, thanks George!<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-6897357182476859168?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(24,0,0,'Being a real person with learners','text/html','http://aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com/2012/04/being-real-person-with-learners.html','freedom',NULL,NULL,342,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-16 10:12:56',19,'A few months ago, I delivered a presentation about freedom and control in the classroom and was asked the question \"what does it mean to be real in a teaching and learning context\" (or something very close to that) - and I think I gave quite an unsatisfactory and&amp;nbsp;surface answer, so that the question has been at the back of my mind ever since. So, I was really pleased to find this from Carl Rogers (and recognising the unintentional sexism of the late 1950s using&amp;nbsp;&apos;he&apos; and &apos;his&apos; when talking in general about people) about the conditions for significant learning, which can be encouraged to the extent that the teacher/facilitator:<br /><blockquote class=\"tr_bq\">&amp;nbsp;\"...becomes a real person in the relationship with his students. He can be enthusiastic about subjects he likes, and bored by topics he does not like. He can be angry, but he can also be sensitive or sympathetic. Because he accepts his feelings as his feelings, he has no need to impose them on his students, or to insist they feel the same way. He is a <em>person</em>, not a faceless embodiment of a curricular requirement, or a sterile pipe through which knowledge is passed from one generation to the next.\" (Rogers, 1961, <em>On Becoming a Person</em>, Constable and Robinson, London). </blockquote>I trust this is a case of better late than never when I say I hope that answers the question!<br /><blockquote class=\"tr_bq\"></blockquote><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-5053742462278408975?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347447343,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-04-16T10:12:00.002+01:00',NULL,'As Wonderful As Sunsets',NULL,'A few months ago, I delivered a presentation about freedom and control in the classroom and was asked the question \"what does it mean to be real in a teaching and learning context\" (or something very close to that) - and I think I gave quite an unsatisfactory and&amp;nbsp;surface answer, so that the question has been at the back of my mind ever since. So, I was really pleased to find this from Carl Rogers (and recognising the unintentional sexism of the late 1950s using&amp;nbsp;&apos;he&apos; and &apos;his&apos; when talking in general about people) about the conditions for significant learning, which can be encouraged to the extent that the teacher/facilitator:<br /><blockquote class=\"tr_bq\">&amp;nbsp;\"...becomes a real person in the relationship with his students. He can be enthusiastic about subjects he likes, and bored by topics he does not like. He can be angry, but he can also be sensitive or sympathetic. Because he accepts his feelings as his feelings, he has no need to impose them on his students, or to insist they feel the same way. He is a <em>person</em>, not a faceless embodiment of a curricular requirement, or a sterile pipe through which knowledge is passed from one generation to the next.\" (Rogers, 1961, <em>On Becoming a Person</em>, Constable and Robinson, London). </blockquote>I trust this is a case of better late than never when I say I hope that answers the question!<br /><blockquote class=\"tr_bq\"></blockquote><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/3680182410838117036-5053742462278408975?l=aswonderfulassunsets.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(25,0,0,'Assessment Myself / Self Examination / Contradictions â€“ Week 2','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/09/10/assessment-myself-self-examination-contradictions-week-2/','EducaciÃ³n;MOOC;TIC;moocmooc;potcert;Week 2',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'I am here, in the PotCert, to learn, to learn a lot, because I have no experience teaching. It is really a very good experience to read the peers week 2 posts, and the tools provided are really a good start. I took some of your experience to think about it. I will give some &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/09/10/assessment-myself-self-examination-contradictions-week-2/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=792&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449172,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Mon, 10 Sep 2012 19:37:15 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I am here, in the PotCert, to learn, to learn a lot, because I have no experience teaching. It is really a very good experience to read the peers week 2 posts, and the tools provided are really a good start. I took some of your experience to think about it. I will give some months classes during my MA this academic year, but not yet. So let&#8217;s go to do a self-examination and check what I would do. I found some contradictions between my thoughts, by answering the questionaire, and the results I thought I would have.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/4056644608_79eb24b78d_m.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-817\" title=\"Each holding a part\" src=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/4056644608_79eb24b78d_m.jpg?w=580\" alt=\"\"  /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a style=\"text-align:justify;\" title=\"Nestor Alonso\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nestoralonso/\" target=\"_blank\">Nestor Alonso Picture</a>Â / <a style=\"text-align:justify;\" title=\"Creative Commons\" href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/deed.en\" target=\"_blank\">(CC BY-SA 2.0)</a></p>\n<p>The title isÂ <strong><em>each holding a part</em></strong>Â (of the knowledge). This is what I thing it should work. Every one sharing their knowledge to do a unit. But after filling the <a title=\"Beginners Questionnaire\" href=\"http://lisahistory.net/pot/BeginnersQuestionnaire.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">questionnaire</a>Â and watching the <a title=\"Lisa&apos;s Video\" href=\"http://mccpot.org/wp/2012/03/self-paced-where-the-hell-do-i-start/\" target=\"_blank\">Lisa&#8217;s video</a>Â I saw some contradictions, because my answers didn&#8217;t fit with it.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Assessment myself, this is what I am doing beginning of week 2 of the Pot Cert proposal. To fill in a questionnaire and to evaluate the results. So simple? Not when the obtained results are not what you think you should have. This make moving your head from one side to the other, checking the questionnaire and the answers to ensure everything is right. And the result remain equal. You are on the right side of the line. This is not bad or good itself, the problem is when you think you are in the left side/middle and you confirmed you are in the right.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Howsoever I am not actually a teacher, so this is not only to see what kind of teacher I am, better is what kind of teacher I would be. So, really, I am starting from the beginning and I can improve to the best proposal, if there is a best proposal, of course.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Talking about my matter, philosophy, I think that the best is to be at the right side, that means <em>providing a big amount of content to the students</em>Â but, after some reflection about the drawings Lisa linked, I think there is good a second step where the students could take part of the teacher&#8217;s role and produce and drive the class and the materials, andÂ <em>introduce discussions in the class.Â </em>So probably I would move toÂ <em>a combination of lectures and discussions.</em> Then there are several proposals for the activities I am sure I will reflect about. But the main thing is that I would do a two step proposal, giving as much materials as possible, not only lectures but also videos and other internet material as a first; and a second step where the students were able to share their experiences and thoughts after attending all of these lectures.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">So, I think correct would be a little bit more to the left than my 19. I saw I am very prescriptive, probably because my inexperience, and I think that I should be a little bit less and give more flexibility to the students with this second step. There was a very interesting reflection for me because, with this short questionnaire and drawing, I saw that I was thinking to do the same teaching I received in the university, and I always critiziced, and permit me to understand and see a different way of teaching.</p>\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=792&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(26,0,0,'POT cert presentation &#8211; Week 1','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/09/02/pot-cert-presentation-week-1/','EducaciÃ³n;Internet;MOOC;TIC;moocmooc;potcert;Week 1',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'I would like to say hello to my peers in the Program for Online Teaching Certificate. The first SMOOC I am taking. I am sure this will be a nice and exciting experience. I will just introduce you a part of me and my life. I am Xavier and I am blogging from Barcelona, a &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/09/02/pot-cert-presentation-week-1/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=727&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449172,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Sun, 02 Sep 2012 16:25:43 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I would like to say hello to my peers in the <em>Program for Online Teaching Certificate</em>. The first <em>SMOOC</em> I am taking. I am sure this will be a nice and exciting experience. I will just introduce you a part of me and my life.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I am Xavier and I am blogging from Barcelona, a very beautiful city situated in the north-east of Spain. I am living with my wife and my two little daughters about 20 kms. from the center, just in the mountain. They are 6 and 4-year-old, and it is really a very nice experience see how they learn about the world around them.Â Normally I speak catalan daily with my family and university colleges but also I speak spanish.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/71088059@N00/430564338/\"><img src=\"http://farm1.staticflickr.com/149/430564338_90e703e800_n.jpg\" alt=\"Clean air Barcelona Neta ;-)\" width=\"320\" height=\"238\" /></a></p>\n<p><em>Clear air Barcelona Neta</em><br />\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/paco_calvino/430564338/lightbox/\">http://www.flickr.com/photos/paco_calvino/430564338/lightbox/</a>Â <a title=\"CC BY-NC-SA 2.0\" href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/deed.en\" target=\"_blank\">(CC BY-NC-SA 2.0)</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I started blogging<em>Â </em>almost one year ago and this course will permit me by blogging in english and also blogging about education.Â Normally I will post in English (I will do my best) for the course, but you could find also some other posts in Spanish. Please fell free to take a walk in my blog and to comment.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I am a graduate in philosophy but my work nowadays has nothing to be with it or with education. This is why I am preparing myself with this and other courses. This academic year, as I explained in my <a title=\"Next academic course / PrÃ³ximo cursoÂ acadÃ©mico\" href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/27/next-academic-course-proximo-curso-academico/\" target=\"_blank\">previous post</a>, I will take a MA in the Teachers School of the <a title=\"UB\" href=\"http://www.ub.edu/web/ub/en/index.html?\" target=\"_blank\">Universitat de Barcelona</a>Â to be a Philosophy Teacher in the secondary School.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Normally I like very much reading philosophy, specially ancient greek philosophy ( I like very much Plato, Socrates and Aristotle), and contemporary continental tradition, hermeneutic-phenomenologic (Husserl, Heidegger and Gadamer), but this is only with paper books. I do not use the web to read about philosophy, to be honest I donÂ´t know exactly why, I will explore it. Now I am reading a lot about education, learning, e-learning and MOOC&#8217;s, specially on the web.Â I am excited to received and start reading the course book, although I think I will receive it with some delay because I booked it last week.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I like very much internet and social media and technologies and also I am enthusiastic with philosophy online teaching and also a discipline called digital humanities. This is why I decide to do this course. I saw that some of you had participate in theÂ <a title=\"Social Media and Open Education\" href=\"http://eci831.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Social media and open education</a> course and other courses, so most of you have a lot of experience in education and also in education online courses. I am sure I will follow you and, at the end, I hope I could collaborate with some online courses. The way I read on the internet is by following hashtag that are of my interest. I am using <a title=\"Diigo\" href=\"http://www.diigo.com\" target=\"_blank\">Diigo</a>Â to bookmark and save by tags all the pages of my interest.Â Actually I read about higher education, <a title=\"Diigo HigherEducation\" href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/xavcap/highereducation\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>Â some of the articles, about digital humanities (DH), <a title=\"Diigo Digital Humanities\" href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/xavcap/digitalhumanities\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>Â some articles and some information about DH MA. I am interested in the DH Pedagogy. To end this short resume about my reading interest, I like very much to read articles about MOOC&#8217;s, just to try to understand what is happening with this <em>new education alternative</em>, because I think that the MOOC&#8217;s has a lot of interest to develop to the learners during a long period after the university, <a title=\"MOOC`s\" href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/xavcap/MOOCS\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>Â you can find some articles about what a MOOC is.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I hope we can participate all together in the blogs with comments but also in twitter with the tag <a title=\"#potcert\" href=\"https://twitter.com//search/?q=%23potcert&amp;src=hash\" target=\"_blank\">#potcert</a> and in the Facebook group.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">See you online.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=727&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(27,0,0,'Embedding Test for Youtube, Slideshare and Flickr','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/29/embedding-test-for-youtube-and-slideshare/','Sin categorÃ­a;test',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'Digital Reality from Chris Schaumann<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=713&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449172,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Wed, 29 Aug 2012 16:01:32 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<iframe src=&apos;http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/81094&apos; width=&apos;427&apos; height=&apos;350&apos; scrolling=&apos;no&apos;></iframe>\n<strong> <a title=\"Digital Reality\" href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/chriss/digital-reality\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Reality</a> </strong> from <strong><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/chriss\" target=\"_blank\">Chris Schaumann</a></strong>\n<p><a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/29/embedding-test-for-youtube-and-slideshare/\"><img src=\"http://img.youtube.com/vi/Pa5_Qf7dh3Q/2.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/xavcap/7010387875/in/photostream\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7098/7010387875_c470d517ff_n.jpg\" alt=\"Portalada\" width=\"214\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/10123995@N04/923344988/\"><img src=\"http://farm2.staticflickr.com/1295/923344988_3ee8e83e3f_n.jpg\" alt=\"Medieval Manor\" width=\"217\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=713&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(28,0,0,'My MOOCMOOC reflections.','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/29/my-moocmooc-reflections/','MOOC;ReflexiÃ³n;TIC;moocmooc',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'After reading thisÂ postÂ by @martinlugtonÂ and this other by @RosemarySewart, both MOOCMOOC participants, I thought that, at least, I owe a post to the MOOCMOOC people of theÂ course I took during this moth. I was, in some kind, obligated to explain my thoughts. Why? Because I as mentioned in my previous post I follow almost completely the &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/29/my-moocmooc-reflections/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=673&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449173,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Wed, 29 Aug 2012 08:21:10 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">After reading thisÂ <a title=\"MOOCMOOC Reflections\" href=\"http://reflectionsandcontemplations.wordpress.com/2012/08/26/im-trying-to-plan-my-next-mooc-but-all-this-learning-gets-in-the-way-reflections-on-the-moocmooc-and-where-i-go-next/\" target=\"_blank\">post</a>Â by @martinlugtonÂ and <a title=\"MOOCMOOC reflection\" href=\"http://moserary.tumblr.com/post/29678301100/the-final-scene-of-moocsummer-nights-dream-a\" target=\"_blank\">this other</a> by @RosemarySewart, both MOOCMOOC participants, I thought that, at least, I owe a post to the <a title=\"MOOCMOOC course\" href=\"http://www.moocmooc.com/\" target=\"_blank\">MOOCMOOC </a>people of theÂ course I took during this moth. I was, in some kind, obligated to explain my thoughts. Why? Because I as mentioned in my <a title=\"MOOC. Massive Open OnlineÂ Course\" href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/20/mooc-massive-open-online-course/\" target=\"_blank\">previous</a> post I follow almost completely the course, each day, each activity, from the shadows,Â behind this parapet internet provides us, but I share nothing. And also because I continue engaged, because I continue following #moocmooc at twitter.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I just followed the course and I am following #moocmooc but without any participation. I thought I could not keep course pace. It was my first MOOC, and in english, scary for a non english speaker.<br />\nBut the experience was very nice for me, after this week I decided to do some other MOOC&#8217;s, xMOOC&#8217;s and cMOOC&#8217;s, and now I am enrrolled in some courses, a part for my MA, for the next academic year. And I was encouraged, specially, because the moocmooc and because the <a title=\"Connectivism\" href=\"http://www.connectivism.ca/?p=116\" target=\"_blank\">connectivism</a>Â that has occurred,Â and that I listened for the first time the second day of the course.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Also I am reading a lot of information sent by other participants to the twitter and I am learning a lot. It is a kind of debt to say, hello I am/ I was here, thank you very much to all MOOCMOOC participants.<a href=\"http://www.connectivism.ca/\"><br />\n</a></p>\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=673&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(29,0,0,'Next academic course / PrÃ³ximo curso acadÃ©mico','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/27/next-academic-course-proximo-curso-academico/','EducaciÃ³n;Internet;MOOC;TIC;potcert',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'This new entry is to present the beginning of next course I will make from September. As I mentioned in the previous post the goal is to support the Master in Pedagogy I&#8217;ll make the next academic year with online courses. I commented the other two that I will follow, Â E-learning and Digital CulturesÂ andÂ Â Openness in &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/27/next-academic-course-proximo-curso-academico/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=641&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449173,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Mon, 27 Aug 2012 22:27:21 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">This new entry is to present the beginning of next course I will make from September. As I mentioned in the <a title=\"MOOC. Massive Open Online Course. PreparaciÃ³nÂ Inicial.\" href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/26/mooc-massive-open-online-course-preparacion-inicial/\" target=\"_blank\">previous</a> post the goal is to support the Master in Pedagogy I&#8217;ll make the next academic year with online courses. I commented the other two that I will follow, Â <em>E-learning and Digital Cultures</em>Â andÂ Â <em>Openness in education</em>. This will be a program to teach online, <a title=\"POT\" href=\"http://pedagogyfirst.org/wppf12/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>POT (Program for Online Teaching)</strong></a>. The program will run over 24 weeks, 12 weeks from September to November, and 12 more from February to April.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">I think the three courses, two MOOC, and this third OOC (Open Online Class), will complement very well and that will be a great opportunity to connect them each other, and these with the Master, and all with a common nexus, <strong>education</strong> in general and <strong>online education of the humanities</strong>, that is the reason of my interest, in particular.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Since the two previous courses will overlap with this and probably with other posts of the master, I will try to make a good tag management. The latter will be using the hashtag <strong>#potcert</strong>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Finally comment that the courses require a job to perform, participate in forums, in the blog itself, in tweets and doing videos, within other things, and how the three are in USA, I will do all of this information in English (in my best English). So this will be the last post bilingual. Those who will follow will be in English, if they are any of the online courses, or Spanish for the rest of the posts.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong>Clarification:</strong> The MA name in which I am trying to get as first option is not pedagogy, is on the faculty of teachers for secondary teacher.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â Â </p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Esta nueva entrada es para presentar el inicio del prÃ³ximo curso que voy a realizar a partir de Septiembre. Como comentÃ© en el post <a title=\"MOOC. Massive Open Online Course. PreparaciÃ³nÂ Inicial.\" href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/26/mooc-massive-open-online-course-preparacion-inicial/\" target=\"_blank\">anterior</a>Â el objetivo es el de apoyar el MÃ¡ster en PedagogÃ­a que voy a realizar el prÃ³ximo curso acadÃ©mico con cursos de educaciÃ³n online. Ya comentÃ© los otros dos que voy a seguir, <em>E-learning and Digital Cultures</em>Â y <em>Openness in education</em>. Este nuevo es un programa para enseÃ±ar online, <a title=\"POT\" href=\"http://pedagogyfirst.org/wppf12/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong><em>POT (Program for Online Teaching)</em></strong></a>. El programa se desarrollarÃ¡ en 24 semanas, 12 semanas de Septiembre a Noviembre, y 12 mÃ¡s de Febrero a Abril.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Pienso que los 3 cursos, dos de ellos <em>MOOC</em>, y este tercero <em>OOC (Open Online Class), </em>se van a complementar muy bien y que van a ser una magnÃ­fica oportunidad para relacionar unos con otros, y estos con el MÃ¡ster, y todo teniendo un nexo comÃºn, la<strong> educaciÃ³n</strong> en general, y la <strong>educaciÃ³n online de las humanidades</strong>, que es el motivo de mi interÃ©s, en particular.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Como quiera que los dos cursos anteriores se van a solapar con este y, probablemente, con otros posts del mÃ¡ster, intentarÃ© hacer una buena gestiÃ³n de etiquetas. Este Ãºltimo serÃ¡ con el hashtag <strong>#potcert</strong>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Por Ãºltimo comentaros que los cursos requieren de un trabajo a realizar, participaciÃ³n en foros, en el propio bloc, en twitter y vÃ­deos, entre otros, y como los 3 son en USA, toda esta informaciÃ³n la harÃ© en inglÃ©s (en mi mejor inglÃ©s). AsÃ­ pues este serÃ¡ el Ãºltimo post bilingÃ¼e. Los que siguen serÃ¡n en inglÃ©s si son de cualquiera de los cursos o en castellano para el resto.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong>Nota:</strong>Â El nombre del mÃ¡ster en el que estoy intentando entrar como primera opciÃ³n no es de pedagogÃ­a, es en la facultad de profesorado para ser profesor de secundaria.</p>\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=641&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(30,28,0,'MOOC. Massive Open Online Course. PreparaciÃ³n Inicial.','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/26/mooc-massive-open-online-course-preparacion-inicial/','EducaciÃ³n;MOOC;#oped12',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'Tal y como habÃ­a comentado en el anterior post habÃ­a decidido seguir dos cursos MOOC, elÂ ofrecido por coursera,Â E-learning and Digital Cultures,Â con un programa Â de la Universidad de Edimburgo y Â el otro, de la Universidad de Alicante,Â iDESWEB: IntroducciÃ³n al desarrollo web.Â  El objetivo de los cursos es el de introducirme en la educaciÃ³n online, pero MOOC, &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/26/mooc-massive-open-online-course-preparacion-inicial/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=620&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449173,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Sun, 26 Aug 2012 10:16:24 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo','28','<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Tal y como habÃ­a comentado en el anterior post habÃ­a decidido seguir dos cursos MOOC, elÂ ofrecido por coursera,Â <strong><a title=\"E-Learning and digital cultures\" href=\"https://www.coursera.org/course/edc\" target=\"_blank\">E-learning and Digital Cultures</a>,Â </strong>con un programa Â de la Universidad de Edimburgo y Â el otro, de la Universidad de Alicante,<a title=\"IntroducciÃ³n al desarrollo web\" href=\"http://idesweb.es/\" target=\"_blank\">Â </a><strong><a title=\"IntroducciÃ³n al desarrollo web\" href=\"http://idesweb.es/\" target=\"_blank\">iDESWEB: IntroducciÃ³n al desarrollo web</a>.Â </strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">El objetivo de los cursos es el de introducirme en la educaciÃ³n online, pero <em>MOOC</em>, para, posteriormente, desarrollar mis trabajos de TIC&#8217;s aplicadas a la educaciÃ³n de humanidades, especialmente filosofÃ­a, durante el MÃ¡ster que pretendo hacer el siguiente curso en la <em><a title=\"UB\" href=\"http://www.ub.edu/web/ub/ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Universidad de Barcelona.</a>Â </em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Finalmente he decidido no seguir el de <em>IntroducciÃ³n al desarrollo web</em> pues, aÃºn siendo muy interesante, y despuÃ©s de realizar un test que hay en la introducciÃ³n inicial del curso, he podido ver que no lo hubiese podido seguir con normalidad pues eran necesarios ciertos, aunque la verdad es que pequeÃ±os, pero necesarios, conocimientos de programaciÃ³n. Por otro lado he sustituido este por otro curso, este ofrecido por la <em><a title=\"Athabascau University\" href=\"http://www.athabascau.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Universidad de Athabasca</a>Â </em>y que forma parte del <a title=\"MeD\" href=\"http://cde.athabascau.ca/programs/mde.php\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>MÃ¡ster de EducaciÃ³n en EducaciÃ³n a Distancia, (MeD)</strong></a>. El curso se llama <strong><a title=\"Openness education\" href=\"http://open.mooc.ca/about.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Openness in education</a>Â </strong>y se realizarÃ¡ durante 12 semanas a partir de la segunda semana de Septiembre.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">El seguimiento del primer curso,Â <em>Openness in Education,Â </em>a partir de Septiembre y que durarÃ¡ 12 semanas, lo harÃ© principalmente con el hashtag <strong><em>#oped12</em></strong>. Para el segundo que empezarÃ¡ a partir de finales de Enero y que durarÃ¡ 5 semanas todavÃ­a no hay seguimiento. InformarÃ© antes del comienzo del curso.</p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong>Â¿CÃ³mo estoy preparando los cursos?</strong></h2>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">El objetivo principal de cualquier curso deberÃ­a ser aprender. El objetivo,Â prÃ¡cticamenteÂ el Ãºnico, de un MOOC es aprender Â¿por quÃ© digo esto? Pues porque debido a que la mayorÃ­a de los cursos, todo y ser impartidos por expertos en las materias y por prestigiosas universidades, no dan un certificado del trabajo realizado ni de seguimiento del curso, <strong><em>aprender</em></strong> se convierte en finalidad casi exclusiva. Aunque esto no es del todo cierto si pensamos en que <em><strong>compartir</strong>Â </em>en nuestros blocs y en nuestros twitters, con infinidad de participantes, todo aquello que vayamos asimilando, es tambiÃ©n un objetivo, pues asÃ­ iremos avanzando en nuestro aprendizaje. A la vez los alumnos se convierten en profesores, aportando material y avanzando en lo propuesto por los profesores, y estos se convierten en alumnos,Â impregnÃ¡ndoseÂ con los comentarios de miles de participantes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Por otro lado en los cursos se describen una serie de herramientas que van a ser las que los participantes van a utilizar para la creaciÃ³n de sus propios contenidos. Para ello se ha de estar habituado a la navegaciÃ³n web, visualizaciÃ³n de vÃ­deos, identificaciÃ³n y guardado (marcado) de las pÃ¡ginas web que creamos interesantes tanto para seguir el curso como para la producciÃ³n de nuestro Â material. Por supuesto serÃ¡n necesarias cuentas en algÃºn servicio de blogging para la creaciÃ³n de un blog, y en twitter, FaceBook, o cualquier otro servicio deÂ InternetÂ con el que trabajemos.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">He cambiado mi gestor de marcadores <em>Delicious </em>por<em> Diigo.Â </em>La ventaja de este es que, ademÃ¡s de poder poner <em>tag</em> a todas las webs guardadas, puedes poner notas, marcar con fluorescente aquellas partes del texto que mÃ¡s te han interesado y guardar una imagen de la pÃ¡gina o de una selecciÃ³n de la misma. Facilitando asÃ­ identificar el motivo por el que guardamos la pÃ¡gina cuando lo hicimos.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">El trabajo principal es pues utilizar las herramientas propuestas. Trabajar con ellas, sobre ellas, y al lado de nuestros miles de compaÃ±eros repartidos por todo el mundo. Y, a elecciÃ³n de cada uno de los participantes, compartirlas con el resto como yo ya estoy haciendo.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=620&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(31,0,0,'MOOC. Massive Open Online Course','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/20/mooc-massive-open-online-course/','EducaciÃ³n;MOOC',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'En mÃ­ ligero devaneo veraniego surfeando la web en bÃºsqueda de informaciÃ³n que me ayude en el MA que pretendo empezar en septiembre me encontrÃ© con las HD (Humanidades digitales). Muestra son los artÃ­culos que he ido colgando. El primeroÂ fueÂ Humanidades e Internet. Como expliquÃ©, pensaba haber encontrado el santo grial cuando descubrÃ­ Â el periodismo de &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/20/mooc-massive-open-online-course/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=578&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449173,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Mon, 20 Aug 2012 13:05:18 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">En mÃ­ ligero devaneo veraniego surfeando la web en bÃºsqueda de informaciÃ³n que me ayude en el MA que pretendo empezar en septiembre me encontrÃ© con las HD (Humanidades digitales). Muestra son los artÃ­culos que he ido colgando. El primeroÂ fueÂ <em><a title=\"Humanidades e Internet\" href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/07/14/la-filosofia-e-internet/\" target=\"_blank\">Humanidades e Internet</a>. </em>Como expliquÃ©, pensaba haber encontrado el santo grial cuando descubrÃ­ Â el <em>periodismo de datosÂ </em>con el artÃ­culoÂ <em><a title=\"Periodisme de dades\" href=\"http://blocs.gencat.cat/blocs/AppPHP/gencat/2012/07/12/el-periodisme-d%E2%80%99avui-es-periodisme-de-dades/\" target=\"_blank\">El periodisme d&#8217;avui Ã©s periodisme de dades</a>.Â </em>YaÂ en el artÃ­culo comentÃ© que el humanista, igual que el periodista, deberÃ­a tambiÃ©n adaptarse a los tiempos. Pocas lecturas despuÃ©s, y no pocos enlaces clicados, pude darme cuenta de que ya existÃ­a y eran lasÂ <strong>Humanidades digitales<em>.</em> </strong>Viene a ser un humanista adaptado a los tiempos de las TIC. El tema no es reducido, todo lo contrario, tiene su componente principal en un trabajo interdisciplinar y en la inclusiÃ³n de profesionales de diferentes disciplinas. Un proyecto de humanidades digitales estÃ¡ compuesto, normalmente, por informÃ¡ticos, bibliotecarios, filÃ³logos, y otros, dependiendo del tipo de proyecto. En otro artÃ­culo de mÃ­ bloc intento hacer una descripciÃ³n de un pequeÃ±o proyecto, mÃ¡s bien una <a title=\"Una aplicaciÃ³n de HumanidadesÂ Digitales\" href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/07/16/una-aplicacion-de-humanidades-digitales/\" target=\"_blank\">aplicaciÃ³n</a>, de humanidades digitales. Esta fue la primera ola cogida. El surf se me estaba dando bien este verano.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">DespuÃ©s de haber surfeado una ola uno requiere seguir practicando y el verano estÃ¡ siendo caluroso. Los clics se iban sucediendo, <a title=\"Delicious Wikipedia\" href=\"http://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delicious\" target=\"_blank\">Delicious</a> empezaba a estar cargado con tags de <em><a title=\"Declicious - Digital Humanities\" href=\"http://www.delicious.com/xavcap/digitalhumanities\" target=\"_blank\">digital humanities</a></em>, <a title=\"Delicious - Recursos\" href=\"http://www.delicious.com/xavcap/recursos\" target=\"_blank\">recursos</a>, <a title=\"Delicious - Blocs\" href=\"http://www.delicious.com/xavcap/blogs\" target=\"_blank\">blocs</a>, <a title=\"Delicious - DigitalizaciÃ³n\" href=\"http://www.delicious.com/xavcap/digitalizaciÃ³n\" target=\"_blank\">digitalizaciÃ³n</a>, y algunos mÃ¡s. Y una ola trae otra ola, y las humanidades digitales dejan entrever los <strong>MOOC</strong>, <em>massive open online course</em>, o lo que es lo mismo,Â curso online abierto y masivo<em>.</em>Â Para saber mÃ¡s sobre los MOOC aconsejo la visualizaciÃ³n del siguiente <a title=\"VÃ­deo MOOC\" href=\"http://youtu.be/eW3gMGqcZQc\" target=\"_blank\">vÃ­deo</a>. Me adentro en ellos a partir del seguimiento un curso de <strong><a title=\"MOOC de MOOC`s\" href=\"http://www.moocmooc.com/\" target=\"_blank\">MOOC de MOOCÂ´s</a>. </strong>El<strong>Â </strong>curso me introduce de lleno en las interioridades de un MOOC, mÃ¡xime porquÃ© todos, o la mayorÃ­a de los asistentes, son acadÃ©micos de universidades, principalmente americanas. Uno piensa en un principio que se trata de un curso online, un curso e-learning, pero es eso y mucho mÃ¡s. Tras mi seguimiento del curso me propongo seguir investigando, con el surfeo sistemÃ¡tico de las olas googlelianas. DespuÃ©s de las lecturas de bastantes, muchos, muchÃ­simos artÃ­culos al respecto y de la visualizaciÃ³n de no pocos vÃ­deos; acerca <a title=\"Buenos y malos MOOC&apos;s\" href=\"http://chronicle.com/blogs/brainstorm/good-moocs-bad-moocs/50361\" target=\"_blank\">de los buenos y malos MOOC`s</a>Â o de <a title=\"College Credit without College\" href=\"http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2012/05/07/prior-learning-assessment-catches-quietly\" target=\"_blank\">crÃ©ditos universitarios sin universidades</a>, entre otro muchos, y de leer sobre el sistema universitario americano, encuentro que algunas de las mejores universidades americanas, Harvard o MIT, entre otras se han lanzado a la organizaciÃ³n de MOOC&#8217;s. El <a title=\"Harvard and M.I.T. Team Up to Offer Free Online Courses\" href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/education/harvard-and-mit-team-up-to-offer-free-online-courses.html?_r=1&amp;adxnnl=1&amp;adxnnlx=1345463599-mBZ4Wn5naF2+tLU4SqLjQw\" target=\"_blank\">artÃ­culo</a> que comenta esto no tiene desperdicio y me anima a seguir investigando el asunto. Universidades como Standford, Princeton, Pensilvania o Michigan anuncian tambiÃ©n su participaciÃ³n en proyectos similares y esto me lleva a su proyecto, <a title=\"Coursera Wikipedia \" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coursera\" target=\"_blank\">Coursera</a>. Una web en la que las citadas universidades, y prestigiosos profesores de las mismas, ofrecen MOOC&#8217;s. Mi introducciÃ³n en los MOOC&#8217;s me ha llevado por las lecturas interesantes sobre sistemas de evaluaciÃ³n de MOOC&#8217;s y a descubrir la propuestaÂ <a title=\"Open Education\" href=\"http://openeducation.us/\" target=\"_blank\">educaciÃ³n abierta</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Seguro que me dejo cosas. He descubierto, por ejemplo,Â <strong><a title=\"Storify Wikipedia \" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Storify\" target=\"_blank\">Storify</a></strong>, un interesante recurso que permite describir un proyecto aÃ±adiendo comentarios de otras redes sociales, como por ejemplo mi descubrimiento de las <a title=\"Storify - XavCap\" href=\"http://storify.com/XavCap/humanidades-digitales-agosto-2012\" target=\"_blank\">humanidades digitales</a>Â durante este verano.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Finalmente decido seguir dos cursos MOOC, uno ofrecido por coursera,Â <strong><a title=\"E-Learning and digital cultures\" href=\"https://www.coursera.org/course/edc\" target=\"_blank\">E-learning and Digital Cultures</a>,Â </strong>con un programa Â de la Universidad de Edimburgo y otro, este en espaÃ±ol, despuÃ©s de hacer una bÃºsqueda entre la poca informaciÃ³n que hay al respecto en castellano, de la Universidad de Alicante,<a title=\"IntroducciÃ³n al desarrollo web\" href=\"http://idesweb.es/\" target=\"_blank\">Â </a><strong><a title=\"IntroducciÃ³n al desarrollo web\" href=\"http://idesweb.es/\" target=\"_blank\">iDESWEB: IntroducciÃ³n al desarrollo web</a>.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">AsÃ­ que durante los meses que siguen, el primer curso es de Septiembre a Diciembre, y el segundo de Febrero a Marzo, mis post o artÃ­culos van a hacer referencia a estos cursos y a otros blocs, hashtag twitter, vÃ­deos y, mÃ¡s que probablemente, a otros compaÃ±eros de cursos y los recursos de seguimiento que usen.</p>\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=578&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(32,0,0,'Comer con cuchara grande','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/13/comer-con-cuchara-grande/','EducaciÃ³n;FilosofÃ­a;PolÃ­tica;ReflexiÃ³n',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'ElÂ espÃ­ritu del pensamientoÂ crÃ­ticoÂ tiene que situarse por encima de las capacidades del estudiante cuando este se acerca a la universidad, esa es la requisiciÃ³n, como los requisitos que debe cumplir un proyecto y que son enviados al ingeniero. Es lo que proponen, o lo que piden, la mayorÃ­a de los grados y mÃ¡steres oficiales. Se requiere &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/08/13/comer-con-cuchara-grande/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=534&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449174,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Mon, 13 Aug 2012 09:11:42 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">ElÂ <em>espÃ­ritu del pensamientoÂ crÃ­tico</em>Â tiene que situarse por encima de las capacidades del estudiante cuando este se acerca a la universidad, esa es la requisiciÃ³n, como los requisitos que debe cumplir un proyecto y que son enviados al ingeniero. Es lo que proponen, o lo que piden, la mayorÃ­a de los grados y mÃ¡steres oficiales. Se requiere esa habilidad mÃ­nimamente, estÃ¡ detallada en elÂ <em>perfil de competencias especÃ­ficas y transversales,</em>Â asÃ­<em>Â </em>lo llaman. ElÂ <em>objetivo</em>Â es conseguir que el alumno que se acerca a la gran escuela, esa que se quieren cargar, tengaÂ <em>eso</em>Â con anterioridad y que lo desarrolle en lo posible durante sus estudios, para que, posteriormente, esas habilidades le sirvan para el desarrollo de su vida comoÂ <em>buen ciudadano</em>Â en nuestra sociedad.<em>Â Habilidades de anÃ¡lisis crÃ­ticoÂ </em>en literatura, en ciencia o en filosofÃ­a, con el fin, a lo largo de las asignaturas y de la carrera o mÃ¡ster, de poder entonar su propio discurso, analizar lo que dicen los textos, si es que lo consigue, con la ayuda, guÃ­a y direcciÃ³n de los profesores,Â <em>autÃ©nticos conocedores</em>Â de la materia, a la postre ser mÃ¡s reflexivo, menos crÃ©dulo y estar mejor informado. DespuÃ©s unos con mÃ¡s suerte y otros con menos van encontrando hueco en el mercado laboral. Unos con mucha suerte en el sector para el que se han preparado, otros con menos suerte en otros ambientes, y los mÃ¡s, especialmente en estos momentos, no encuentran nada. No obstante todos, despuÃ©s de estudiar una carrera, la que sea, y de encontrar un trabajo, o no encontrarlo, sea el sector que sea, nos encontramos ante la misma sociedad.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">En mi casa me enseÃ±aron a comer con respeto al resto de comensales, lo mismo que intento hacer con mis hijas. No comas muy rÃ¡pido, no abras mucho la boca, no hagas ruido. En cierta manera eseÂ <em>espÃ­ritu crÃ­tico</em>Â del que hablaba empieza a trabajarse en la mesa, con la familia, con aquellos profesores de infantil o primaria que nos animaban a gritar, o callar, o bailar. EseÂ <em>espÃ­ritu crÃ­tico</em>Â que nos invita a pensar con independencia de lo que nos dicten.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Hoy dÃ­a todos los ciudadanos intentamos entender que estÃ¡ pasando. AquelÂ <em>espÃ­ritu crÃ­tico</em>Â se ha convertido, al final, en una guÃ­a de buenas prÃ¡cticas, en un no hacer daÃ±o al vecino y a tratarlo con respeto, en un comer pausadamente, sin abrir mucho la boca y sin hacer ruido. Y lo mismo pide cada uno de nosotros a nuestros semejantes y compaÃ±eros de esta sociedad que nos ha tocado vivir.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">La situaciÃ³n parece ser contraria cuando uno mira hacia arriba, hacia los dirigentes, sean del color que sean. Uno ve queÂ <em>comen con cucharas grandes,</em><em>Â </em>mascullando y riendo a carcajada entre cucharada y cucharada, abriendo mucho la boca y haciendo mucho ruido, con una falta total de respeto a los demÃ¡s. No aprendieron nada de eseÂ <em>espÃ­ritu crÃ­tico</em>Â que les debÃ­a haber acompaÃ±ado a lo largo de su vida, con su familia, con sus primeros maestros y, los que lo hayan conseguido, con sus profesores en la universidad. Ese <em>espÃ­ritu crÃ­tico</em> que les hubiera hecho mejorar como personas.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Me han enseÃ±ado a comer con cuchara pequeÃ±a, a no llenarme mucho el plato, a no gritar, a respetar, en fin, me han educado para vivir en una sociedad con consideraciÃ³n yÂ cortesÃ­a. En una sociedad que ahora me da la espalda y me demuestra, por mucho que intento pensar lo contrario, que todo esto no sirve para nada. Que nos dirigen con una falta total de deferencia y honradez, sin entendimiento, sin ningÃºn tipo de Ã©tica, unos dirigentes que parecen no aprendieron nada en el transcurso de su vida, sÃ³lo aÂ <em>comer con cuchara grande.</em></p>\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=534&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(33,0,0,'Lo impopular de lo acadÃ©mico','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/07/23/lo-impopular-de-lo-academico/','EducaciÃ³n;Humanidades Digitales;#RedHD;@ernestopriego;@kfitz;Humanismo',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'Aunque no soy un acadÃ©mico, ni siquiera un alumno becado, y mucho menos brillante, sÃ­ que he entonado en alguna ocasiÃ³n aquello deÂ Panem et Circenses, o en su formato mÃ¡s actual, y que tanto Ã©xito ha tenido entre los espaÃ±oles, Pan y FÃºtbol. Y es que, echar la culpa a los demÃ¡s es el deporte &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/07/23/lo-impopular-de-lo-academico/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=472&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449174,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Mon, 23 Jul 2012 15:59:07 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Aunque no soy un acadÃ©mico, ni siquiera un alumno becado, y mucho menos brillante, sÃ­ que he entonado en alguna ocasiÃ³n aquello deÂ <em>Panem et Circenses,</em> o en su formato mÃ¡s actual, y que tanto Ã©xito ha tenido entre los espaÃ±oles, Pan y FÃºtbol. Y es que, echar la culpa a los demÃ¡s es el deporte preferido de las personas. AsÃ­ nos lanzamos los menos preparados, los mÃ¡s, los del medio, y todos, por separado y juntos, a entonar elÂ <em>Panem et Circenses</em>, pero a los demÃ¡s, y con una consecuencia (de ser consecuente) cero. De tal manera que despuÃ©s saltamos todos de alegrÃ­a con el fÃºtbol, con las coches o con las motos; cuando antesÂ seÃ±alÃ¡bamosÂ con el dedo a los demÃ¡s ciudadanos de segunda que seguÃ­an pidiendoÂ <em>Panem et Circenses,Â </em>y es que esto se pedÃ­a, se exigÃ­a, a los gobernantes, para divertirse. Es ahora cuando nos lo dan sin que lo pidamos. Pero esto es otro tema. A lo que iba, seÃ±alamos a los otros, aquellos que piden pan y diversiÃ³n, y Â los tratamos poco menos que deÂ <em>pocoÂ </em><em>listos</em>, cuando continuamos haciendo exactamente lo mismo, sin cambiar nada. Y ahÃ­ estamos todosÂ seÃ±alÃ¡ndonos, los unos a los otros,Â <em>pocoÂ </em><em>listos,</em>Â y saltando juntos por los deportes. AsÃ­ que no nos miramos el ombligo y entramos en un cÃ­rculo del queÂ difÃ­cilmenteÂ salimos. Puesto que el fÃºtbol y la tele, queridos, estÃ¡n ahÃ­, y lo cogen los que quieren, y los que no, pues cogen un libro.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Algo parecido es lo que le pasa a los<strong> intelectuales</strong> y<strong> acadÃ©micos</strong>Â de cualquier disciplina.Â <em>La investigaciÃ³n acadÃ©mica</em>, cito del artÃ­culo,Â <em>es la principal forma deÂ <strong>serialidad impopular</strong></em>.Â Y en mucho menor grado, pero tambiÃ©n, a aquellos licenciados en humanidades o con ciertos intereses intelectuales al respecto, entre los que sÃ­ me incluyo ahora, que no hacemos mÃ¡s que quejarnos de lo mal vistas que estÃ¡n las humanidades, o los intelectuales, o los acadÃ©micos,Â hoy dÃ­a. Y de Â lo poco aceptados que estÃ¡n socialmente. Y de lo incomprendidos que estÃ¡n. Y de lo impopulares que son. Y la culpa, como en el caso del <em>pan y fÃºtbol</em>, es de los demÃ¡s, del pÃºblico que no comprende lo que decimos. En definitiva, y cito,<em> hasta quÃ© grado nos sentimos faltos de popularidad como acadÃ©micos, produciendo apasionadamente un trabajo que nadie parece apreciar</em>. Esto crea un sentimiento de diferencia, de exclusiÃ³n, que ademÃ¡s es bidireccional, puesto que los no acadÃ©micos ni se atreven a acercarse a su trabajo. Â El artÃ­culo que enlazo se cuestiona por los motivos de la poca aceptaciÃ³n de los temas de los que hablan los <strong>acadÃ©micos</strong>, si es que hay un culpable para esto, y propone el reto de hacer el esfuerzo para que esos temas sean seleccionados por el auditorio y, a su vez, que sean interesantes para el mercado y el capital, a la postre, culpables del desaguisado, o quizÃ¡s no, y exige para ellos mismos un esfuerzo por hacerse comprender.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Sugiere un giro por parte de los acadÃ©micos para conseguir esa aceptaciÃ³n, digamos, de masas, guardando para sÃ­, ocultando quizÃ¡s, un reducto donde poder compartir sus interioridades. Propone un cambio, una apertura, para que puedan ser mÃ¡s atractivos, quitando, sobretodo, la culpa al ciudadano que no consume su <em>trabajo.</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Esto mismo se puede aplicar a cualquier disciplina, a la vuestra seguro que tambiÃ©n. Y es que, amigos mÃ­os, que tire la primera piedra el que estÃ© libre de pecado Â¿Somos unos incomprendidos o no nos comprendemos a nosotros mismos?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">El texto que motiva el post es la muy interesante traducciÃ³n de <a title=\"ErnestoPriego\" href=\"https://twitter.com/ernestopriego\" target=\"_blank\">@ernestopriego</a> de &#8220;lo impopular&#8221; de lo acadÃ©mico, &#8220;The Unpopular&#8221; de <a title=\"Kathleen Fitzpatrick\" href=\"https://twitter.com/kfitz\" target=\"_blank\">@kfitz</a> <a title=\"Red HD\" href=\"https://twitter.com//search/%23redhd\" target=\"_blank\">#RedHD</a>. PodÃ©is leer el artÃ­culo completoÂ <a title=\"Lo Impopular\" href=\"http://humanidadesdigitales.net/blog/?p=361\" target=\"_blank\">aquÃ­.</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/\" rel=\"license\"><img src=\"http://i.creativecommons.org/l/by-nc-sa/3.0/88x31.png\" alt=\"Licencia Creative Commons\" /></a><br />\n\"Lo impopular\" porÂ Ernesto PriegoÂ <a title=\"http://humanidadesdigitales.net/blog/?p=361\" href=\"http://humanidadesdigitales.net/blog/?p=361\" rel=\"cc:attributionURL\" target=\"_blank\">es una traducciÃ³n al espaÃ±ol del texto original en inglÃ©s de Kathleen Fitzpatrick</a>. Se comparte bajo una LicenciaÂ <a title=\"CC 3.0\" href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons AtribuciÃ³n-NoComercial-CompartirIgual 3.0 Unported.</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=472&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(34,0,0,'Una aplicaciÃ³n de Humanidades Digitales','text/html','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/07/16/una-aplicacion-de-humanidades-digitales/','Humanidades Digitales;Internet;TIC;@cabralens;@kpeiro;@media140cat;DataJournalism;Ejemplo DH',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'Si bien es cierto que he comentado en el anterior post que el humanista debe convertirse en humanista digital,Â no se nos escapan, como seguramente habÃ©is pensado la mayorÃ­a, dos cuestiones principales. Por un lado Â¿QuÃ© son exactamente las humanidades digitales? y por el otro Â¿CÃ³mo un humanista puede evolucionar hacÃ­a el humanismo digital? Voy a &#8230; <a href=\"http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com/2012/07/16/una-aplicacion-de-humanidades-digitales/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=418&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347449174,NULL,NULL,'FilodeBolsillo','http://filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com','Mon, 16 Jul 2012 18:26:19 +0000',NULL,'FilosofÃ­a de Bolsillo',NULL,'<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Si bien es cierto que he comentado en el anterior post que el humanista debe convertirse en <em>humanista digital,Â </em>no se nos escapan, como seguramente habÃ©is pensado la mayorÃ­a, dos cuestiones principales. Por un lado Â¿QuÃ© son exactamente las humanidades digitales? y por el otro Â¿CÃ³mo un humanista puede evolucionar hacÃ­a el<em> humanismo digital</em>? Voy a intentar aclarar un poco los tÃ©rminos, pero existen discusiones entre los expertos universitarios de los principales centros de investigaciÃ³n de esta materia, y yo no pertenezco a ninguno de ellos. AsÃ­ que lo que voy a sugerir es, con la mejor intenciÃ³n, sÃ³lo una aproximaciÃ³n.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Voy a tratar de responder a la segunda y voy a tratar de hacer una pequeÃ±a prÃ¡ctica con una aplicaciÃ³n donde se vea el resultado. Con el resultado de este ejercicio y su explicaciÃ³n, y tras una pequeÃ±a reflexiÃ³n por vuestra parte, espero que la primera pregunta quede, cuanto menos, parcialmente resuelta. En el post anterior puse un enlace del resultado de un trabajo de investigaciÃ³n realizado por un grupo de trabajo de una Universidad de Canada. El proyecto titulaba <em><a title=\"Cultureplez\" href=\"http://cultureplex.ca/projects/\" target=\"_blank\">Complejidad Cultural y Humanidades digitales</a>, </em>y dentro del mismo podÃ©is encontrar<em><a title=\"Hispanic Baroque\" href=\"http://cultureplex.ca/projects/the-hispanic-baroque/\" target=\"_blank\">Â \"The Hispanic Baroque: Complexity in the first Atlantic culture\"</a></em>, que me sirve muy bien para mostrar que esÂ <em>humanismo digital</em> y quien puede ser elÂ <em>humanista digital.</em>Â El resultado de una investigaciÃ³n sobre datos y su publicaciÃ³n, en este caso en una <em><a title=\"Hispanic Baroque\" href=\"http://www.hispanicbaroque.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">web</a>,Â </em>es el proyecto de humanidades digitales<em>Â y</em>,Â obviamente, todos aquellos que de alguna manera han participado en el proyecto son los <em>humanistas digitales. </em>Â No es mi intenciÃ³n con la inclusiÃ³n de los enlaces mÃ¡s que la de presentar un ejemplo, no tengo absolutamente ninguna relaciÃ³n con ellos, no obstante entiendo que puede ser un poco complicado, por eso he proyectado un pequeÃ±o ejercicio donde poder exponer un resultado mucho mÃ¡s simple como respuesta.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><em></em>Igual que comentaba <a title=\"Mar Cabra\" href=\"https://twitter.com/cabralens\" target=\"_blank\">@cabralens</a>Â que unÂ <em>profesional que recoge y analiza gran cantidad de informaciÃ³n y despuÃ©s la hace comprensible a travÃ©s de artÃ­culos u otras aplicaciones </em>podÃ­a identificarse con un <em>periodista de datos</em>, cualquier profesional que intervenga en un proyecto de <em>humanismo digitalÂ </em>serÃ­a equiparado con un <em>humanista digital.Â </em>Como ya comentÃ©, y como verÃ©is en el ejemplo, un <em>investigadorÂ </em>de este tipo no trabaja nunca sÃ³lo y necesita de expertos en otros campos, tÃ©cnicos informÃ¡ticos, programadores, lingÃ¼istasÂ y otros dependiendo del tipo de proyecto.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Para el ejercicio he tomado una hashtag <a title=\"#datajournalism\" href=\"https://twitter.com//search/%23datajournalism\" target=\"_blank\">#DataJournalism</a> ya que en el aparecen algunos de los protagonistas del primer post como <a title=\"Mar Cabra\" href=\"https://twitter.com/cabralens\" target=\"_blank\">@cabralens</a>,Â Â <a title=\"Media140cat\" href=\"https://twitter.com/media140cat\" target=\"_blank\">@media140cat</a>Â yÂ <a title=\"Karma PeirÃ³\" href=\"https://twitter.com/kpeiro\" target=\"_blank\">@kpeiro</a>Â con su interesante <a title=\"KarmaPeiro Bloc\" href=\"http://karmapeiro.wordpress.com/\" target=\"_blank\">bloc</a>Â sobre <em>periodismo digital</em>. A partir de un API <em>(vista en las Conferencias de Digital Humanities 2012 #dh2012)</em> donde se introduce el hashtag y se activan una serie de filtros se puede obtener una nube de datos con los principales protagonistas de twitter que han usado el hashtag en cuestiÃ³n y su relaciÃ³n, si la hay, entre ellos. Clicando sobre cada uno de los actores tendrÃ©is, automÃ¡ticamente, el resultado de la interacciÃ³n del mismo con el hashtag, si ha escrito tweet, si le han respondido o si tiene una menciÃ³n. En la parte izquierda podÃ©is ver Â tres campos de selecciÃ³n,Â <em>top tweeters, top hashtagsÂ </em>yÂ <em>top conversationalist.Â </em>Donde se pueden ver los usuarios mÃ¡s activos con ese hashtag u otros hashtags usados por usuarios que usan <em>#datajouranlism.</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Clicando sobre el hastagÂ <em><strong><a title=\"AplicaciÃ³n\" href=\"http://hawksey.info/tagsexplorer/?key=0At-B6fTIYNT8dGo3UkRkVnl2bkNhcFYxaUJ2UXo3dGc&amp;sheet=oaw\" target=\"_blank\">#DataJournalism</a></strong></em>Â verÃ©is el resultado de que os hablo. Y si buscÃ¡is podrÃ©is encontrar vuestras entradas (hablo de @cabralens, @kpeiro y @media140cat, por ejemplo).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Esto, claro estÃ¡, es sÃ³lo un ejemplo con el que seguro que os podÃ©is hacer una idea de las muchas aplicaciones que tiene este tipo de proyectos, tanto para <em>periodismo de datos</em> como para <em>humanidades digitales.Â </em>Y, espero, haber clarificado un poco,por lo menos como una ligera idea, lo que son las <em>Humanidades Digitales</em>, aunque seguirÃ© publicando al respecto. Estos datos pueden serÂ incluidosÂ en un estudio conjuntamente con otros. El hashtag puede ser sobre filosofÃ­a o historia y los datos formar parte de un proyecto todavÃ­a mayor, en fin, las aplicaciones se hacen infinitas.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong><em>Nota:</em></strong> El resultado de la nube variarÃ¡ ya que existe una diferencia temporal entre la generaciÃ³n de la misma y la redacciÃ³n del post y su posteo y lectura por parte vuestra. SirvaÂ ÃºnicamenteÂ como ejemplo. En todo caso la nube ha sido generada a las 18 hrs. del 16 de Julio de 2012.</p>\n<br /> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=filosofiadebolsillo.wordpress.com&#038;blog=28508677&#038;post=418&#038;subd=filosofiadebolsillo&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(35,39,0,'edX explores demographics of most persistent MOOC students | Inside Higher Ed','Diigo','http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2012/09/12/edx-explores-demographics-most-persistent-mooc-students',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/mooc&quot;>mooc</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/gsiemens&quot; title=&quot;View gsiemens &apos;s content in group&quot;>gsiemens </a></p>',1347450092,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Wed, 12 Sep 2012 11:25:19 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','39',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(36,19,0,'Learning is business','Diigo','http://www.internettime.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/Learning-is-Business.pdf',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/%22jay+cross%22&quot;>jay cross</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/leadership&quot;>leadership</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/networks&quot;>networks</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/design&quot;>design</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></p>',1347450092,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Tue, 11 Sep 2012 17:12:32 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(37,92,0,'Information R/evolution','Diigo','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4CV05HyAbM',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/%22information+management%22&quot;>information management</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></p>',1347450092,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Tue, 11 Sep 2012 14:03:20 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','92',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(38,20,0,'Tinkering with John Seely Brown','Diigo','http://learnstreaming.com/tinkering-with-john-seely-brown/',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Highlights and Sticky Notes:</strong><p><STRONG>Questing disposition</STRONG></p><p><LI>Gamers: \n<UL>\n<LI>are bottom line oriented</LI>\n<LI>want to be measured because they want to see how much they&apos;re improving</LI>\n<LI>think, If I&apos;m not learning then it&apos;s not fun</LI>\n<LI>keep learning because they embrace change</LI>\n<LI>live for trying something new</LI></UL></LI></p><p><p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/%22john+seely+brown%22&quot;>john seely brown</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/games&quot;>games</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/enchantment&quot;>enchantment</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/networks&quot;>networks</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></p>',1347450092,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Tue, 11 Sep 2012 13:35:10 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','20',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(39,0,0,'RT @gsiemens: #oped12 starts today, welcome newsletter: http://t.co/4L4ejfSK','twitter','http://twitter.com/omiralbell/statuses/245796322442096640',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/omiralbell/statuses/245796322442096640',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/gsiemens\">gsiemens</a>: #<em>oped12</em> starts today, welcome newsletter: <a href=\"http://t.co/4L4ejfSK\">http://t.co/4L4ejfSK</a>',1347450107,NULL,NULL,'omiralbell','http://twitter.com/omiralbell','Wed, 12 Sep 2012 08:09:44 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(40,0,0,'#oped12 started - and so did my comments. Have 2 find out: Is MOOC just  a new buzz word, or is it more than that? http://t.co/H7wMVYa0','twitter','http://twitter.com/sabine_dcu/statuses/245761285977948160',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/sabine_dcu/statuses/245761285977948160',NULL,NULL,29,'#<em>oped12</em> started - and so did my comments. Have 2 find out: Is MOOC just a new buzz word, or is it more than that? <a href=\"http://t.co/H7wMVYa0\">http://t.co/H7wMVYa0</a>',1347450107,NULL,NULL,'sabine_dcu','http://twitter.com/sabine_dcu','Wed, 12 Sep 2012 05:50:31 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(41,0,0,'i will be lurking the #oped12 MOOC','twitter','http://twitter.com/FredWBaker/statuses/245752820916187136',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/FredWBaker/statuses/245752820916187136',NULL,NULL,29,'i will be lurking the #<em>oped12</em> MOOC',1347450107,NULL,NULL,'FredWBaker','http://twitter.com/Fred