ial; outline-width: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-top: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"> Tree-roots&amp;nbsp;<br style=\"outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; outline-width: 0px;\" />(July 1890 - 1890)</h2><h3 style=\"border-bottom-width: 0px; border-color: initial; border-left-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-top-width: 0px; color: black; font-family: Georgia, &apos;New Century Schoolbook&apos;, &apos;Nimbus Roman No9 L&apos;, serif; font-size: 18px; font: inherit; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-top: 0px; outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; outline-width: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-top: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"> Vincent van Gogh</h3><a href=\"http://g.co/artproject/cay2\">http://g.co/artproject/cay2</a><br />At first sight, this painting appears as a jumble of bright colors and wild abstract shapes. Powerful strokes and thickly applied paint mark the canvas. The subject only becomes apparent when you look more closely: tree roots, plants, leaves, with the brown and yellow of a sandy woodland floor under them. Van Gogh painted other scenes of trees and woods. He often cut off his compositions in an unusual fashion, often painting trees without their tops, or a piece of woodland showing only undergrowth and flowers â€“ or, as here, only the roots of the trees.<br /><br /><br /><table cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"tr-caption-container zemanta-img\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VanGogh_Daubigny.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: clear:right;\"><img alt=\"Daubigny&apos;s Garden, July 1890, Auvers, Kunstmus...\" border=\"0\" class=\"zemanta-img-inserted\" height=\"174\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/VanGogh_Daubigny.jpg/300px-VanGogh_Daubigny.jpg\" style=\"border-bottom-style: none; border-color: initial; border-left-style: none; border-right-style: none; border-top-style: none; border-width: initial; font-size: 0.8em;\" width=\"320\" /></a></td></tr><tr><td class=\"tr-caption zemanta-img-attribution\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 300px;\">Daubigny&apos;s Garden, July 1890, Auvers, Kunstmuseum Basel, one of Van Gogh&apos;s final works Pickvance (1986), 272â€“273 (Photo credit: <a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VanGogh_Daubigny.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">Wikipedia</a>)</td></tr></tbody></table><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\"><img alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=5d871266-2899-4942-9091-b1ee2b9aa896\" style=\"border: none; float: right;\" /></a><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7998294428961863698-7218631176219020486?l=notreallyalibrarian-markwashere.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347893886,NULL,NULL,'markwashere','http://www.blogger.com/profile/16895029067006588081','2012-06-24T17:10:00.000+10:00',NULL,'something found or shared',NULL,'Just love this Van Gogh one of his lesser known works.<br /><br /><br /><h2 style=\"border-bottom-width: 0px; border-color: initial; border-left-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-top-width: 0px; color: black; font-family: Georgia, &apos;New Century Schoolbook&apos;, &apos;Nimbus Roman No9 L&apos;, serif; font-size: 26px; font: inherit; line-height: 30px; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-top: 0px; outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; outline-width: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-top: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"> Tree-roots&amp;nbsp;<br style=\"outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; outline-width: 0px;\" />(July 1890 - 1890)</h2><h3 style=\"border-bottom-width: 0px; border-color: initial; border-left-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-top-width: 0px; color: black; font-family: Georgia, &apos;New Century Schoolbook&apos;, &apos;Nimbus Roman No9 L&apos;, serif; font-size: 18px; font: inherit; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-top: 0px; outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; outline-width: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-top: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"> Vincent van Gogh</h3><a href=\"http://g.co/artproject/cay2\">http://g.co/artproject/cay2</a><br />At first sight, this painting appears as a jumble of bright colors and wild abstract shapes. Powerful strokes and thickly applied paint mark the canvas. The subject only becomes apparent when you look more closely: tree roots, plants, leaves, with the brown and yellow of a sandy woodland floor under them. Van Gogh painted other scenes of trees and woods. He often cut off his compositions in an unusual fashion, often painting trees without their tops, or a piece of woodland showing only undergrowth and flowers â€“ or, as here, only the roots of the trees.<br /><br /><br /><table cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"tr-caption-container zemanta-img\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VanGogh_Daubigny.jpg\" imageanchor=\"1\" style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: clear:right;\"><img alt=\"Daubigny&apos;s Garden, July 1890, Auvers, Kunstmus...\" border=\"0\" class=\"zemanta-img-inserted\" height=\"174\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/VanGogh_Daubigny.jpg/300px-VanGogh_Daubigny.jpg\" sty