collaborators. Can we resolve the paradox of a staggering global teacher shortage and unemployment? We need more teachers, not fewer.&nbsp; If our drop out rate is 50% we are at the tipping point. Just the market forces alone would legitimize an alternative that can include those who have given up.&nbsp; Maybe it is just like electricity. All the waste to get to the end--a systemic problem with monolithic networks. It is worse in electricity, sometimes 90% line loss!!&nbsp; Our schools mimic this in many ways. The web 2 transition to a losely connected network of whole systems makes much more sense. Local, glocal, hyperlocal solutions to waste, energy, food, education. We can leverage the affordances of broadband to break out of the dominant paradigm and save a lot of money doing it. I have to think about this.&nbsp; Teachers would have hybrid responsiblitlies as well, fluid, flexible, allowing for Professional Development.&nbsp; For example, there are opportunities to create on-line versions of their successes, for which a market exists based on use, that extends their earning power into the global economy.&nbsp; This is a vision of lateral wealth creation and meritocracy, bringing the best to the top. Would we need fleets of buses to simultaneously transport students? Once and a while, for special events. Facility use would be spread out accomodating different populations of learners and projects.</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile6.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-19/JJGsnlkgzcCCetHsioDsoCkpHbbbyljzBwckqdlxFdwncfByfkquwJrGcFsl/Nancy_on_the_Board.JPG.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Nancy_on_the_board\" height=\"375\" src=\"http://getfile5.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-19/JJGsnlkgzcCCetHsioDsoCkpHbbbyljzBwckqdlxFdwncfByfkquwJrGcFsl/Nancy_on_the_Board.JPG.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> <em>Nancy actualizing a design at the board</em></p>\n<p>It is very strange to see schools closing!&nbsp; Is there an opportunity? Those edifices of conformity--Let the students redesign the archaic educational buildings into<a href=\"http://www.oceanarks.org/Education.php\" title=\"living machines\" target=\"_blank\"> living green machines</a>. Consider the facility if it could become a hybrid of teaching, creativity, learning, business and science. There is no reason that these redesigned facilities would not only be carbon neutral, but could easily produce food for the community--not only lunch as the <a href=\"http://www.ecoliteracy.org/\" title=\"ecoliteracy.org\" target=\"_blank\">Center for Ecoliteracy</a> suggests. The ecosystems of the sustainable community are the curriculum. This is the doorway to all the interdisciplines, a place for passion driven learning to propogate and bear fruit.&nbsp; Let the geeks geek and the thesbians act. Empowering the students this way would be a step in applying <a href=\"http://bfi.org/\" title=\"Buckminster Fuller Org\" target=\"_blank\">Buckminister Fuller&apos;s</a> idea of Design Science. Beginning with design, allowing students to create their own learning environment; accustom them to solving problems using desing and allow them to effect real change in their environment --so they can see the consequences of their decisions.</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile2.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-19/mkaqcBdAEBsuvupqIzCExrunubjszaurGBeCFdAFdvDnxwfldpqhFfoBrnhm/Our_Red_Fox.JPG.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Our_red_fox\" height=\"375\" src=\"http://getfile0.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-19/mkaqcBdAEBsuvupqIzCExrunubjszaurGBeCFdAFdvDnxwfldpqhFfoBrnhm/Our_Red_Fox.JPG.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> <em>Vermont Red Fox, Lamoilllev</em>t</p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/time-and-money-considerations-in-21st-century\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/time-and-money-considerations-in-21st-century#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(343,0,0,'How Would Universal Broadband change the culture of Vermont? Micro Grids and Media','text/html','http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/how-would-universal-broadband-change-the-cult',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,42,'\n    <p>\n	<p>Its a big question. I am challenging myself to envision the world with 100 gigabytes download speed, here in every house in Vermont.&nbsp; I see some big changes possible with education, which I started to get at in my last post.&nbsp; The excitement is that with unfettered access to the internet the world&apos;s on line repositories of knolwedge and the global brain are there to help you learn anything you want. Anything. Anytime. For example, a network of micro grids makes much more sense than a mega grid for our electricity generation, distribution and uses.&nbsp; The technology and resources are there to create your own micro grid and be liberated from the constraints of the power companies. In many cases this is possible. I envision the smart grid as the web 2.0 of electricity. In other words, that user generated power is the future.&nbsp; The cost of the power lost in transmission along monolithic networks are precisely the savings we can leverage to decentralize our grid.&nbsp; This democratization of power is part of the paradigm shift accompanying the transition to the digital age, and a component of what it means to have ubiquitous broadband here, or anywhere for that matter.</p>\n<p>But think about simple day to day commerce. Instead of each household going out to buy individual items, things are ordered all on line and a delivery service stops by as needed.&nbsp; This makes much more sense than endless trips to the store; instead, fleets of energy efficient delivery vehicles routed through a GPS system would be making their rounds.&nbsp; More people would be working from home, perhaps tending gardens or creating other localized enterprises, perhaps participating in their children&apos;s education.&nbsp; Travelling would be special, not a commute. This reduces emissions and wear and tear on the roads.</p>\n<p>I see a dynamic between a hyperlocal intensification of&nbsp; the value and understanding of location and a global connectedness that is always learning, being exposed to diversity and new ideas. The content that we create as we live our lives in our specific location is like the water beneath our feet and flowing around us. Our content is, like our water, our most precious resource. Is it being bottled and sold? Our media is as vulnerable.&nbsp; Equally our participation in the emerging global web is what defines and adds value to our unique content. That dialogue with the global village is an important part of what rejuvinates our ability to be creative and innovate.</p>\n<p>I would love to hear how you envision what effects broadband to every household in Vermont would have.\n<a href=\"http://getfile0.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-17/qdgesamFdGjniqyeduttjDeCwuGjjIqmowIxiiBqBrJpDrmEviwdEAbtmewo/DSCF8331.JPG.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dscf8331\" height=\"375\" src=\"http://getfile4.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-17/qdgesamFdGjniqyeduttjDeCwuGjjIqmowIxiiBqBrJpDrmEviwdEAbtmewo/DSCF8331.JPG.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://getfile5.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-17/dzxiJobzhbnkrnHDqFGBAvlAtEfGtlotqmitkCDHxpooCxbIdDmuHuqIBqhu/DSCF8332.JPG.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dscf8332\" height=\"375\" src=\"http://getfile8.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-17/dzxiJobzhbnkrnHDqFGBAvlAtEfGtlotqmitkCDHxpooCxbIdDmuHuqIBqhu/DSCF8332.JPG.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/how-would-universal-broadband-change-the-cult\">See the full gallery on Posterous</a> The <a href=\"http://riotofreasons.blogspot.com/2005/10/million-dollar-toilet.html\" title=\"Vietnam\" target=\"_blank\">Vietnam Veterans Memorial Rest Stop Living Machine</a> on <a href=\"http://maps.google.com/maps?q=veitnam+veterans+restop+vermont&amp;oe=utf-8&amp;rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&amp;client=firefox-a&amp;um=1&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;sa=N&amp;hl=en&amp;tab=wl\" title=\"Northfield\" target=\"_blank\">Route I-89, Northfield, Vermont</a></p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/how-would-universal-broadband-change-the-cult\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/how-would-universal-broadband-change-the-cult#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',1347894499,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Thu, 17 Feb 2011 20:44:10 -0800',NULL,'Jan&apos;s posterous',NULL,'\n    <p>\n	<p>Its a big question. I am challenging myself to envision the world with 100 gigabytes download speed, here in every house in Vermont.&nbsp; I see some big changes possible with education, which I started to get at in my last post.&nbsp; The excitement is that with unfettered access to the internet the world&apos;s on line repositories of knolwedge and the global brain are there to help you learn anything you want. Anything. Anytime. For example, a network of micro grids makes much more sense than a mega grid for our electricity generation, distribution and uses.&nbsp; The technology and resources are there to create your own micro grid and be liberated from the constraints of the power companies. In many cases this is possible. I envision the smart grid as the web 2.0 of electricity. In other words, that user generated power is the future.&nbsp; The cost of the power lost in transmission along monolithic networks are precisely the savings we can leverage to decentralize our grid.&nbsp; This democratization of power is part of the paradigm shift accompanying the transition to the digital age, and a component of what it means to have ubiquitous broadband here, or anywhere for that matter.</p>\n<p>But think about simple day to day commerce. Instead of each household going out to buy individual items, things are ordered all on line and a delivery service stops by as needed.&nbsp; This makes much more sense than endless trips to the store; instead, fleets of energy efficient delivery vehicles routed through a GPS system would be making their rounds.&nbsp; More people would be working from home, perhaps tending gardens or creating other localized enterprises, perhaps participating in their children&apos;s education.&nbsp; Travelling would be special, not a commute. This reduces emissions and wear and tear on the roads.</p>\n<p>I see a dynamic between a hyperlocal intensification of&nbsp; the value and understanding of location and a global connectedness that is always learning, being exposed to diversity and new ideas. The content that we create as we live our lives in our specific location is like the water beneath our feet and flowing around us. Our content is, like our water, our most precious resource. Is it being bottled and sold? Our media is as vulnerable.&nbsp; Equally our participation in the emerging global web is what defines and adds value to our unique content. That dialogue with the global village is an important part of what rejuvinates our ability to be creative and innovate.</p>\n<p>I would love to hear how you envision what effects broadband to every household in Vermont would have.\n<a href=\"http://getfile0.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-17/qdgesamFdGjniqyeduttjDeCwuGjjIqmowIxiiBqBrJpDrmEviwdEAbtmewo/DSCF8331.JPG.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dscf8331\" height=\"375\" src=\"http://getfile4.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-17/qdgesamFdGjniqyeduttjDeCwuGjjIqmowIxiiBqBrJpDrmEviwdEAbtmewo/DSCF8331.JPG.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://getfile5.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-17/dzxiJobzhbnkrnHDqFGBAvlAtEfGtlotqmitkCDHxpooCxbIdDmuHuqIBqhu/DSCF8332.JPG.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dscf8332\" height=\"375\" src=\"http://getfile8.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-17/dzxiJobzhbnkrnHDqFGBAvlAtEfGtlotqmitkCDHxpooCxbIdDmuHuqIBqhu/DSCF8332.JPG.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/how-would-universal-broadband-change-the-cult\">See the full gallery on Posterous</a> The <a href=\"http://riotofreasons.blogspot.com/2005/10/million-dollar-toilet.html\" title=\"Vietnam\" target=\"_blank\">Vietnam Veterans Memorial Rest Stop Living Machine</a> on <a href=\"http://maps.google.com/maps?q=veitnam+veterans+restop+vermont&amp;oe=utf-8&amp;rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&amp;client=firefox-a&amp;um=1&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;sa=N&amp;hl=en&amp;tab=wl\" title=\"Northfield\" target=\"_blank\">Route I-89, Northfield, Vermont</a></p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/how-would-universal-broadband-change-the-cult\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/how-would-universal-broadband-change-the-cult#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(344,0,0,'What would ubiquitous broadband look like in rural Vermont?','text/html','http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/what-would-ubiquitous-broadband-look-like-in',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,42,'\n    <p>\n	<p>The tsunami of connectedness is reaching many rural areas of the world.</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile9.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/JxcvmBfuxphntjuwJDlEoixmJcIdobBsJhewbHgbptwkuAwEeaiejzJnskuy/Villa_Altagarcia_Telecenter_Dominican_Republic_2009.jpg.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Villa_altagarcia_telecenter_dominican_republic_2009\" height=\"387\" src=\"http://getfile7.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/JxcvmBfuxphntjuwJDlEoixmJcIdobBsJhewbHgbptwkuAwEeaiejzJnskuy/Villa_Altagarcia_Telecenter_Dominican_Republic_2009.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> a Community Technology Center in the Dominican Republic at Villa Altagarcia</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.telecentre.org/\" title=\"telecenter\" target=\"_blank\">telecenter,</a> and inceasingly, <a href=\"http://txteagle.com/\" title=\"mobile apps\" target=\"_blank\">mobile apps</a>, are giving voices, income and information to the millions who have been muted by the hegemony of power or circumstance. Our society is shuddering from the transition of a fossil fuel based economy to a knowledge or wisdom based economy. Increasingly connectedness is described as a <a href=\"http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Global-News/2010/0309/Is-Internet-access-a-human-right-Top-10-nations-that-say-yes\" title=\"human right\" target=\"_blank\">human right</a>.&nbsp; or see Timothy Karr&apos;s post: <a href=\"http://mediacitizen.blogspot.com/\" title=\"Freedom to Connect\" target=\"_blank\">Is the &apos;Freedom to Connect&apos; a Right?</a> This includes calls for <a href=\"http://www.workerscenter.org/\" title=\"Healthcare as a Human Right\" target=\"_blank\">Healthcare as a Human Right</a>.&nbsp; (Why? as information is shared the monopoly of the health care system is weakened, comparable and alternatives emerge that do not involve drugs)&nbsp; But, if you build it--ubiquitous broadband--will they come? Oh yeah they will.&nbsp; Will they stay? Maybe. How does it change a rural community? What remains? What evolves? What is lost or gained?</p>\n<p>\n<img alt=\"Fox_leap_\" height=\"412\" src=\"http://getfile3.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/yFBeyfHggubyexEgcFmCtxclAdCdcqFIqfkbiAphIkmusaDbstEutaCnrecr/Fox_Leap_.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"393\" /> </p>\n<p>Red fox mousing, Lamoillevt</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Vermont was one of the last states to receive the Interstate system. Farming with horses was still common in the 50&apos;s in the Green Mountain State. What was it like when electricity first came to town?&nbsp; Are there parallels to the impact of broadband? No, this is something of a magnitude different from these events.&nbsp; When I look at the school drop out rate--hovering around 50%--I can&apos;t help but wonder that broadband has the potential to disrupt our institutional structures in unforseeable ways. Would, for example, a student centric learning environment reverse drop out trends? Or offer something unique when the \"plug and play\" generation thinks about where to live? I try and imagine.</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile6.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/qcdJutIjtteuuaCoyopaHjpjiJBowFeEuqdhIAJehormIhHfwkagyCtcmqbt/CTCgridGFS_003.jpg.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Ctcgridgfs_003\" height=\"274\" src=\"http://getfile0.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/qcdJutIjtteuuaCoyopaHjpjiJBowFeEuqdhIAJehormIhHfwkagyCtcmqbt/CTCgridGFS_003.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> </p>\n<p>Green re design of the <a href=\"http://wikimapia.org/#lat=30.2068611&amp;lon=77.5991821&amp;z=9&amp;l=0&amp;m=b&amp;show=/1504445/Dehradun\" title=\"Green Feild School\" target=\"_blank\">Green Feild School in Dehadrun</a>, India using <a href=\"http://reactiongrid.com/\" title=\"ReactionGrid\" target=\"_blank\">ReactionGrid</a></p>\n<p>What would a re visioned school look like in rural Vermont if broadband was ubiquitous?&nbsp; Each student had a notebook or iPad and the school was a wireless hub for the local network, and each home had 10 Gigs for download speed? What would You do? There is no constraint on time, as lessons are delivered in a hybrid or blended way, scyncronous and asyncronous, face to face and virtually. The teachers role was also..dispersed. And the curriculum is sustainability-<a href=\"http://www.ecoliteracy.org/\" title=\"ecoliteracy\" target=\"_blank\">ecoliteracy</a>, to which all the other 21st Century literacy&apos;s connect. Cohorts of students grouped by interest, ability and passion--not age, meet 3 or 4 times a week, face to face at the school, or maybe daily in some cases, but return to their team projects and engagement in experiential learning; tending gardens, excavating archeological sites, making a film, installing algae bio reactors simialr to the ones at school, imagine. What happens to the need to transport students? Its reduced. What happens to large buildings that need to accomodate everyone simultaneously? The facility is re visioned as well; its footprint reflecting ecodesign, sustainability, labs, state of the art technology, presentation and performance space, seminar rooms, kitchens, gardens, <a href=\"http://www.oceanarks.org/Education.php\" title=\"living machines\" target=\"_blank\">living machines</a>. The school could produce extra energy and food. The curriculum is the sustainable community and the systems that support it. The school becomes a microcosm of the home. <a href=\"http://earthship.com/\" title=\"Earthship\" target=\"_blank\">Earthship</a>, Earthschool:</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile4.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/dyeElpmjlnadiGaFeDHzxDgxEEJDeagrHDhioAInfpvBcpxgtvilmnjvAFbx/Earth_Ship_Haiti.jpg.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Earth_ship_haiti\" height=\"263\" src=\"http://getfile3.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/dyeElpmjlnadiGaFeDHzxDgxEEJDeagrHDhioAInfpvBcpxgtvilmnjvAFbx/Earth_Ship_Haiti.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> </p>\n<p>the awesome huricane resistant Earthship made from recycled materials</p>\n<p>Many more parents would be working from home, telecommuting instead of burning fossil fuels, available for their children. Teaching is going through a similar transformation. The apprenticeship model would be able to permeate every level as students appentice to teach as well. With incentives and encouragement teachers (and students) would be engaged with a global--not just hyperlocal--student body.&nbsp; This too would lead to economic opportunites supporting excellence locally, with the cost spread out to the marketplace of the internet. Why should a good teacher be limited to one town, one age group? Those with the capacity and inclination could address the huge teacher shortage the world is facing. If the financial model was more spread out it would take some pressure off the tax rate, with further incentives to support apprentices and interns.</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile1.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/brqkAafntuoxswkfoncDqcionwyAjIzAlpxEznEJiGBjqyxoIJbfnDdmceax/SL_Earthship1.jpg.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Sl_earthship1\" height=\"319\" src=\"http://getfile7.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/brqkAafntuoxswkfoncDqcionwyAjIzAlpxEznEJiGBjqyxoIJbfnDdmceax/SL_Earthship1.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> </p>\n<p>designing virtually in <a href=\"http://secondlife.com/\" title=\"Second Life\" target=\"_blank\">Second Life</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/what-would-ubiquitous-broadband-look-like-in\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/what-would-ubiquitous-broadband-look-like-in#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',1347894500,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Sun, 13 Feb 2011 12:49:00 -0800',NULL,'Jan&apos;s posterous',NULL,'\n    <p>\n	<p>The tsunami of connectedness is reaching many rural areas of the world.</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile9.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/JxcvmBfuxphntjuwJDlEoixmJcIdobBsJhewbHgbptwkuAwEeaiejzJnskuy/Villa_Altagarcia_Telecenter_Dominican_Republic_2009.jpg.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Villa_altagarcia_telecenter_dominican_republic_2009\" height=\"387\" src=\"http://getfile7.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/JxcvmBfuxphntjuwJDlEoixmJcIdobBsJhewbHgbptwkuAwEeaiejzJnskuy/Villa_Altagarcia_Telecenter_Dominican_Republic_2009.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> a Community Technology Center in the Dominican Republic at Villa Altagarcia</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.telecentre.org/\" title=\"telecenter\" target=\"_blank\">telecenter,</a> and inceasingly, <a href=\"http://txteagle.com/\" title=\"mobile apps\" target=\"_blank\">mobile apps</a>, are giving voices, income and information to the millions who have been muted by the hegemony of power or circumstance. Our society is shuddering from the transition of a fossil fuel based economy to a knowledge or wisdom based economy. Increasingly connectedness is described as a <a href=\"http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Global-News/2010/0309/Is-Internet-access-a-human-right-Top-10-nations-that-say-yes\" title=\"human right\" target=\"_blank\">human right</a>.&nbsp; or see Timothy Karr&apos;s post: <a href=\"http://mediacitizen.blogspot.com/\" title=\"Freedom to Connect\" target=\"_blank\">Is the &apos;Freedom to Connect&apos; a Right?</a> This includes calls for <a href=\"http://www.workerscenter.org/\" title=\"Healthcare as a Human Right\" target=\"_blank\">Healthcare as a Human Right</a>.&nbsp; (Why? as information is shared the monopoly of the health care system is weakened, comparable and alternatives emerge that do not involve drugs)&nbsp; But, if you build it--ubiquitous broadband--will they come? Oh yeah they will.&nbsp; Will they stay? Maybe. How does it change a rural community? What remains? What evolves? What is lost or gained?</p>\n<p>\n<img alt=\"Fox_leap_\" height=\"412\" src=\"http://getfile3.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/yFBeyfHggubyexEgcFmCtxclAdCdcqFIqfkbiAphIkmusaDbstEutaCnrecr/Fox_Leap_.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"393\" /> </p>\n<p>Red fox mousing, Lamoillevt</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Vermont was one of the last states to receive the Interstate system. Farming with horses was still common in the 50&apos;s in the Green Mountain State. What was it like when electricity first came to town?&nbsp; Are there parallels to the impact of broadband? No, this is something of a magnitude different from these events.&nbsp; When I look at the school drop out rate--hovering around 50%--I can&apos;t help but wonder that broadband has the potential to disrupt our institutional structures in unforseeable ways. Would, for example, a student centric learning environment reverse drop out trends? Or offer something unique when the \"plug and play\" generation thinks about where to live? I try and imagine.</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile6.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/qcdJutIjtteuuaCoyopaHjpjiJBowFeEuqdhIAJehormIhHfwkagyCtcmqbt/CTCgridGFS_003.jpg.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Ctcgridgfs_003\" height=\"274\" src=\"http://getfile0.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/qcdJutIjtteuuaCoyopaHjpjiJBowFeEuqdhIAJehormIhHfwkagyCtcmqbt/CTCgridGFS_003.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> </p>\n<p>Green re design of the <a href=\"http://wikimapia.org/#lat=30.2068611&amp;lon=77.5991821&amp;z=9&amp;l=0&amp;m=b&amp;show=/1504445/Dehradun\" title=\"Green Feild School\" target=\"_blank\">Green Feild School in Dehadrun</a>, India using <a href=\"http://reactiongrid.com/\" title=\"ReactionGrid\" target=\"_blank\">ReactionGrid</a></p>\n<p>What would a re visioned school look like in rural Vermont if broadband was ubiquitous?&nbsp; Each student had a notebook or iPad and the school was a wireless hub for the local network, and each home had 10 Gigs for download speed? What would You do? There is no constraint on time, as lessons are delivered in a hybrid or blended way, scyncronous and asyncronous, face to face and virtually. The teachers role was also..dispersed. And the curriculum is sustainability-<a href=\"http://www.ecoliteracy.org/\" title=\"ecoliteracy\" target=\"_blank\">ecoliteracy</a>, to which all the other 21st Century literacy&apos;s connect. Cohorts of students grouped by interest, ability and passion--not age, meet 3 or 4 times a week, face to face at the school, or maybe daily in some cases, but return to their team projects and engagement in experiential learning; tending gardens, excavating archeological sites, making a film, installing algae bio reactors simialr to the ones at school, imagine. What happens to the need to transport students? Its reduced. What happens to large buildings that need to accomodate everyone simultaneously? The facility is re visioned as well; its footprint reflecting ecodesign, sustainability, labs, state of the art technology, presentation and performance space, seminar rooms, kitchens, gardens, <a href=\"http://www.oceanarks.org/Education.php\" title=\"living machines\" target=\"_blank\">living machines</a>. The school could produce extra energy and food. The curriculum is the sustainable community and the systems that support it. The school becomes a microcosm of the home. <a href=\"http://earthship.com/\" title=\"Earthship\" target=\"_blank\">Earthship</a>, Earthschool:</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile4.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/dyeElpmjlnadiGaFeDHzxDgxEEJDeagrHDhioAInfpvBcpxgtvilmnjvAFbx/Earth_Ship_Haiti.jpg.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Earth_ship_haiti\" height=\"263\" src=\"http://getfile3.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/dyeElpmjlnadiGaFeDHzxDgxEEJDeagrHDhioAInfpvBcpxgtvilmnjvAFbx/Earth_Ship_Haiti.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> </p>\n<p>the awesome huricane resistant Earthship made from recycled materials</p>\n<p>Many more parents would be working from home, telecommuting instead of burning fossil fuels, available for their children. Teaching is going through a similar transformation. The apprenticeship model would be able to permeate every level as students appentice to teach as well. With incentives and encouragement teachers (and students) would be engaged with a global--not just hyperlocal--student body.&nbsp; This too would lead to economic opportunites supporting excellence locally, with the cost spread out to the marketplace of the internet. Why should a good teacher be limited to one town, one age group? Those with the capacity and inclination could address the huge teacher shortage the world is facing. If the financial model was more spread out it would take some pressure off the tax rate, with further incentives to support apprentices and interns.</p>\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile1.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/brqkAafntuoxswkfoncDqcionwyAjIzAlpxEznEJiGBjqyxoIJbfnDdmceax/SL_Earthship1.jpg.scaled1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Sl_earthship1\" height=\"319\" src=\"http://getfile7.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-02-13/brqkAafntuoxswkfoncDqcionwyAjIzAlpxEznEJiGBjqyxoIJbfnDdmceax/SL_Earthship1.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a> </p>\n<p>designing virtually in <a href=\"http://secondlife.com/\" title=\"Second Life\" target=\"_blank\">Second Life</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/what-would-ubiquitous-broadband-look-like-in\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/what-would-ubiquitous-broadband-look-like-in#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO `link` VALUES (345,0,0,'Social media imitates collective intelligent behavior','text/html','http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/social-media-imitates-collective-intelligent',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,42,'\n    <p>\n	<p>It would be cool to see the economic numbers behind this data--but I found this very interesting. What does it have to do with education?&nbsp; if you think about the voices of the unvoiced--this is just the beginning.&nbsp; Contribute, share, and things will open. Empower your students, give them a voice. This activity mimics the brain. Synthesis is synopsis, syntax. Only by expressing and connecting does the node become existent--created. The rapid and exponential growth we will experience in the next \"era\" (which could be as short as a few years)--will be fueled by the BoP generally. Conceived as emergent evolution or steps towards the <a href=\"http://www.singularity.com/charts/page17.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">singularity</a>.</p>\n<p>\n<img alt=\"F04-monks16\" height=\"300\" src=\"http://getfile0.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-01-15/rlsqimvJEdJcAcdlphDhkmBfbhJDqGyFnfFFEEDxyIHGCwyEkCmrcbIpvufa/F04-Monks16.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"400\" /> Tibetan Sand Mandala from monks of the <a href=\"http://www.drepung.org/\" title=\"drepung.org\" target=\"_blank\">Drepung Loseling Monastary</a>,&nbsp; during their visit to Johnson, Vermont 2003<strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Collected from <a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/blog/tabid/6307/bid/8471/11-Social-Web-Facts-that-Will-Blow-Your-Mind.aspx#ixzz1B79YLyTh\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Hubspot.com</a></p>\n<p><strong>1.</strong> In 2010, <strong>107 trillion emails</strong> were sent on the Internet. (<a href=\"http://www.radicati.com/?p=5290\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>2.</strong> At the current rate <strong>36 billion photos</strong> will be uploaded to Facebook each year. (<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/press/info.php?statistics\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>3.</strong> Each day <strong>2 billion videos</strong> are watched on YouTube. (<a href=\"http://youtube-global.blogspot.com/2010/11/great-scott-over-35-hours-of-video.html\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>4.</strong> Each month <strong>30 billion pieces of content</strong> (links, notes, photos, etc.) are shared on Facebook. (<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/press/info.php?statistics\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>5.</strong> In 2010, users sent <strong>25 billion tweets</strong>. (<a href=\"http://blog.twitter.com/2010/12/stocking-stuffer.html\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>6.</strong> Worldwide there are <strong>1.97 billion Internet users</strong>. (<a href=\"http://internetworldstats.com/stats.htm\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>7.</strong> At the end of 2010, there were <strong>88.8 million &ndash; .COM domain names</strong> registered. (<a href=\"http://verisigninc.com/en_US/why-verisign/research-trends/domain-name-industry-brief/index.xhtml\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>8.</strong> As of December 2010, there were <strong>255 million websites</strong>. (<a href=\"http://news.netcraft.com/archives/2010/12/01/december-2010-web-server-survey.html\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>9.</strong> Worldwide, there are <strong>2.9 billion email accounts</strong>. (<a href=\"http://www.radicati.com/?p=5290\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_self\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>10.</strong> The average Internet user watched <strong>186 online videos</strong> per month (USA). (<a href=\"http://www.comscore.com/Press_Events/Press_Releases/2010/12/comScore_Releases_November_2010_U.S._Online_Video_Rankings\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>11.</strong> Every minute <strong>35 hours of video</strong> is uploaded to YouTube. (<a href=\"http://youtube-global.blogspot.com/2010/11/great-scott-over-35-hours-of-video.html\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/social-media-imitates-collective-intelligent\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/social-media-imitates-collective-intelligent#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',1347894503,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Sat, 15 Jan 2011 08:37:00 -0800',NULL,'Jan&apos;s posterous',NULL,'\n    <p>\n	<p>It would be cool to see the economic numbers behind this data--but I found this very interesting. What does it have to do with education?&nbsp; if you think about the voices of the unvoiced--this is just the beginning.&nbsp; Contribute, share, and things will open. Empower your students, give them a voice. This activity mimics the brain. Synthesis is synopsis, syntax. Only by expressing and connecting does the node become existent--created. The rapid and exponential growth we will experience in the next \"era\" (which could be as short as a few years)--will be fueled by the BoP generally. Conceived as emergent evolution or steps towards the <a href=\"http://www.singularity.com/charts/page17.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">singularity</a>.</p>\n<p>\n<img alt=\"F04-monks16\" height=\"300\" src=\"http://getfile0.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/temp-2011-01-15/rlsqimvJEdJcAcdlphDhkmBfbhJDqGyFnfFFEEDxyIHGCwyEkCmrcbIpvufa/F04-Monks16.jpg.scaled500.jpg\" width=\"400\" /> Tibetan Sand Mandala from monks of the <a href=\"http://www.drepung.org/\" title=\"drepung.org\" target=\"_blank\">Drepung Loseling Monastary</a>,&nbsp; during their visit to Johnson, Vermont 2003<strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Collected from <a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/blog/tabid/6307/bid/8471/11-Social-Web-Facts-that-Will-Blow-Your-Mind.aspx#ixzz1B79YLyTh\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Hubspot.com</a></p>\n<p><strong>1.</strong> In 2010, <strong>107 trillion emails</strong> were sent on the Internet. (<a href=\"http://www.radicati.com/?p=5290\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>2.</strong> At the current rate <strong>36 billion photos</strong> will be uploaded to Facebook each year. (<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/press/info.php?statistics\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>3.</strong> Each day <strong>2 billion videos</strong> are watched on YouTube. (<a href=\"http://youtube-global.blogspot.com/2010/11/great-scott-over-35-hours-of-video.html\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>4.</strong> Each month <strong>30 billion pieces of content</strong> (links, notes, photos, etc.) are shared on Facebook. (<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/press/info.php?statistics\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>5.</strong> In 2010, users sent <strong>25 billion tweets</strong>. (<a href=\"http://blog.twitter.com/2010/12/stocking-stuffer.html\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>6.</strong> Worldwide there are <strong>1.97 billion Internet users</strong>. (<a href=\"http://internetworldstats.com/stats.htm\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>7.</strong> At the end of 2010, there were <strong>88.8 million &ndash; .COM domain names</strong> registered. (<a href=\"http://verisigninc.com/en_US/why-verisign/research-trends/domain-name-industry-brief/index.xhtml\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>8.</strong> As of December 2010, there were <strong>255 million websites</strong>. (<a href=\"http://news.netcraft.com/archives/2010/12/01/december-2010-web-server-survey.html\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>9.</strong> Worldwide, there are <strong>2.9 billion email accounts</strong>. (<a href=\"http://www.radicati.com/?p=5290\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_self\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>10.</strong> The average Internet user watched <strong>186 online videos</strong> per month (USA). (<a href=\"http://www.comscore.com/Press_Events/Press_Releases/2010/12/comScore_Releases_November_2010_U.S._Online_Video_Rankings\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>11.</strong> Every minute <strong>35 hours of video</strong> is uploaded to YouTube. (<a href=\"http://youtube-global.blogspot.com/2010/11/great-scott-over-35-hours-of-video.html\" title=\"Source\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/social-media-imitates-collective-intelligent\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/social-media-imitates-collective-intelligent#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(346,0,0,'Using Machinima for Proposal Creation','text/html','http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/using-machinima-for-proposal-creation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,42,'\n    <p>\n	<p>\n<a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/using-machinima-for-proposal-creation\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://posterous.com/images/filetypes/ppt.png\" /></a> <strong>Using Machinima for Proposal Creation.ppt</strong>\n<a href=\"http://getfile6.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/aRi7kDQhxmnZ0Z5lmA5V1RuB9KFM7ulhCHQn7OBEiTp5DpFRgnQ7Ido8BVjF/Using_Machinima_for_Proposal_C.ppt\">Download this file</a> \n</p>\n<p>Last December I applied for a <a href=\"http://www.hubzurich.org/wp/fellowship/fellowship-program/\">Fellowship at the Hub Zurich</a> and co-sponsored by the World Wildlife Foundation. I wanted a way to illustrate my idea with video, so I chose<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machinima\"> machinima</a> and used my simulator in reactiongrid--Ontos2.<p /> These are some slides of the set design and some of the building processes that I used to build the set. You can also see some different lighting techniques using the Environmental Editor. In the end I ran out of time and didn&apos;t get the quality I wanted, but the process was very exciting and was an interesting way to try and visualize ideas.<p /> Virtual Dibden was copied to my inventory in reactiongrid and there is some exciting news to share about that. I needed to get this design out there so I could delete it and move on--as the idea matures. No, I didn&apos;t get the Fellowship--but the work lives on!</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<strong style=\"display: block; margin: 12px 0 4px;\"><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/CTCGrid/mobile-micro-payments-for-ecosystem-services-as-a-digital-literacy-wealth-creation-nd-environmental-strategy\" title=\"Mobile Micro Payments for Ecosystem Services as a Digital Literacy, Wealth Creation and Environmental Strategy\">Mobile Micro Payments for Ecosystem Services as a Digital Literacy, Wealth Creation and Environmental Strategy</a></strong> \n<object height=\"355\" width=\"425\">\n<param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://static.slidesharecdn.com/swf/playerv.swf?doc=hbfellow-110107152328-phpapp01-video&amp;stripped_title=mobile-micro-payments-for-ecosystem-services-as-a-digital-literacy-wealth-creation-nd-environmental-strategy&amp;autoplay=0&amp;userName=CTCGrid\" />\n<param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\" />\n<param name=\"allowScriptAccess\" value=\"always\" /><embed src=\"http://static.slidesharecdn.com/swf/playerv.swf?doc=hbfellow-110107152328-phpapp01-video&amp;stripped_title=mobile-micro-payments-for-ecosystem-services-as-a-digital-literacy-wealth-creation-nd-environmental-strategy&amp;autoplay=0&amp;userName=CTCGrid\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" height=\"355\" width=\"425\"></embed>\n</object>\nView more <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/\">videos</a> from <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/CTCGrid\">Pausanius Raymaker</a>.\n<p />\nyeah, I know, a rough draft--there never seems to be enough time....why is the rum always gone?...These things are connected 	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/using-machinima-for-proposal-creation\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/using-machinima-for-proposal-creation#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',1347894504,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fri, 07 Jan 2011 15:23:00 -0800',NULL,'Jan&apos;s posterous',NULL,'\n    <p>\n	<p>\n<a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/using-machinima-for-proposal-creation\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://posterous.com/images/filetypes/ppt.png\" /></a> <strong>Using Machinima for Proposal Creation.ppt</strong>\n<a href=\"http://getfile6.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/aRi7kDQhxmnZ0Z5lmA5V1RuB9KFM7ulhCHQn7OBEiTp5DpFRgnQ7Ido8BVjF/Using_Machinima_for_Proposal_C.ppt\">Download this file</a> \n</p>\n<p>Last December I applied for a <a href=\"http://www.hubzurich.org/wp/fellowship/fellowship-program/\">Fellowship at the Hub Zurich</a> and co-sponsored by the World Wildlife Foundation. I wanted a way to illustrate my idea with video, so I chose<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machinima\"> machinima</a> and used my simulator in reactiongrid--Ontos2.<p /> These are some slides of the set design and some of the building processes that I used to build the set. You can also see some different lighting techniques using the Environmental Editor. In the end I ran out of time and didn&apos;t get the quality I wanted, but the process was very exciting and was an interesting way to try and visualize ideas.<p /> Virtual Dibden was copied to my inventory in reactiongrid and there is some exciting news to share about that. I needed to get this design out there so I could delete it and move on--as the idea matures. No, I didn&apos;t get the Fellowship--but the work lives on!</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<strong style=\"display: block; margin: 12px 0 4px;\"><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/CTCGrid/mobile-micro-payments-for-ecosystem-services-as-a-digital-literacy-wealth-creation-nd-environmental-strategy\" title=\"Mobile Micro Payments for Ecosystem Services as a Digital Literacy, Wealth Creation and Environmental Strategy\">Mobile Micro Payments for Ecosystem Services as a Digital Literacy, Wealth Creation and Environmental Strategy</a></strong> \n<object height=\"355\" width=\"425\">\n<param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://static.slidesharecdn.com/swf/playerv.swf?doc=hbfellow-110107152328-phpapp01-video&amp;stripped_title=mobile-micro-payments-for-ecosystem-services-as-a-digital-literacy-wealth-creation-nd-environmental-strategy&amp;autoplay=0&amp;userName=CTCGrid\" />\n<param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\" />\n<param name=\"allowScriptAccess\" value=\"always\" /><embed src=\"http://static.slidesharecdn.com/swf/playerv.swf?doc=hbfellow-110107152328-phpapp01-video&amp;stripped_title=mobile-micro-payments-for-ecosystem-services-as-a-digital-literacy-wealth-creation-nd-environmental-strategy&amp;autoplay=0&amp;userName=CTCGrid\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" height=\"355\" width=\"425\"></embed>\n</object>\nView more <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/\">videos</a> from <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/CTCGrid\">Pausanius Raymaker</a>.\n<p />\nyeah, I know, a rough draft--there never seems to be enough time....why is the rum always gone?...These things are connected 	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/using-machinima-for-proposal-creation\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/using-machinima-for-proposal-creation#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(347,0,0,'Construction on Virtual Dibden in Reactiongrid Continues','text/html','http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/construction-on-virtual-dibden-in-reactiongri',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,42,'\n    <p>\n	Press Release: Ontos2, <a href=\"http://reactiongrid.com/\">Reactiongrid</a><p />There was renewed construction on Ontos2 today as Pausanius Raymaker pushed up efforts to be ready for the <a href=\"http://www.lamoillevalleychamber.com/green_mountain_business_expo.html\">Green Mountain Business Exposition</a> November 9th, at the <a href=\"http://www.stoweflake.com/\">Stoweflake Resort and Conference Center</a>, in Stowe, Vermont.Â  Raymaker is feverishly reconstructing Virtual Dibden after making the move from Ontos in Second Life. Excited by megaprims in the new build, Raymaker said, &quot;As a designer this is a very different experience than building in Second Life.Â  Designing and building in a virtual world makes scale fluid, malleable, imaginative--I love megaprims!&quot; <p /> Plans are afoot to integrate a solar array installation along with a green roof. It will be a challenge to see how this all fits together. A virtual world offers an excellent way to simulate the proposals. As for the performance space itself, the imagination--again, is the limit. Complimenting the virtual aspects of place are the mixed media and events occurring hyper locally.Â  &quot;This intersection of imagined and constructed space, immersed within a locality that is mirrored through a wider media ecology is the dimension I am interested in&quot;, says Pausanius.<p /> We will stay tuned for late breaking developments--best of luck Pausanius!<p />Reported by Virtual Dude, Reactiongrid, Ontos2--somewhere in the cloud.<p /> <p>\n<a href=\"http://getfile2.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/nvdTG9Dip9trHp4eU3I5RnPKgyMInt8CaD1z0VtWtjwhLrZSTQPKhcOCUfSe/Dibden_Ontos2_001.png.scaled.1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dibden_ontos2_001\" height=\"298\" src=\"http://getfile1.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/fZLUPQKnZNDcODuTfwnYd5IQFgG3bBM0P5DdQrX3sgoiUhOg1mCJkoE0n2YX/Dibden_Ontos2_001.png.scaled.500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://getfile7.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/RQaqHVQvDpZGujS76cOjTh3LENnlgjBE1ndamzLjpcbjNA1D5OA3mMZIabcx/Dibden_Ontos2_002.png.scaled.1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dibden_ontos2_002\" height=\"298\" src=\"http://getfile6.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/hlVpxXStWxmiPWVBYwLk3fV2VSylvFMh9FX1YEBXmdZwwKYxRkpha02gWzbp/Dibden_Ontos2_002.png.scaled.500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://getfile3.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/CCLk3E8kUBiAk2KaONHZ1wnkJngegCtpoLcxUPOeOt82hggOHVzKOAGBolyJ/Dibden_Ontos2_003.png.scaled.1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dibden_ontos2_003\" height=\"298\" src=\"http://getfile2.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/w2QMLQs4lmWzUkKBAKSTphDGsiSZ7yGspCg0dpl5EpcIiH7aY9Lx252aXv8Q/Dibden_Ontos2_003.png.scaled.500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://getfile9.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/XkIl9KRnv6U9VyBnMcg3aCgzp6EnvzETQo1ChawNiBI0Emy3d6WaYsNVH4TR/Dibden_Ontos2_004.png.scaled.1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dibden_ontos2_004\" height=\"298\" src=\"http://getfile8.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/mrZclv3fEl9w3OlNGvxJIWeBXX2yM3kZTtBWuKITyM5OZ2uj19666hQn12i0/Dibden_Ontos2_004.png.scaled.500.jpg\" width=\"500\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://getfile4.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/1aBVfd7y0ABUaN1emr9h5dL2sngOclZbtljd4oJoM2NTmYDoSJ7HOk9hdVzB/Dibden_Ontos2_005.png.scaled.1000.jpg\"><img alt=\"Dibden_ontos2_005\" height=\"298\" src=\"http://getfile3.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/blogasaurus/mciI7007K7WOukg2yVtuSaQp8a1V7heC9ErHR1U73JbUpVTIWGpA1GNzffjW/Dibd