8',NULL,NULL,29,'New blog post on \"Open Learning\" in k12 #<em>oped12</em> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23vsmooc12\" title=\"#vsmooc12\" class=\" \">#vsmooc12</a> <a href=\"http://t.co/Lm4rJbje\">http://t.co/Lm4rJbje</a>',1347895324,NULL,NULL,'verenanz','http://twitter.com/verenanz','Mon, 17 Sep 2012 00:01:42 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(375,0,0,'El poder de la imagen para aprender a contar.','text/html','http://claudiaguerreros.wordpress.com/2012/09/17/el-poder-de-la-imagen-para-aprender-a-contar/','EstadÃ­stica',NULL,NULL,5,NULL,NULL,NULL,10,'En el cÃ¡lculo de la probabilidad clÃ¡sica &#8220;a priori&#8221; de los juegos de azar, desde la definicÃ³n clÃ¡sica de Laplace &#8230;<p><a href=\"http://claudiaguerreros.wordpress.com/2012/09/17/el-poder-de-la-imagen-para-aprender-a-contar/\">Continuar leyendo &#187;</a></p><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=claudiaguerreros.wordpress.com&#038;blog=19275578&#038;post=235&#038;subd=claudiaguerreros&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347903966,NULL,NULL,'claudiaguerreros','http://claudiaguerreros.wordpress.com','Mon, 17 Sep 2012 15:33:02 +0000',NULL,'De acÃ¡ y de allÃ¡',NULL,'<p>En el cÃ¡lculo de la probabilidad clÃ¡sica &#8220;a priori&#8221; de los juegos de azar, desde la definicÃ³n clÃ¡sica de Laplace que emplea espacios muestrales finitos, igualmente probables,Â  la probabilidad es el resutlado de dividir los casos favorables entre todos los resultados posibles.</p>\n<p>La enumeraciÃ³n de estos resultados posibles se puede elaborar mediante los Ã¡rboles muestrales que permiten imaginar cada uno de los resultdos posibles e ir variando los posibles estados subsecuentes.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignleft\" title=\"Cuando los dedos no alcanzan\" src=\"http://www.deduk.cl/img/productos/184_Manos%20para%20contar%20y%20ensartar.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"328\" height=\"318\" /></p>\n<p>El anÃ¡lisis combinatorio identifica a partir del nÃºmero de elementos elegidos, del Ã³rden y de la repeticiÃ³n de los mismos las reglas de conteo bÃ¡sicas conocidads como arreglos, permutaciones (caso especial del arreglo) y las combinaciones.</p>\n<p>En las fÃ³rmulas intervienen cÃ¡lculos de factoriales, y las proporciones que resusltan de la repeticiÃ³n de los elementos o de la igualdad de los resultados por ejemplo si el orden no importa.<br />\nEl objetivo de la fÃ³rmula es realizar el cÃ¡lculo sin necesidad de elaborar el Ã¡rbol muestral.</p>\n<p>En el documento que anexo intentÃ© ilustrar el paso de la elaboraciÃ³n del Ã¡rbol muestral a la utilizaciÃ³n de la fÃ³rmula correspondiente y finalmente un diagrama de flujo que me permitirÃ¡ elegir el arreglo numÃ©rico que estoy tratando de contabilizar.</p>\n<p><a title=\"Ãrboles y reglas de conteo\" href=\"http://es.scribd.com/doc/106155205/Arboles-y-Reglas-de-Conteo\" target=\"_blank\">Ãrboles y reglas de conteo</a></p>\n<p>Un paso mÃ¡s para seguir aprendiendo a contar.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/claudiaguerreros.wordpress.com/235/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/claudiaguerreros.wordpress.com/235/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=claudiaguerreros.wordpress.com&#038;blog=19275578&#038;post=235&#038;subd=claudiaguerreros&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(376,0,0,'UofT and Moocs - Oped12','text/html','http://moocworld.blogspot.com/2012/09/uoft-and-moocs-oped12.html',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-09-17 11:06:45',20,'Earlier this year, the University of Toronto stated that they had great interest in MOOCs as it would showcase&amp;nbsp;their contributions to global innovation and it would \"enhance&amp;nbsp;(their) situation, through the recognition of their)contribution\" <br />(<a href=\"http://collaboration.itincanada.ca/index.php?cid=327&amp;amp;id=17443&amp;amp;np=3\">http://collaboration.itincanada.ca/index.php?cid=327&amp;amp;id=17443&amp;amp;np=3</a>).&amp;nbsp; <br />I don&apos;t doubt that when a rather prestigious univeristy, such as UofT, wants to dive into the world of MOOCs, it will benefit many of us on&amp;nbsp;the \"outside\".&amp;nbsp; But I think we should also think about the growths of MOOCs as playing a key role&amp;nbsp;as an educational platform geared towards the&amp;nbsp;everyday individual.&amp;nbsp; This is not just about recognition and showcasing talents, but allowing everyone to benefit from&amp;nbsp;such openess.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;I also can&apos;t help thinking about Hatakka&apos;s article (<a href=\"http://www.ejisdc.org/ojs2/index.php/ejisdc/article/viewFile/545/279\">http://www.ejisdc.org/ojs2/index.php/ejisdc/article/viewFile/545/279</a>) on MOOCs and developing countries.&amp;nbsp; It is not a matter of uploading as much content as possible into the MOOC universe, but also building content that is relevant, accessible and meanginful.&amp;nbsp; MOOCs provide a real opportunity for the sharing of knowledge, but we must be aware of how knowledge is accessed, synthesized and used.&amp;nbsp; We can build a ton of content, but it doesn&apos;t mean everyone wants it or can use it.&amp;nbsp; <br />&amp;nbsp;<br />...just some thoughts...<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/285347253083067562-9177601182822513093?l=moocworld.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347905043,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Mon, 17 Sep 2012 15:06:00 +0000',NULL,'Open Ed - A MOOC World',NULL,'Earlier this year, the University of Toronto stated that they had great interest in MOOCs as it would showcase&amp;nbsp;their contributions to global innovation and it would \"enhance&amp;nbsp;(their) situation, through the recognition of their)contribution\" <br />(<a href=\"http://collaboration.itincanada.ca/index.php?cid=327&amp;amp;id=17443&amp;amp;np=3\">http://collaboration.itincanada.ca/index.php?cid=327&amp;amp;id=17443&amp;amp;np=3</a>).&amp;nbsp; <br />I don&apos;t doubt that when a rather prestigious univeristy, such as UofT, wants to dive into the world of MOOCs, it will benefit many of us on&amp;nbsp;the \"outside\".&amp;nbsp; But I think we should also think about the growths of MOOCs as playing a key role&amp;nbsp;as an educational platform geared towards the&amp;nbsp;everyday individual.&amp;nbsp; This is not just about recognition and showcasing talents, but allowing everyone to benefit from&amp;nbsp;such openess.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;I also can&apos;t help thinking about Hatakka&apos;s article (<a href=\"http://www.ejisdc.org/ojs2/index.php/ejisdc/article/viewFile/545/279\">http://www.ejisdc.org/ojs2/index.php/ejisdc/article/viewFile/545/279</a>) on MOOCs and developing countries.&amp;nbsp; It is not a matter of uploading as much content as possible into the MOOC universe, but also building content that is relevant, accessible and meanginful.&amp;nbsp; MOOCs provide a real opportunity for the sharing of knowledge, but we must be aware of how knowledge is accessed, synthesized and used.&amp;nbsp; We can build a ton of content, but it doesn&apos;t mean everyone wants it or can use it.&amp;nbsp; <br />&amp;nbsp;<br />...just some thoughts...<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/285347253083067562-9177601182822513093?l=moocworld.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(377,0,0,'MOOCs: How new are they?','text/html','https://landing.athabascau.ca/blog/view/163931/moocs-how-new-are-they',NULL,NULL,NULL,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,39,'<p>The research on MOOCs may be scarce, but that is because they are relatively recent. Or are they? According to the Wiki definition (and others) of a MOOC, Athabasca University and other open universities have been delivering MOOCs for nearly 20 years. They have had Massive numbers of students Online taking Open Courses (MOOCs), but without using the name. There is older research on Large classes. Here&rsquo;s some listed below. And there is much research on online learning and openness in education, so one must think in terms of knitting this research together with new finding on how MOOCs are presently being delivered (or connected!).</p>\n<p>Ritzer, G. (2004). <em>The McDonaldization of society: Revised new century edition</em>. Thousand Oaks: Pine Forge Press.</p>\n<p>Wenglinksy, H. (2002, July 1). The effect of class size on achievement: What the research says&nbsp; Retrieved March 19, 2003, from http://www.ets.org/research/policy_research_reports/pic-memorandum</p>\n<p>Hanushek, E. (1998, February). The Evidence on Class Size Occasional Paper 98-1. Retrieved March 18, 2003, from http://www.wallis.rochester.edu/WallisPapers/wallis_10.pdf</p>\n<p>Gilbert, S. (1995). Quality education: Does class size matter? Vol. 1. <em>Research File </em>(pp. 1 - 7).&nbsp; Retrieved from http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/search/detailmini.jsp?_nfpb=true&amp;_&amp;ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=ED421026&amp;ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=no&amp;accno=ED421026</p>\n<p>Glass, G. V., Cohen, L. S., Smith, M. L., &amp; Filby, N. W. (1982). <em>School class size: Research and policy</em>. Beverly Hills, CA: Sage.</p>\n<p>Hanushek, E. A. (1986). The economics of schooling: Production and efficiency in public schools. <em>Journal of Economic Literature, XXIV</em>(3), 1141 - 1177.</p>\n',1347907084,NULL,NULL,'Rory McGreal','https://landing.athabascau.ca/blog/owner/rory','Mon, 17 Sep 2012 10:47:17 -0600',NULL,'CDATA(0)',NULL,'<p>The research on MOOCs may be scarce, but that is because they are relatively recent. Or are they? According to the Wiki definition (and others) of a MOOC, Athabasca University and other open universities have been delivering MOOCs for nearly 20 years. They have had Massive numbers of students Online taking Open Courses (MOOCs), but without using the name. There is older research on Large classes. Here&rsquo;s some listed below. And there is much research on online learning and openness in education, so one must think in terms of knitting this research together with new finding on how MOOCs are presently being delivered (or connected!).</p>\n<p>Ritzer, G. (2004). <em>The McDonaldization of society: Revised new century edition</em>. Thousand Oaks: Pine Forge Press.</p>\n<p>Wenglinksy, H. (2002, July 1). The effect of class size on achievement: What the research says&nbsp; Retrieved March 19, 2003, from http://www.ets.org/research/policy_research_reports/pic-memorandum</p>\n<p>Hanushek, E. (1998, February). The Evidence on Class Size Occasional Paper 98-1. Retrieved March 18, 2003, from http://www.wallis.rochester.edu/WallisPapers/wallis_10.pdf</p>\n<p>Gilbert, S. (1995). Quality education: Does class size matter? Vol. 1. <em>Research File </em>(pp. 1 - 7).&nbsp; Retrieved from http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/search/detailmini.jsp?_nfpb=true&amp;_&amp;ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=ED421026&amp;ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=no&amp;accno=ED421026</p>\n<p>Glass, G. V., Cohen, L. S., Smith, M. L., &amp; Filby, N. W. (1982). <em>School class size: Research and policy</em>. Beverly Hills, CA: Sage.</p>\n<p>Hanushek, E. A. (1986). The economics of schooling: Production and efficiency in public schools. <em>Journal of Economic Literature, XXIV</em>(3), 1141 - 1177.</p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(378,0,0,'Tech failures r the cracks that let the light in. They allow us 2 c  tech that would otherwise b invisible 2 us #oped12 http://t.co/DpfcfR4I','twitter','http://twitter.com/mark_mcguire/statuses/247740044838830081',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/mark_mcguire/statuses/