uris/statuses/247816474922733571',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/DimitrisTzouris/statuses/247816474922733571',NULL,NULL,29,'Lecture 01 - History - Introduction to Open Education on Blip <a href=\"http://t.co/8WbrLmUH\">http://t.co/8WbrLmUH</a> via @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/Blip\">Blip</a> #<em>oped12</em>',1347923404,NULL,NULL,'DimitrisTzouris','http://twitter.com/DimitrisTzouris','Mon, 17 Sep 2012 21:57:06 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(386,0,0,'Rees underwhelmed by Coursera history course. Hope he gets intrigued &amp;amp; decides to do a better course. http://t.co/DySsUM9d #oped12 #moocmooc','twitter','http://twitter.com/ifrank/statuses/247854904004198400',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/ifrank/statuses/247854904004198400',NULL,NULL,29,'Rees underwhelmed by Coursera history course. Hope he gets intrigued &amp;amp; decides to do a better course. <a href=\"http://t.co/DySsUM9d\">http://t.co/DySsUM9d</a> #<em>oped12</em> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23moocmooc\" title=\"#moocmooc\" class=\" \">#moocmooc</a>',1347928444,NULL,NULL,'ifrank','http://twitter.com/ifrank','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 00:29:48 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(387,0,0,'One way in which Open Educational Resources and Open Software are different. http://t.co/8u6GHriB #oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/yukondude/statuses/247846797932892160',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/yukondude/statuses/247846797932892160',NULL,NULL,29,'One way in which Open Educational Resources and Open Software are different. <a href=\"http://t.co/8u6GHriB\">http://t.co/8u6GHriB</a> #<em>oped12</em>',1347928444,NULL,NULL,'yukondude','http://twitter.com/yukondude','Mon, 17 Sep 2012 23:57:36 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(388,29,0,'One way in which Open Educational Resources and Open Software are different #oped12','text/html','http://yukonmooc.blogspot.com/2012/09/one-way-in-which-open-educational.html','oped12',NULL,NULL,13,NULL,NULL,'2012-09-17 16:56:38',23,'The <a href=\"http://open.mooc.ca/week1.htm\">week 1 readings</a>, particularly <a href=\"http://firstmonday.org/htbin/cgiwrap/bin/ojs/index.php/fm/article/view/1472/1387\">The Cathedral and the Bazaar</a>, discussed the advantages and meaning of the term \"open\" when it comes to computer software code. There is at least one obvious parallel with open educational resources: both are creative works, subject to copyright. That the audience of one is a machine, and of the other is a human student, doesn&apos;t materially affect the \"openness\" of either.<br /><br />Having been a software developer (a.k.a., computer programmer or code jockey) for the past couple of decades, I&apos;ve watched the growth of public domain, free, and open source projects with interest: using many, publishing a handful <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/klondike-firewall/\">of</a> <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/casebase/\">my</a> <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/scripnix/\">own</a>, and even changing a couple in small ways for my specific needs.<br /><br />And having taught computer courses for the past ten years, I&apos;ve released all of my class notes under the <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.5/ca/\">Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 2.5 Canada License</a> (once it was invented).<br />While I&apos;ve enjoyed only middling interest in my software and course materials, the way in which they have been \"shared\" (in the sense of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copyleft\">copyleft</a> licences) with others has one difference; the same difference in the way I&apos;ve \"borrowed\" (under the terms of the licences) open source software and open eductational resources. That difference could be called \"scope.\"<br /><br />When I use open educational resources, I typically borrow in small measures: a paragraph or two, a class activity, a problem set. The same is true when borrowing from copyright-protected materials: small bites are&amp;nbsp;permissible&amp;nbsp;under the <a href=\"http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-42/page-17.html#h-24\">fair dealing provisions</a> of the <a href=\"http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-42/index.html\">Copyright Act</a>&amp;nbsp;of Canada. An interpretation that was <a href=\"http://scc.lexum.org/en/2012/2012scc37/2012scc37.html\">recently affirmed by the Supreme Court</a>&amp;nbsp;(<a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2012/07/12/f-vp-nowak-copyright-ruling-consumer.html\">see the section called Textbook Photocopying</a> for a simple explanation of this ruling). Unfortunately, as <a href=\"http://blip.tv/file/1645455\">David Wiley points out</a>, constructing educational materials from disparate, though open, sources can be&amp;nbsp;bedevilling&amp;nbsp;because of the seemingly infinite variety of clashing open licensing schemes.<br /><br />Software, on the other hand, is typically borrowed whole: entire projects, or at least significant modules that themselves could qualify as free or open-source licensed projects. Bite-sized portions of computer code are rarely useful in isolation. From within, computer programs may appear like tangles of spaghetti-like dependencies. Because of this, programmers work hard to encapsulate their logic into modules with simple interfaces (called <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Application_programming_interface\">API</a>s) to access the modules&apos; features. Within a project, these modules may depend on others, and before long another form of spaghetti appears. Knowing this, programmers tend to borrow whole projects rather than attempt to just extract the components they will need.&amp;nbsp;Together with the fact that many <a href=\"http://opensource.org/licenses/category\">open-source licences</a> require that any constituent project be distributed in its entirety, there is simply very little sharing in the software world of small pieces of intellectual property. So long as re-use is limited to a project&apos;s API, there is also less chance of&amp;nbsp;incompatibility&amp;nbsp;between open licences (<a href=\"http://www.networkworld.com/news/2012/053112-judge-clears-google-of-java-259747.html\">assuming Oracle doesn&apos;t win its Java API lawsuit against Google on appeal</a>).<br /><br />For this reason, I am not convinced that the comparison between open educational resource and open software licenses is a true apple-to-apples comparison. In particular, I doubt that any legal ruling made about one of these licences would carry over to the other domain.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1181176236413981837-7589520815738201510?l=yukonmooc.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1347930604,NULL,NULL,'yukondude','http://www.blogger.com/profile/14427008736132127215','2012-09-17T16:56:00.000-07:00',NULL,'YukonMOOC','29','The <a href=\"http://open.mooc.ca/week1.htm\">week 1 readings</a>, particularly <a href=\"http://firstmonday.org/htbin/cgiwrap/bin/ojs/index.php/fm/article/view/1472/1387\">The Cathedral and the Bazaar</a>, discussed the advantages and meaning of the term \"open\" when it comes to computer software code. There is at least one obvious parallel with open educational resources: both are creative works, subject to copyright. That the audience of one is a machine, and of the other is a human student, doesn&apos;t materially affect the \"openness\" of either.<br /><br />Having been a software developer (a.k.a., computer programmer or code jockey) for the past couple of decades, I&apos;ve watched the growth of public domain, free, and open source projects with interest: using many, publishing a handful <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/klondike-firewall/\">of</a> <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/casebase/\">my</a> <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/scripnix/\">own</a>, and even changing a couple in small ways for my specific needs.<br /><br />And having taught computer courses for the past ten years, I&apos;ve released all of my class notes under the <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.5/ca/\">Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 2.5 Canada License</a> (once it was invented).<br />While I&apos;ve enjoyed only middling interest in my software and course materials, the way in which they have been \"shared\" (in the sense of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copyleft\">copyleft</a> licences) with others has one difference; the same difference in the way I&apos;ve \"borrowed\" (under the terms of the licences) open source software and open eductational resources. That difference could be called \"scope.\"<br /><br />When I use open educational resources, I typically borrow in small measures: a paragraph or two, a class activity, a problem set. The same is true when borrowing from copyright-protected materials: small bites are&amp;nbsp;permissible&amp;nbsp;under the <a href=\"http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-42/page-17.html#h-24\">fair dealing provisions</a> of the <a href=\"http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-42/index.html\">Copyright Act</a>&amp;nbsp;of Canada. An interpretation that was <a href=\"http://scc.lexum.org/en/2012/2012scc37/2012scc37.html\">recently affirmed by the Supreme Court</a>&amp;nbsp;(<a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2012/07/12/f-vp-nowak-copyright-ruling-consumer.html\">see the section called Textbook Photocopying</a> for a simple explanation of this ruling). Unfortunately, as <a href=\"http://blip.tv/file/1645455\">David Wiley points out</a>, constructing educational materials from disparate, though open, sources can be&amp;nbsp;bedevilling&amp;nbsp;because of the seemingly infinite variety of clashing open licensing schemes.<br /><br />Software, on the other hand, is typically borrowed whole: entire projects, or at least significant modules that themselves could qualify as free or open-source licensed projects. Bite-sized portions of computer code are rarely useful in isolation. From within, computer programs may appear like tangles of spaghetti-like dependencies. Because of this, programmers work hard to encapsulate their logic into modules with simple interfaces (called <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Application_programming_interface\">API</a>s) to access the modules&apos; features. Within a project, these modules may depend on others, and before long another form of spaghetti appears. Knowing this, programmers tend to borrow whole projects rather than attempt to just extract the components they will need.&amp;nbsp;Together with the fact that many <a href=\"http://opensource.org/licenses/category\">open-source licences</a> require that any constituent project be distributed in its entirety, there is simply very little sharing in the software world of small pieces of intellectual property. So long as re-use is limited to a project&apos;s API, there is also less chance of&amp;nbsp;incompatibility&amp;nbsp;between open licences (<a href=\"http://www.networkworld.com/news/2012/053112-judge-clears-google-of-java-259747.html\">assuming Oracle doesn&apos;t win its Java API lawsuit against Google on appeal</a>).<br /><br />For this reason, I am not convinced that the comparison between open educational resource and open software licenses is a true apple-to-apples comparison. In particular, I doubt that any legal ruling made about one of these licences would carry over to the other domain.<img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1181176236413981837-7589520815738201510?l=yukonmooc.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(389,0,0,'#oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/redclaycat/statuses/247880297776021504',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/redclaycat/statuses/247880297776021504',NULL,NULL,29,'#<em>oped12</em>',1347938523,NULL,NULL,'redclaycat','http://twitter.com/redclaycat','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 02:10:43 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(390,0,0,'OTR Links 09/18/2012','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/otr-links-09182012/','Links',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'Citelighter &#8211; The fully automated bibliography, research, citation, and internet highlighting tool. Store, organize, and share your education and research for free. tags: research citation biography collaboration tools reference highlight tool english language Wikis In School Libraries Wikis in School &#8230; <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/otr-links-09182012/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11038&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347949923,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 05:30:37 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<ul class=\"diigo-linkroll\">\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.citelighter.com\">Citelighter &#8211; The fully automated bibliography, research, citation, and internet highlighting tool.</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Store, organize, and share your education and research for free.</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/research\">research</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/citation\">citation</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/biography\">biography</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/collaboration\">collaboration</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tools\">tools</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/reference\">reference</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/highlight\">highlight</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tool\">tool</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/english\">english</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/language\">language</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/dukicd/wikis-in-school-libraries-1053307\">Wikis In School Libraries</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Wikis in School Libraries</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/wikis\">wikis</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dn0x9wmr5uw\">Wikis 1 &#8211; Technology Tips for Librarians &#8211; YouTube</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Librarians can watch this video to learn more about how to use wikis to support teaching and learning in their library programs.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/technology\">technology</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/youtube\">youtube</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/librarians\">librarians</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/wikis\">wikis</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://visual.ly/awesome-science-mindmapping\">The Awesome Science of Mindmapping | Visual.ly</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Mindmapping is a very serious and well researched subject, or art ... or something . Whatever it is a map of the mind is definately something to be valued and this &#8216;instructionalicious&#8217; guide is no exception. Allow this infographic to simultaneously blow and map your mind.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/mindmapping\">mindmapping</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/mindmap\">mindmap</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/poster\">poster</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infographic\">infographic</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.microsoft.com/athome/students/studentsites.aspx?WT.mc_id=MSCOM_EN_US_AH_TIPS_131Z6ENUS22202&amp;WT.rss_f=At%20Home%20RSS&amp;WT.rss_a=Jump-start%20and%20improve%20your%20Internet%20research%20for%20school&amp;WT.rss_ev=a\">Top 14 websites for students</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;If you want to a see a blank look on students&apos; faces, ask them about the Dewey Decimal library classification system. For better or for worse, the Internet has become the alternative to a library card catalog for browsing and locating resources. But how do you navigate that system, and how can you trust what you read on the web?&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/websites\">websites</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/students\">students</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.ideaslab.edu.au\">ideasLAB &#8211; exploring new possibilities</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">ideasLAB aims to challenge the way we think about learning and teaching, and find new ways to take technology into the classroom.</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/education\">education</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ideaslab\">ideaslab</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/research\">research</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/technology\">technology</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/leadership\">leadership</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://java.dzone.com/articles/quicksort-easy-way\">Quicksort &#8211; the Easy Way | Javalobby</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Quick sort is the fastest known comparision sort for arrays. To top it, it could be done in-place for arrays. For Linked Lists, Merge Sort might be a better option. Also since Quicksort improves its performance by using random numbers, it also becomes an example of a breed of algorithms named \"Randomized Algorithms\".&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/way\">way</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/sort\">sort</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/quicksort\">quicksort</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/programming\">programming</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.edgalaxy.com/journal/2012/9/17/lesson-idea-go-fly-a-kite-includes-kite-template.html\">Lesson Idea: Go Fly a Kite &#8211; Includes KiteÂ Template &#8211; Edgalaxy &#8211; Cool Stuff For Nerdy Teachers &#8211; Edgalaxy: Where Education and Technology Meet.</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Kids love making kites.Â  And the kite I have included in this lesson is incredibly easy to make, requires very few resources and flies brilliantly.Â  Secondly this is a great opportunity for you to learn about writing procedural texts.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/lesson\">lesson</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/idea\">idea</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/kite\">kite</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/includes\">includes</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/cool\">cool</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/cool stuff\">cool stuff</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/stuff\">stuff</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/nerdy\">nerdy</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/template\">template</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/education\">education</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/technology\">technology</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/meet\">meet</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.buildwithchrome.com/static/map\">Build with Chrome</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Build with Chrome &#8211; and Lego</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/lego\">lego</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/chrome\">chrome</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/google\">google</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/build\">build</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/maps\">maps</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/create\">create</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/architecture\">architecture</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/legos\">legos</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.sec-ed.co.uk/best-practice/byod-in-10-steps\">BYOD in 10 steps &#8211; SecEd</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Mobile learning lets pupils move toward personalised, anytime/anywhere learning, with access to the wealth of information and resources on the web at their fingertips. But budget concerns often leave schools without the ability to provide every student with their own device. And research increasingly shows that students already own those devices anyway.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/steps\">steps</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/byod\">byod</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://edudemic.com/2012/09/the-5-most-amazing-feats-of-ancient-engineering/\">The 5 Most Amazing Feats Of Ancient Engineering | Edudemic</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Want to build your own pyramid? How about some rice terraces? Sure, you could use some fancy modern equipment and take the easy way out...&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ancient\">ancient</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/engineering\">engineering</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://slav.global2.vic.edu.au/2012/09/17/automate-your-dropbox-with-wappwolf/\">Automate your Dropbox with Wappwolf | Bright Ideas</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Wappwolf is a free service which connects with your Dropbox or Google Drive account and lets you set automated tasks&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/automate\">automate</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/dropbox\">dropbox</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ideas\">ideas</a></p>\n<ul class=\"diigo-comments\">         </ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://connectedprincipals.com/archives/6272\">4 Ways We Can Connect With Parents | Connected Principals</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Recently I was asked about the idea of using specialized software to connect with parents so that they can login, see all of their child&apos;s grades, marks, assignments, homework, and a ton of other information. Â Although I believe that these systems are designed to help make our systems transparent and ensure that we connect with kids, are they really effective for learning and improving our relationships with parents? &#8220;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ways\">ways</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/parents\">parents</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/connected\">connected</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/principals\">principals</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://wordpress.holyspirit.ab.ca/?p=745\">Being an instructional leader! Â» Superintendent&#8217;s Blog</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;It is already September 15th and the question is, \"Have youÂ visited a classroom yet?\" Â Most school administrators will probably be able to answer that questionÂ in the affirmative. Within the first couple of weeks and generally throughout the year, principals and associatesÂ find themselves walking through and visiting many classrooms. However, if I rated this activity on the basis of improving teaching qualityÂ using a modified version of Â Bloom&apos;s Taxonomy, I&apos;d probably rate it as lower level.Â Visitations or walkthroughs are Â better than not being in classrooms at all, but not by much.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/being\">being</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/instructional\">instructional</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/leader\">leader</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/superintendent\">superintendent</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/blog\">blog</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/teacher-network/2012/sep/16/tablets-laptops-mobile-in-classrooms-teachers-tips\">Tablets, laptops and mobiles in the classroom: top tips from teachers | Teacher Network Blog | Guardian Professional</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Tablets, laptops and mobiles aren&#8217;t there to replace traditional teaching tools, but designed to complement them. Our panel of education experts share advice on using one to one devices in schools&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tablets\">tablets</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/laptops\">laptops</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/mobiles\">mobiles</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/classroom\">classroom</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tips\">tips</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teacher\">teacher</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/network\">network</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/blog\">blog</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/guardian\">guardian</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/professional\">professional</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://designyoutrust.com/2012/09/the-history-of-html5-infographic/\">The History of HTML5 [Infographic] Â» Design You Trust â€“ Design Blog and Community</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;The History of HTML5 [Infographic]&#8220;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/history\">history</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/html\">html</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infographic\">infographic</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/design\">design</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/blog\">blog</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/community\">community</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.othersidegroup.com/2012/09/worldwide-internet-usage-infographic/\">Infographic of Worldwide Internet Usage | Other Side Group</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;This is a goodie. Brought to us by WebpageFX, this infographic shows us how the internet has been adopted around the world.Â But you may be surprised at what nations have adopted the internet the most....&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infographic\">infographic</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/internet\">internet</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/usage\">usage</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/group\">group</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://stephenslighthouse.com/2012/09/16/learning-analytics-leveraging-education-data-infographic/\">New Learning Analytics: Leveraging Education Data [Infographic] â€“ Stephen&#8217;s Lighthouse</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Learning Analytics: Leveraging Education Data [Infographic]&#8220;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/learning\">learning</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/analytics\">analytics</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/education\">education</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/data\">data</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infographic\">infographic</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/stephen\">stephen</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/lighthouse\">lighthouse</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.premiumwp.com/wordpress-and-tumblr-the-fairy-tale/\">WordPress and Tumblr: The Fairy Tale</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Once upon a time, in the electric island of Blogosphere grew the sibling rivalry of WordPress and Tumblr.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/wordpress\">wordpress</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tumblr\">tumblr</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/fairy\">fairy</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tale\">tale</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.problogger.net/archives/2012/09/16/curb-your-blogging-frustration-in-8-steps/\">Curb Your Blogging Frustration in 8 Steps : @ProBlogger</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">That last blog post wasÂ reallyÂ good. It was supposed to be the one. The post that launched you into blogging stardom. Right into the spotlight. Making you an overnight success.</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/blogging\">blogging</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/frustration\">frustration</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/steps\">steps</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/problogger\">problogger</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.onlinedegrees.org/12-compelling-reasons-we-should-rethink-school-desks/\">12 Compelling Reasons We Should Rethink School Desks &#8211; OnlineDegrees.org</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Students young and old frequently complain about the quality of the desks and chairs provided on campus, yet it remains one of the more overlooked issues. A pity, because poor ergonomics and comfort can actually lead to poor health, and poor health leads to missed classes and heightened medical expenditures once career time rolls around. Maybe it&apos;s about time educators, schools, and districts reconsidered their approach towards how they set up classrooms. The positive outcomes might very well prove surprising.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/reasons\">reasons</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/school\">school</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/desks\">desks</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/org\">org</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://blog.core-ed.org/blog/2012/09/ten-trends-2012-social-learning.html\">Ten Trends 2012: Social Learning |</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;What opportunities lie in the vast array of social media platforms and technologies out there? Also, how can we deconstruct the educational riches as professionals plus for those whom we serve (our students and our organisations)?&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/trends\">trends</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/social\">social</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/learning\">learning</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.educatorstechnology.com/2012/09/what-teachers-need-to-know-about-21st.html\">What Teachers Need to Know about 21st Century Literacy</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Technology is not only changing the way education is perceived of today but is redefining the overall education scope. It has created new sciences and reorganized the relationships between long-standing disciplines and fields of inquiry. It has also created new cultural representations and industries. At this historical moment , Â knowledge itself is in transition as new systems for the generation, systematization, surveillance, and management of knowledge are beign created.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/know\">know</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/literacy\">literacy</a></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"diigo-ps\">Posted from <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com&apos;>Diigo</a>. The rest of my favorite links are <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete&apos;>here</a>.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11038/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11038/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11038&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(391,0,0,'How do you foster technological innovation?','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/how-do-you-foster-technological-innovation/','Computers;Education;learning;Teaching;classroom;Google;Harrow Fair;Innovation;London;school;web 2.0;Western Fair',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'In the past month, I enjoyedÂ both the Harrow Fair and the Western Fair in London.Â  One of the things that you&apos;ll find at any good fair is the midway filled with fair food, the newest in farm equipment, and of &#8230; <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/how-do-you-foster-technological-innovation/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11032&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347960003,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 09:00:00 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<p>In the past month, I enjoyedÂ both the Harrow Fair and the Western Fair in London.Â  One of the things that you&apos;ll find at any good fair is the midway filled with fair food, the newest in farm equipment, and of course, those games.Â  You know them â€“ Whack a Mole, throwing darts at balloons, shooting big basketballs into little hoops, the fish pond, and more.Â  All of these stops are intriguing even though I know that the games are next to impossible.Â  (at least for me...)</p>\n<p>The games aren&apos;t impossible though.Â  You see all kinds of people stepping up and laying their money down for a chance to win that big stuffed animal.</p>\n<p>Why?</p>\n<p>If you watch carefully, when the booths are empty, the counter workers play the and do so successfully.Â  Is it boredom?Â  Nah!Â  It&apos;s part of their job!Â  In addition to showing how it&apos;s done, they&apos;re talking the talk.Â  It doesn&apos;t take too long before they convince everyone within eye and ear sight that they can do it too &#8211; even if they&apos;ve never done it before.Â  They even change the rules a bit to give everyone a chance.Â  That little guy that hangs around with us is a perfect example.Â  (and he went 4 for 5 too and won a duck)</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://dougpete.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/fair.jpg\"><img style=\"background-image:none;padding-left:0;padding-right:0;display:block;float:none;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;padding-top:0;border-width:0;\" title=\"fair\" src=\"http://dougpete.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/fair_thumb.jpg?w=554&h=829\" alt=\"fair\" width=\"554\" height=\"829\" border=\"0\" /></a></p>\n<p align=\"center\">I wasn&apos;t allowed the stand on the counter though...</p>\n<p align=\"left\">Shouldn&apos;t the rules of the midway apply in education?</p>\n<p align=\"left\">The rest of this post is directed at those who would be leaders and supporters of change.Â  What are you doing to support those who would like to try things in their classrooms?Â  Are you supportive?Â  Are you leading?</p>\n<p align=\"left\">I think everyone would like to think that their school system is right on the leading edge.Â  This includes reaching out to teachers and students who would like to use the latest in technology but know that there will be a bit of a learning curve, with some stumbling blocks.Â  Is that OK with you?Â  Are you showing the way by example?</p>\n<p align=\"left\">If the use of Web 2.0 tools is important to you and your school, are you using them?Â  Or do you create a memo in your office tool, convert it to PDF so that it can&apos;t be changed and then emailing it to staff members individually?</p>\n<p align=\"left\">Do you collaborate for staff meetings or initiatives like you&apos;d like to see collaboration happen in the classrooms?Â  How about the easiest and perhaps one of the most powerful tools â€“ the blog?</p>\n<p align=\"left\">If blogging is important to happen, are you blogging yourself?Â  It&apos;s quite one thing to sit back and issue an edict that you want blogging to happen in the school, but quite another to be supportive.</p>\n<p align=\"left\">Here are some ideas to be supportive</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\nwrite your own blog â€“ you&apos;re probably doing a <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/03/22/your-school-doesnt-need-a-newsletter/\">newsletter</a> anyway;\n</li>\n<li>\ncomment on each and every classroom blog â€“ time well spent &#8211; advertise class blogs through your own;\n</li>\n<li>\nbe a guest blogger on a classroom blog â€“ help the cause with some of your insights to a classroom topic;\n</li>\n<li>\nlet the class interview you on a topic and have them post the interview;\n</li>\n<li>\ntake your smartphone for a walk and do a scavenger hunt of the school and have the students explore and discover;\n</li>\n<li>\ntake your smartphone and show images of the monthly theme â€“ let the kids share their thoughts;\n</li>\n<li>do a show and tell, bring and brag, at the next parents&apos; group meeting;</li>\n<li>create and share a webquest via blog post &#8211; you&#8217;re passionate about something;</li>\n<li>go through that filing cabinet and turn your great lessons into lessons to be shared with others;</li>\n<li>\nyou were a teacher before &#8211; what can you pay back to the profession?\n&#8230;\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p align=\"left\">We talk about the need for kids to be \"Google-able\".Â  What about you?Â  If the only results are your name on the front page of a school or district or perhaps embedded in a copy of the minutes of a meeting, it&apos;s time that you up your game.</p>\n<p align=\"left\">With a bit of effort, you can push the innovation process along.Â  Today it&apos;s blogging; tomorrow â€“ ?</p>\n<h6 class=\"zemanta-related-title\" style=\"font-size:1em;\">Related articles</h6>\n<ul class=\"zemanta-article-ul\">\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/15/always-learning-always-connected/\" target=\"_blank\">Always Learning, Always Connected</a> (dougpete.wordpress.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://bloxhammarketing.com/2012/09/03/technology-in-my-ideal-school-the-marketers-perspective/\" target=\"_blank\">Technology in my ideal school &#8211; the marketer&#8217;s perspective</a> (bloxhammarketing.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://teachingslearnings.wordpress.com/2012/09/11/who-will-drive-teaching-teachers-or-students/\" target=\"_blank\">Who will drive Teaching: Teachers or Students?</a> (teachingslearnings.wordpress.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://www.angelamaiers.com/2012/09/skype-in-the-classroom-connecting-dots-between-schools-students-and-communities.html\" target=\"_blank\">Skype In the Classroom &#8211; Connecting Dots between Schools, Students and Communities</a> (angelamaiers.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://www.connectwithyourteens.net/2012/08/15-educational-technology-blogs-that.html\" target=\"_blank\">15 Educational Technology Blogs that Rock</a> (connectwithyourteens.net)</li>\n</ul>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11032/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11032/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11032&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(392,0,0,'Work in Progress&#8230;','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/work-in-progress/','Just Rambling',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'This is one of the coolest things I&#8217;ve seen in a while. Â After reading this story this morning &#8220;Watch This Author Use A Google Document To Write And Edit A Book InÂ Real-Time&#8220;, I took the bait and headed over to &#8230; <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/work-in-progress/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11040&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347970083,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 10:49:36 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<p>This is one of the coolest things I&#8217;ve seen in a while. Â After reading this story this morning &#8220;<a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/09/18/watch-this-author-use-a-google-document-to-write-and-edit-a-book-in-real-time/\">Watch This Author Use A Google Document To Write And Edit A Book InÂ Real-Time</a>&#8220;, I took the bait and headed over to the Google Document to see it!</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1AwxZlO1uVnFFKh_NWAlZ78oK2c5gxzvVCfrYbe7EOE8/preview?pli=1&amp;sle=true#heading=h.f0dths2bdy48\">The Document</a></p>\n<p>I wasn&#8217;t alone &#8211; the Google Document gave me the warning that there were too many people accessing the document at the present time and some functionality was disabled but it was interesting to poke around anyway.</p>\n<p>How&#8217;s that for open and sharing?</p>\n<p>You&#8217;ve got to give it a peek. Â You know you want to&#8230;.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11040/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11040/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11040&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(393,0,0,'Text, email, search addiction: http://t.co/EcF2UINO MT @psychologytoday via @marciamarcia +Info Diet/Clay Johnson #lrnchat #goc3 #oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/brainysmurf1234/statuses/248035958166003712',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/brainysmurf1234/statuses/248035958166003712',NULL,NULL,29,'Text, email, search addiction: <a href=\"http://t.co/EcF2UINO\">http://t.co/EcF2UINO</a> MT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/psychologytoday\">psychologytoday</a> via @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/marciamarcia\">marciamarcia</a> +Info Diet/Clay Johnson <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23lrnchat\" title=\"#lrnchat\" class=\" \">#lrnchat</a> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23goc3\" title=\"#goc3\" class=\" \">#goc3</a> #<em>oped12</em>',1347973803,NULL,NULL,'brainysmurf1234','http://twitter.com/brainysmurf1234','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 12:29:15 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(394,3,0,'The Special Sauce of Social Learning','Diigo','http://www.learningsolutionsmag.com/articles/537/the-special-sauce-of-social-learning',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Highlights and Sticky Notes:</strong><p>Social learning will fail if the culture does not support it. No technology by \nitself can overcome a restrictive or non-existent knowledge sharing culture.</p><p><I>Our role</I>: Infuse social learning into the long-term enterprise learning \nand performance strategy</p><p>Help change the performance management process to encourage and reward knowledge \nsharing, and integrate social media and social learning into management training \nand talent management programs.</p><p><P><I>Our role</I>: Establish initial social networks and communities of \npractice around compelling tasks, problems, or other aspects of the business. \nMake sure everyone knows why the community is forming and what it hopes to \naccomplish. Then let users \"have at it.\"</P></p><p>Remove barriers to anytime, anywhere, and any device, while still making the \nwhole process as trouble-free as possible to use.</p><p><I>Our role</I>: Provide guidance and training to help people become better \nauthors, or, in some cases, understand their limitations and defer to others</p><p><I>Our role</I>: Focus more on content and design and less on the latest gizmo</p><p><p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/%22marc+j.+rosenberg%22&quot;>marc j. rosenberg</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/design&quot;>design</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/networks&quot;>networks</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/%22social+learning%22&quot;>social learning</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/leadership&quot;>leadership</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></p>',1347978723,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Tue, 18 Sep 2012 14:13:42 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','3',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(395,0,0,'RT @ahnjune: I&apos;m excited to help lead the research efforts @p2pu http://t.co/9Css9mMP msg me if you have any questions or inquiries! #oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/p2pu/statuses/248064983890538496',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/p2pu/statuses/248064983890538496',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/ahnjune\">ahnjune</a>: I&apos;m excited to help lead the research efforts @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/p2pu\">p2pu</a> <a href=\"http://t.co/9Css9mMP\">http://t.co/9Css9mMP</a> msg me if you have any questions or inquiries! #<em>oped12</em>',1347978843,NULL,NULL,'p2pu','http://twitter.com/p2pu','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 14:24:35 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(396,0,0,'finally, we have #oped12 newsletter, harvesting, aggregation working: http://t.co/4L4ejfSK . That was an ugly first week :(','twitter','http://twitter.com/gsiemens/statuses/248072884973600769',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/gsiemens/statuses/248072884973600769',NULL,NULL,29,'finally, we have #<em>oped12</em> newsletter, harvesting, aggregation working: <a href=\"http://t.co/4L4ejfSK\">http://t.co/4L4ejfSK</a> . That was an ugly first week :(',1347983882,NULL,NULL,'gsiemens','http://twitter.com/gsiemens','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 14:55:59 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(397,0,0,'A Teacher&#8217;s guide to Social Media','text/html','http://www.openclassroomonline.com/a-teachers-guide-to-social-media/','Uncategorized',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,24,'Retrieved from:Â http://www.onlinecolleges.net/2012/07/26/a-teachers-guide-to-social-media/ From: OnlineColleges.net',1347986166,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Tue, 18 Sep 2012 15:28:13 +0000',NULL,'Creating an Open Classroom',NULL,'<p>Retrieved from:Â <a href=\"http://www.onlinecolleges.net/2012/07/26/a-teachers-guide-to-social-media/\">http://www.onlinecolleges.net/2012/07/26/a-teachers-guide-to-social-media/</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.onlinecolleges.net/2012/07/26/a-teachers-guide-to-social-media/\"><img src=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/infographics/Teacher-Guide-Social-Media-800.png\" alt=\"A Teacher&apos;s Guide to Social Media\" width=\"500\" border=\"0\" /></a><br />\nFrom: <a href=\"http://www.onlinecolleges.net\">OnlineColleges.net</a></p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(398,0,0,'#mobimooc2012, Sulla condivisione degli strumenti mobili e sul curriculum mlearning','text/html','https://serenaturri.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/mobimooc2012-sulla-condivisione-degli-strumenti-mobili-e-sul-curriculum-mlearning/','mobiMOOC;competenze;condivisione;conoscenza;curriculum;lingua_inglese;mobile learning;open course;partecipazione;strumenti',NULL,NULL,20,NULL,NULL,NULL,36,'Desidero prendere in esame due fra i temi discussi nei vari forum del corso, perchÃ© piÃ¹ rispondenti ai miei attuali bisogni formativi: condivisione dei personali strumenti mobili preferiti relativi all&#8217;apprendimento perchÃ© un curriculum mobile learning. Noto che i due argomenti sono in relazioneÂ fra loro per alcune ragioni che indico e visualizzo. Gli strumenti mobili rappresentano [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=serenaturri.wordpress.com&#038;blog=9618855&#038;post=2136&#038;subd=serenaturri&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1347987364,NULL,NULL,'serenaturri','http://serenaturri.wordpress.com','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 16:42:10 +0000',NULL,'serenaturri&#039;s Blog',NULL,'<p>Desidero prendere in esame due fra i temi discussi nei vari forum del corso, perchÃ© piÃ¹ rispondenti ai miei attuali bisogni formativi:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>condivisione dei personali strumenti mobili preferiti relativi all&#8217;apprendimento</li>\n<li>perchÃ© un curriculum mobile learning.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Noto che i due argomenti sono in relazioneÂ fra loro per alcune ragioni che indico e visualizzo.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://serenaturri.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/relazioni.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2156\" title=\"relazioni\" src=\"http://serenaturri.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/relazioni.jpg?w=500&h=375\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></p>\n<p>Gli strumenti mobili rappresentano soluzioni a bisogni formativi specifici;Â  considerata la loro varietÃ ,Â richiedono l&#8217;acquisizione di cognizioni sull&#8217;argomento al fine di operare scelte conformi alle necessitÃ . Evidenziano, inoltre, come sia essenziale l&#8217; appropriazione di un lessico specifico anche in considerazione della continua comparsa di nuove parole, di frasi e abbreviazioni della tecnologia.</p>\n<p>La lettura degli interventi dei colleghi ha permesso di orientare la mia attenzione, focalizzareÂ meglio le articolazioni dei due problemi esaminati e ha suggerito riflessioni sugli effetti della condivisione sul piano dell&#8217;apprendimento.</p>\n<p>Allineando il mio comportamento alle richieste esplicitate nei forum, richiamo alla memoria gli strumenti mobili che ho usato per l&#8217;apprendimento ma che ora, pur essendo a portata di mano, utilizzo rararmente, si tratta di un Nokia 7210 col quale mi sono divertita a scattare fotografie eÂ  l&#8217;iPod con cui ho ascoltato musica e <a href=\"http://learnenglish.britishcouncil.org/en/elementary-podcasts\">English Podcast</a>. Ora sono alle prese con un HTC sensation 4G, causa prima della mia partecipazione al corso, come ho esplicitato <a href=\"https://serenaturri.wordpress.com/2012/06/13/mobilmooc/\">qui.</a></p>\n<p>Per poterÂ meglio conoscere il mio cellulare eÂ sfruttare appieno la guida all&#8217;uso incorporata nel mio HTC Sensation; sperimentare le caratteristiche e le funzioni ancora non praticate e, infine, per individuare applicazioni, rivolgendo un&#8217;attenzione particolare per quelle che sostengono l&#8217;apprendimento della lingua inglese, ho realizzato dapprima una tabella a tripla entrata, i cui indicatori sono a) caratteristiche b) descrizione c) definizione; ho provveduto quindi a cercare significati e ad inserire definizioni facendo ricorso ad alcune risorse</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:30px;\">Â * <a href=\"http://www.telefonino.net/glossario/A/index.html\">telefonino.net</a> il sito italiano d&#8217;informazione sulla telefonia</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:30px;\">* <a href=\"http://www.pianetacellulare.it/Modelli/Htc/Htc_Sensation.php\">pianeta cellulare</a> una rivista a carattere informativo, tecnico e scientifico</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:30px;\">* <a href=\"http://www.webopedia.com/quick_ref/index.asp\">WebopediaÂ  </a>dizionario</p>\n<p>Attraverso le ricerche relative al p.3,Â  ho visto confermata la convinzione che siano necessarie</p>\n<ul>\n<li>l&#8217;assunzione di un atteggiamento critico,</li>\n<li>l&#8217;acquisizione di competenze, come ho evidenziato in un <a href=\"https://serenaturri.wordpress.com/2012/08/19/mobimooc-condivisione-dei-segnalibri-tramite-delicious/\">precedente post ,</a> che permettano (anche) la prevenzione della bulimia di applicazioni.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Concludo ripensando agli effetti che ha avuto su di me la temporanea impossibilitÃ  di accedere al forum di discussione, mi riferisco alla</p>\n<ul>\n<li>comparsa di emozioni spiacevoli quali ansia, sgomento, mortificazione, senso di inadeguatezza;</li>\n<li>ricerca di soluzioni alternative;</li>\n<li>modifica della mia modalitÃ  di partecipazione nello spazio di #mobimooc12 google groups;</li>\n<li>focalizzazione su quello che nel tempo dell&#8217;attesa mi era possibile fare.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Riconosco inoltre cheÂ  proprio grazie a quell&#8217;iniziale impasse devo l&#8217; incremento della comprensione dell&#8217;affermazione di McLuhanÂ  secondo cui l&#8217;oggetto di studio dovrebbe essere il mezzo non il contenuto veicolato.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<br />Filed under: <a href=&apos;https://serenaturri.wordpress.com/category/mobimooc/&apos;>mobiMOOC</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/serenaturri.wordpress.com/2136/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/serenaturri.wordpress.com/2136/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=serenaturri.wordpress.com&#038;blog=9618855&#038;post=2136&#038;subd=serenaturri&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(399,0,0,'Open Learning is different from Open Education? #oped12 #vsmooc12 http://t.co/VzwoGe0k','twitter','http://twitter.com/monicagrossoni/statuses/248091294927298560',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/monicagrossoni/statuses/248091294927298560',NULL,NULL,29,'Open Learning is different from Open Education? #<em>oped12</em> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23vsmooc12\" title=\"#vsmooc12\" class=\" \">#vsmooc12</a> <a href=\"http://t.co/VzwoGe0k\">http://t.co/VzwoGe0k</a>',1347988923,NULL,NULL,'monicagrossoni','http://twitter.com/monicagrossoni','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 16:09:08 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(400,5,0,'Larry Lessig: Laws that choke creativity','Diigo','http://www.ted.com/talks/larry_lessig_says_the_law_is_strangling_creativity.html',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Comments:</strong><ul><li>Are we turning our kids into pirates, willing to live life against the law? \"Artist choice is the key for new technology having an oppportunity to be open for business...\" - Larry Lessig - <small><a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></small></li></ul></p><p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/creativity&quot;>creativity</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/design&quot;>design</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></p>',1347993844,NULL,NULL,NU