tml','http://apointofcontact.wordpress.com/2012/09/19/defining-openess-quick-random-thoughts/','Distance Education;#oped12;open education',NULL,NULL,17,NULL,NULL,NULL,31,'I&#8217;m still away from home with not very much internet access, but I did want to post some initial, probably very thin, thoughts on the first week of readings for the Openess in Education course. The Cathedral and Bazaar article was the most interesting, mainly because of its context of programming. I always love learning [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=apointofcontact.wordpress.com&#038;blog=9885639&#038;post=790&#038;subd=apointofcontact&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348082763,NULL,NULL,'Glenyan','http://apointofcontact.wordpress.com','Wed, 19 Sep 2012 18:27:36 +0000',NULL,'A Point of Contact','23','I&#8217;m still away from home with not very much internet access, but I did want to post some initial, probably very thin, thoughts on the first week of readings for the Openess in Education course. The Cathedral and Bazaar article was the most interesting, mainly because of its context of programming. I always love learning [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=apointofcontact.wordpress.com&#038;blog=9885639&#038;post=790&#038;subd=apointofcontact&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(434,40,0,'Open or Closed?','text/html','http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/open-or-closed',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,42,'\n    <p>\n	<p>\n<p>#oped12 In the MOOC, getting into the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://open.mooc.ca/index.html\" title=\"open.mooc.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Open.MOOC.ca</a>, I am just beginning my Masters of Education and I am new to being a &apos;researcher.&apos; It is not that I haven&apos;t always done research. &nbsp;In the f2f courses I am taking we are encouraged to use&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.eric.ed.gov/\" title=\"ERIC\" target=\"_blank\">ERIC</a>. It can only be fully accessed through our library, with a login. Of course the articles I wanted to access have &apos;limited availability&apos;, something about inadvertently giving away authors social security numbers or something. I&rsquo;m thinking about the use of restricted non open sourced peer reviewed material as a basis for scholarship.&nbsp; If it is behind a money or status firewall is it a legitimate repository for information?&nbsp; Or is it in fact biased for just this reason, out of date and incomplete or accessible only to fee paying institutions?&nbsp; Why does an author choose to do that with their work when we have creative commons?&nbsp; I understand the issue of intellectual property and the need to keep confidence, but in the interchange of ideas, limiting diversity and access, limits the insights.&nbsp; Do we have time to wait? Melting arctic ice suggests, no.</p>\n<p>A discussion of open educational resources must also consider equitable access.&nbsp; A closed system is exactly what we have had in academia since the middle ages. It is more of a cultural firewall than a real one. But why open up everything? My own theories are driven by the thought that somewhere out there someone will have a great innovation that changes everything. Perhaps it is Tellihard de Chardin echoing the world brain, the <a href=\"http://www.matrixmasters.com/spirit/html/2a/2a.html\" target=\"_blank\">noosphere.</a> Actually, that&rsquo;s it! That is why we need to open up learning resources that we have sequestered behind walls for so many years.&nbsp; Group thinking is emerging, connectivism mimics this brain activity. If we don&rsquo;t open it to everyone we miss nodes, synapses, serendipity.</p>\n</p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/open-or-closed\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/open-or-closed#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',1348084131,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Wed, 19 Sep 2012 12:41:00 -0700',NULL,'Jan&apos;s posterous','28','\n    <p>\n	<p>\n<p>#oped12 In the MOOC, getting into the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://open.mooc.ca/index.html\" title=\"open.mooc.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Open.MOOC.ca</a>, I am just beginning my Masters of Education and I am new to being a &apos;researcher.&apos; It is not that I haven&apos;t always done research. &nbsp;In the f2f courses I am taking we are encouraged to use&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.eric.ed.gov/\" title=\"ERIC\" target=\"_blank\">ERIC</a>. It can only be fully accessed through our library, with a login. Of course the articles I wanted to access have &apos;limited availability&apos;, something about inadvertently giving away authors social security numbers or something. I&rsquo;m thinking about the use of restricted non open sourced peer reviewed material as a basis for scholarship.&nbsp; If it is behind a money or status firewall is it a legitimate repository for information?&nbsp; Or is it in fact biased for just this reason, out of date and incomplete or accessible only to fee paying institutions?&nbsp; Why does an author choose to do that with their work when we have creative commons?&nbsp; I understand the issue of intellectual property and the need to keep confidence, but in the interchange of ideas, limiting diversity and access, limits the insights.&nbsp; Do we have time to wait? Melting arctic ice suggests, no.</p>\n<p>A discussion of open educational resources must also consider equitable access.&nbsp; A closed system is exactly what we have had in academia since the middle ages. It is more of a cultural firewall than a real one. But why open up everything? My own theories are driven by the thought that somewhere out there someone will have a great innovation that changes everything. Perhaps it is Tellihard de Chardin echoing the world brain, the <a href=\"http://www.matrixmasters.com/spirit/html/2a/2a.html\" target=\"_blank\">noosphere.</a> Actually, that&rsquo;s it! That is why we need to open up learning resources that we have sequestered behind walls for so many years.&nbsp; Group thinking is emerging, connectivism mimics this brain activity. If we don&rsquo;t open it to everyone we miss nodes, synapses, serendipity.</p>\n</p>\n	\n</p> <p><a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/open-or-closed\">Permalink</a>  	| <a href=\"http://blogasaurus.posterous.com/open-or-closed#comment\">Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;&raquo;</a> </p>\n   ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(435,8,0,'Slip Sliding Away: The Open in MOOC | iterating toward openness','Diigo','http://opencontent.org/blog/archives/2509',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/openness&quot;>openness</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/gsiemens&quot; title=&quot;View gsiemens &apos;s content in group&quot;>gsiemens </a></p>',1348094883,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Wed, 19 Sep 2012 22:13:45 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','8',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(436,0,0,'reading @opencontent on slip sliding away: http://t.co/dqzbFj5H #oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/gsiemens/statuses/248545607415902209',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/gsiemens/statuses/248545607415902209',NULL,NULL,29,'reading @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/opencontent\">opencontent</a> on slip sliding away: <a href=\"http://t.co/dqzbFj5H\">http://t.co/dqzbFj5H</a> #<em>oped12</em>',1348095003,NULL,NULL,'gsiemens','http://twitter.com/gsiemens','Wed, 19 Sep 2012 22:14:25 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(437,0,0,'RT @atsc: Open course in (PostGrad) Study Skills for BS