LL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(474,0,0,'Peer-review process a key incentive for faculty participation in #OER creation. #oped12 http://t.co/jM5MXiJ2','twitter','http://twitter.com/yayin_ko/statuses/248988782802657280',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/yayin_ko/statuses/248988782802657280',NULL,NULL,29,'Peer-review process a key incentive for faculty participation in <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23OER\" title=\"#OER\" class=\" \">#OER</a> creation. #<em>oped12</em> <a href=\"http://t.co/jM5MXiJ2\">http://t.co/jM5MXiJ2</a>',1348200851,NULL,NULL,'yayin_ko','http://twitter.com/yayin_ko','Fri, 21 Sep 2012 03:35:26 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(475,6,0,'OER Myths','Diigo','https://openeducationalresources.pbworks.com/w/page/25228307/OER%20Myths',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Comments:</strong><ul><li>Perspective/studies from JISC on the sharing myth and an OER metaphor to explore the roles in the production, use/reuse. - <small><a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/westdanam&quot; title=&quot;View Dana West&apos;s content in group&quot;>Dana West</a></small></li></ul></p><p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/OER&quot;>OER</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/oped12&quot;>oped12</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/MDDE622&quot;>MDDE622</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/westdanam&quot; title=&quot;View Dana West&apos;s content in group&quot;>Dana West</a></p>',1348205763,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fri, 21 Sep 2012 05:09:28 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','6',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(476,0,0,'OTR Links 09/21/2012','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/21/otr-links-09212012/','Links',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'Let&#8217;s help people understand that WordPress is not a company &#8211; WPMU.org &#8220;This week I want to talk about WordPress and how people sometimes misinterpret it. Some people, more that you&apos;d imagine I&apos;d wager, seems to think that WordPress is &#8230; <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/21/otr-links-09212012/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11060&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348207203,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Fri, 21 Sep 2012 05:30:35 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<ul class=\"diigo-linkroll\">\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://wpmu.org/lets-help-people-understand-that-wordpress-is-not-a-company/\">Let&#8217;s help people understand that WordPress is not a company &#8211; WPMU.org</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;This week I want to talk about WordPress and how people sometimes misinterpret it. Some people, more that you&apos;d imagine I&apos;d wager, seems to think that WordPress is a company. \"WordPress releases live blogging theme\", \"the latest plugins from WordPress\", and similar misunderstandings show up every now and then, sometimes on big time tech sites that honestly should know better.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/help\">help</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/people\">people</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/wordpress\">wordpress</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/company\">company</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/wpmu\">wpmu</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/org\">org</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.educatorstechnology.com/2012/09/ios6-simplified-for-educators.html\">iOS6 Simplified for Educators</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Apple has recently released iOS6. This is the latest and most recent and probably the most performing Â operating system out there. I personally liked its features and thought I might provide you with a little review in case you want to upgrade to it.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ios\">ios</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/educators\">educators</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://52tiger.net/guided-access-for-iphone-and-ipad-will-benefit-teachers-and-parents/\">Guided Access for iPhone and iPad will benefit teachers and parents | 52 Tiger</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Apple&apos;s iOS 6 introduces a feature that will benefit teachers and parents alike. Guided Access is a new accessibility functionÂ on the iPhone and iPad thatÂ lets you disable certain controls within an app and prevents kids from navigating away. When I was a special ed. teacher, I would have loved something like this.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/guided\">guided</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/access\">access</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/iphone\">iphone</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ipad\">ipad</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/will\">will</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/benefit\">benefit</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/parents\">parents</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tiger\">tiger</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://mrsmoandtechnology.posterous.com/engaging-with-nearpod-22957\">Engaging with NearPod! &#8211; The Thinkings of Mrs. Mo</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;What to know about an app that will increase student engagement? Nearpod&#8230;learning through interactive, multimedia presentations! Thanks to @dteahon and @phillipshuskies, I have been actively utilizing this app to actively engage students and give informal assessments throughout my lessons. Here is what occurs:&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/nearpod\">nearpod</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ipod\">ipod</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ipad\">ipad</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://learninginhand.com/blog/limit-an-ios-device-to-running-a-single-app.html\">Tony Vincent&#8217;s Learning in Hand &#8211; Blog &#8211; Limit an iOS Device to Running a SingleÂ App</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Locking a mobile device into a single app has been a request of parents and educators for some time. Using Guided Access to limit an iPad, iPhone, or iPod touch to one app can be handy when you want a child to remain on task and focused. It is also nice for youngsters who might accidentally click the Home button.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tony\">tony</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/vincent\">vincent</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/learning\">learning</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/hand\">hand</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/blog\">blog</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/limit\">limit</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ios\">ios</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/device\">device</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/running\">running</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/single\">single</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/app\">app</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://edudemic.com/2012/09/feedback-feeds-evolution/\">Why Teachers Should Seek Feedback (Whether They Want To Or Not)</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;I have evolved as a educator since my beginnings as a teacher back in 2001. I have evolved as a leader since my beginnings as an AP six years ago. I have evolved even more since becoming a principal 4 years ago. With time, and with feedback, change should happen as long as said feedback is used. However, one must be willing to change in order for change to occur.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/feedback\">feedback</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://blogs.kqed.org/mindshift/2012/09/where-do-educational-games-come-from/\">Where Do Educational Games Come From? | MindShift</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Increasingly, digital games are cropping up everywhere in education. And that&apos;s stimulated a flurry of activity leading to the expectation that no longer are learning games only likely to come from traditional education companies, but a wide variety of sources.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/educational games\">educational games</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/games\">games</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.fractuslearning.com/2012/09/19/tips-tweeting-teachers/\">Top Tips for Tweeting Teachers</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Since the advent of e-learning and PLNs (personal learning networks), tech-savvy teachers have turned in their droves to the social networking site Twitter. But whilst the site provides a host of useful #edtech functions, from networking and making connections to sharing great new resources, some teachers are undeniably more successful at harnessing its power than others. Here are our top tips for how to be a great tweeting teacher...&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tips\">tips</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.educatorstechnology.com/2012/09/a-great-new-collection-of-educational.html\">A Great New Collection of Educational Posters for Teachers</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Educational Technology and Mobile Learning is back to you with a Â list of some awesome Â inspirational posters that you as a teacher would really enjoy and hopefully hang on your classroom wall. They can also be equally inspirational for your students. I am definitely adding these posters to the section we created here under the title : &#8220; Educational Posters for Teachers &#8220;.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/great\">great</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/collection\">collection</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/posters\">posters</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://edudemic.com/2012/09/the-50-best-ipad-apps-for-students-with-reading-disabilities/\">50 Useful Apps For Students With Reading Disabilities</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Here, we highlight just a few of the amazing apps out there that can help students with a reading disability improve their skills not only in reading, writing, and spelling, but also get a boost in confidence and learn to see school as a fun, engaging activity, not a struggle.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/reading\">reading</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/apps\">apps</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/disabilities\">disabilities</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://mashable.com/2012/09/19/e-reader-infographic/\">Are Books Doomed? The Rise of the e-Reader [INFOGRAPHIC]</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;According to the infographic below, people who own e-book devices say they read more than people who don&apos;t, at a rate of 24 books per year to 15. Education, escape, relaxation and entertainment rank as people&apos;s main motivations to plow through books - proving that, whether electronically or via dead tree, reading remains a popular pastime.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/books\">books</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/rise\">rise</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infographic\">infographic</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.howtogeek.com/124814/the-history-of-digital-storage-infographic/\">The History of Digital Storage [Infographic] &#8211; How-To Geek</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">This history of storage media</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://socialmediatoday.com/kratzpr/822601/5-tips-creating-infographic-people-actually-want-read\">5 Tips to Creating an Infographic People Actually Want to Read | Social Media Today</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Unless you&apos;ve been living under a rock (or still have WebTV like my grandparents&#8230;) you surely have across at least a few infographics over the last couple years. While they are still popular and widely shared, many people feel that they are being over-produced and often lazily executed. That said, an infographic can still be widly successful on many levels if done right and organized strategically where the audience benefits from the information and story you are telling. From my experience in producing several widely shared infographics for MBA@UNC, here are five tips on how to create a great infographic:&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tips\">tips</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/creating\">creating</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infographic\">infographic</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/people\">people</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/to read\">to read</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/social\">social</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/social media\">social media</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/media\">media</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.neowin.net/news/microsoft-fixes-ie-security-hole-another-update-on-friday\">Microsoft fixes IE security hole; another update on Friday &#8211; Neowin</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Microsoft has moved quickly to fix an exploit that was discovered a few days ago in some versions of its Internet Explorer web browser. The hole was already being used by hackers to deliver a malware program via a Flash issue on IE7, IE8, and IE9 on Windows XP, Vista, and 7.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/microsoft\">microsoft</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/fixes\">fixes</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/security\">security</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/hole\">hole</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/update\">update</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/friday\">friday</a></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"diigo-ps\">Posted from <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com&apos;>Diigo</a>. The rest of my favorite links are <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete&apos;>here</a>.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11060/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11060/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11060&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(477,0,0,'Social Media Rules &#8211; Business','text/html','http://www.openclassroomonline.com/social-media-rules-business/','Uncategorized',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,24,'I am reflecting upon how these &#8220;Social Media Rules&#8221; apply to Education as well. Retrieved from:Â http://www.mediabistro.com/alltwitter/social-media-rules_b27799',1348208167,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fri, 21 Sep 2012 05:41:04 +0000',NULL,'Creating an Open Classroom',NULL,'<p>I am reflecting upon how these &#8220;Social Media Rules&#8221; apply to Education as well.</p>\n<p>Retrieved from:Â <a href=\"http://www.mediabistro.com/alltwitter/social-media-rules_b27799\">http://www.mediabistro.com/alltwitter/social-media-rules_b27799</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.openclassroomonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/36-rules-social-media.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-51\" title=\"36-rules-social-media\" src=\"http://www.openclassroomonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/36-rules-social-media-826x1024.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"793\" /></a></p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(478,7,0,'Education in Finland: smart, continuous development (a bit like agile software development)','Diigo','http://flosse.blogging.fi/2011/10/12/education-in-finland-smart-continuos-development-a-bit-like-agile-software-development/',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Comments:</strong><ul><li>Here&apos;s a perspective on the Finnish education system from someone who also has a view towards open and free software in education. Suggests we all take a cue from agile software development to improve our own <sub your locale>educational culture/system.</sub> - <small><a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/westdanam&quot; title=&quot;View Dana West&apos;s content in group&quot;>Dana West</a></small></li></ul></p><p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/MDDE622&quot;>MDDE622</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/agile&quot;>agile</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/oped12&quot;>oped12</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/westdanam&quot; title=&quot;View Dana West&apos;s content in group&quot;>Dana West</a></p>',1348210823,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fri, 21 Sep 2012 06:19:50 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','7',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(479,0,0,'RT @AnneHole: RT @goldsmithsleu: Introduction to Openness in Education: An open online course led by David Wiley. http://t.co/1Ird50yA b ...','twitter','http://twitter.com/dieGoerelebt/statuses/249075079487561728',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/dieGoerelebt/statuses/249075079487561728',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/AnneHole\">AnneHole</a>: RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/goldsmithsleu\">goldsmithsleu</a>: Introduction to Openness in Education: An open online course led by David Wiley. <a href=\"http://t.co/1Ird50yA\">http://t.co/1Ird50yA</a> b ...',1348221003,NULL,NULL,'dieGoerelebt','http://twitter.com/dieGoerelebt','Fri, 21 Sep 2012 09:18:21 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(480,0,0,'An Interview with Shannon Smith','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/21/an-interview-with-shannon-smith/','Computers;ECOO;Education;learning;Read/Write Web;Doug;ontario;Ottawa Carleton District School Board;Shannon;Special education;wordpress',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'I first met Shannon at an OTF Professional Learning event but we stayed in touch over the years through our use of Social Media. Â While at the event, we agreed upon the need for global connections, but we both could &#8230; <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/21/an-interview-with-shannon-smith/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11057&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348222324,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Fri, 21 Sep 2012 09:00:18 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<p>I first met Shannon at an OTF Professional Learning event but we stayed in touch over the years through our use of Social Media. Â While at the event, we agreed upon the need for global connections, but we both could see the need to push for something uniquely Ontario. Â This fall, Shannon assumes the role of Principal at <a href=\"http://glencairnps.ca/\">Glen Cairn Public School </a>in the Ottawa Carleton District School Board. Â I used this as an opportunity to interview her as she makes this big, exciting move.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â Congratulations on the appointment to Principal at Glen Cairn. Â This must be an exciting time for you.</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â Thanks, Doug. Â This is indeed a very exciting time for me. Â I am still amazed at how lucky I am to be a Principal in a really progressive district here in Ontario. Â </p>\n<p>Doug: Â Your background is strong as a Special Education teacher before entering administration. Â What unique attributes do you bring to the school because of this?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â That is a tough one because I cannot imagine any educator not having the same high level of commitment to every student &#8211; those who struggle as well as those for whom school comes easily. Â I can say that having a daughter with a developmental disability drew me to Special Education and I think that she has had a greater impact on my philosophy than any level of specialist training I hold. Â </p>\n<p>Having said that, as a Special Education teacher, you are afforded many opportunities to work with families who are going through difficult times. Â Every single time I sit with a family who is learning, perhaps for the first time, that their child is \"different\" from typical children, I am keenly aware of what that experience can feel like. Â I have learned so much from sitting and listening to parents as they share their fears, their hopes and their love for their child. Â </p>\n<p>Doug: Â A while back, I had written the post \"<a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/03/22/your-school-doesnt-need-a-newsletter/\">Your School Doesn&apos;t Need a Newsletter</a>\". Â When I visit the Glen Cairn website, I see icons for Twitter, Facebook, Flickr, Pinterest, and YouTube. Â is this a sign that you&apos;re prepared to go paperless?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â Glen Cairn PS had made some moves towards less paper before my arrival. Â They did away with agendas in favour of online homework calendars (google) and a few teachers already have blogs. Â I will still send home paper notices from time to time, but I do plan to rely quite heavily on digital means for communication. Â We are using our blog and those other services you mention, as well as weekly synrevoice messages (email and automated phone calls). Â After speaking with staff at GCPS, I discovered that a very small percentage of families do not have access to the internet at home and this is why I plan to use a combination of paper and digital communication.</p>\n<p>The more important shift for me is from broadcast only to two-way communication. Â Digital communication facilitates this, if used effectively. Â The caveat is that communication with the learning community must invite participation. Â Using blogs and social media will only be \"old wine in new bottles\" if we don&apos;t also shift to engaging in dialogue. Â It is not enough to broadcast what you are doing. Â We know that parents play a key role in supporting learning, and so whatever choices I make around communication channels, I must look for ways to draw the community into discussions and decision-making.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â Related to this, do you see eBooks and electronic textbooks in Glen Cairn&apos;s future?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â Great question. Â GCPS is about to transition from a K &#8211; 8 school to a middle school next year. Â There are many decisions to be made and I intend to have staff involved in making decisions related to our future. Â Personally, I like to offer a variety of types of learning materials. Â I don&apos;t feel a huge need for e-textbooks because I think that textbooks are too linear and limited. Â I would prefer to spend that money on teachers &#8212; supporting staff who want to try new approaches, acquire tools that they will use meaningfully with students. Â If someone wants to try something new, I want to be in a position to support that.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â Glen Cairn is located in the heart of Kanata, one of Canada&apos;s high technology centres. Â Does this put extra importance on the use of technology effectively at the school?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â I don&apos;t know if it puts additional importance, but it may mean that we have some parents who are quite accustomed to using technology in innovative ways. Â It is critical that we foster digital literacy within our students, regardless of where the school is situated.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â Is or will Glen Cairn be a BYOT school? Â What do you see as the possibilities for this? Â Is there a concern that some students will not bring technology of their own to school?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â Students in intermediate grades will have the opportunity to use their own technology at school. Â This is our first year with wireless, so there is going to be a learning curve. Â If students are unable to bring technology, they will not be left out because we will make it a priority to ensure that everyone has access. Â Stay tuned as we move into BYOD!</p>\n<p>Doug: Â There may come a time when you add additional staff members to your school. Â How important is a strong technical background coming into the position?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â I will be adding many new staff members next year, as we are projected to double in size when we transition to being a middle school. Â You can bet that a strong interest and comfort level with technology will be an asset. Â I will be looking for teachers who are master learners first and foremost. Â I have already begun conversations with staff members who will stay when we make the change to explore what strengths we already have and what gaps will need to be filled. Â For instance, we have an instrumental music teacher and a Core French teacher with a strong Visual Arts background. Â We will be looking for individuals with strong backgrounds in Math, Literacy, Science and Physical Education. Â We intend to link with our neighbouring High School whenever possible and I believe that a solid comfort level with connective technologies will play a key role in that relationship.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â Will you do a Social Media \"check\" of applicants?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â I will pay added attention to individuals who highlight a positive digital footprint in their application. Â I have pondered the \"check\" quite a bit and I don&apos;t think at this time that I would do that. Â I must admit though, that I do expect an applicant to have spent some time researching the school online and to be able to articulate, based on what he or she finds, how she or he will compliment the school team.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â I note that the Glen Cairn website is created using WordPress whereas other OCDSB websites are templates from Sharepoint. Â What do you see as the advantage of a web presence this way?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â Nice catch! Â I am a wordpress gal. Â I tried google sites this summer and just couldn&apos;t get the site to do what I wanted. Â I want strong social integration. Â I want it to look pretty and I want it to be very accessible. Â I have to admit I don&apos;t know much about the inner workings of Sharepoint, but I found the template very limiting. Â I like easy and seamless.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â One of my favourite Ontario blogs has always been \"ShannonInOttawa\". Â You&apos;ve been very transparent with your learnings there. Â Will that continue? Â Will there be a \"ShannonThePrincipalInOttawa\" blog instead?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Thanks, Doug. Â I will keep with ShannoninOttawa, although I anticipate many cross-posts to <a href=\"http://glencairnps.ca/\">http://glencairnps.ca</a> because I intend to share my personal learnings there too. Â I think that posting my own learning on the school blog might engage parents, students and staff in conversations about learning. Â I also think that when I share about my own learning, I model what I expect of all members of the school community. Â I will look for feedback and pushback too, although I know it will likely take some time for community members to feel safe engaging in those conversations online. Â </p>\n<p>Doug: Â In your new position, you will not have the assistance of a vice-principal. Â Can your use of technology help with this? Â How?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Yes! Â In a sense I am filling two positions this year &#8211; principal and vice-principal. Â Within those roles I wear many other hats. Â I rely heavily on technology to keep me organized, to help me stay current in my professional reading and lead the instructional program, and to build relationships and communicate with my community. Â </p>\n<p>I stay organized with a google calendar. Â My husband is also a Principal in our District and we have two children (Violet is 12 and Donovan is 10). Â We have swimming lessons, skating, dancing, skiing. Â We have 2 staff meetings and 2 parent council meetings every month. Â I also have many meetings with parents, community members and professionals every week, as well as District PLCs and operations meetings. Â The google calendar is indispensable. Â </p>\n<p>I subscribe to many blog feeds with my google reader and I check it from time to time to stay current on what others are saying about education around the world. Â I use Diigo to bookmark and share great finds on the web and I also use twitter to share. Â That way, I can go back and find the gems when I want to reference them, either in a blog post, or a PD session with staff or community.</p>\n<p>I blog to share and solicit feedback on my thinking and vision. Â I think that adopting a stance of openness has given me some initial credibility within the GCPS learning community. Â I hope that as we head into a fairly large change process, that trust will continue to grow. Â I expect push back too, because that is all part of engaging in honest dialogue. Â And while the face to face conversations are real, connections that happen withÂ Social media can be a great starting point.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â You&apos;ve been a leadership voice in the Connected Principals initiative. Â <a href=\"http://connectedprincipals.com/\">http://connectedprincipals.com/</a> Â Now that you&apos;ll be attending principals meetings and professional learning opportunities, do you see the Ottawa Carleton influence growing?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â I hope so. Â There are many leaders in the OCDSB beginning to \"get\" the benefits of connected learning and leadership. Â I believe that we are about to see a \"tipping point\" within leadership across the province as more school leaders realize the power of harnessing technology across all domains of leadership, from instruction to relationship building.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â Bizarre as it may seem this early in your stint, there will come a time when you move from Glen Cairn. Â In the sentence, \"We remember Mrs. Smith when she was principal. Â She was responsible for ...&#8230;\", how would you like to complete that sentence?</p>\n<p>Shannon: \"... helping us to have a smooth transition to a middle school environment\". Â That is my priority at this point.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â One last question &#8212; you&apos;re speaking at the ECOO Conference in October. Â Can you give us a preview and inspiration to circle your sessions on our calendars?</p>\n<p>Shannon: Â I will be speaking in two different sessions. Â The first is called, \"Innovation or Novelty?\" and it will be a lively discussion amongst participants, co-hosted by my husband, Brent Smith (@OttawaBrent). Â Our aim is to tease out some of our beliefs around the role of technology with regards to fostering innovation, creativity and critical thinking in schools. Â What role does tinkering play in the classroom? Â Is there a space for playing around, or should we be demanding more rigour in our learning environments? Â </p>\n<p>For the second session I will join Brian Harrison (@bharrisonp) to explore how we can use personal devices to capture, document and celebrate learning. Â This session will look at how we can provide timely feedback to students and parents and streamline some of our assessment practices using smartphones and other \"pocket\" technologies.</p>\n<p>Doug: Â Thanks for your time and your thoughts. Â I wish you all the best in your new setting and hope to see that you find the time to continue the online leadership that you have provided in the past.</p>\n<p>You can follow Shannon&apos;s education thoughts at <a href=\"http://www.shannoninottawa.ca\">http://www.shannoninottawa.ca</a>.</p>\n<h6 class=\"zemanta-related-title\" style=\"font-size:1em;\">Related articles</h6>\n<ul class=\"zemanta-article-ul\">\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/08/31/this-week-in-ontario-edublogs-30/\" target=\"_blank\">This Week in Ontario Edublogs</a> (dougpete.wordpress.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/14/an-interview-with-brenda-sherry-and-peter-skillen/\" target=\"_blank\">An Interview with Brenda Sherry and Peter Skillen</a> (dougpete.wordpress.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/08/20/an-interview-with-royan-lee/\" target=\"_blank\">An Interview with Royan Lee</a> (dougpete.wordpress.com)</li>\n</ul>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11057/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11057/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11057&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(481,0,0,'Reshared post from Peter Sipes:','text/html','https://plus.google.com/110117137800261731479/posts/e6vfAVtQpTa',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'What a brilliant man! #education Â  #onlineeducation Â  #mooc Â <hr/><p><strong><a href=&apos;https://plus.google.com/105985614558366179588/posts/B6rAfEGXe6s&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Original Post</a> from <a href=&apos;https://plus.google.com/105985614558366179588&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Peter Sipes</a>:</strong></p><p>Astonishing. I sometimes think about the future and never see things like this. Maybe he thought about the future more than I do. How could he have guessed at the direction of learning and schools like that?<br /><br />Oh, and the guy could write too.</p><p class=&apos;attachment video&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8ZmFEFO72gA&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=http%3A%2F%2Fi1.ytimg.com%2Fvi%2F8ZmFEFO72gA%2Fhqdefault.jpg&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/>Isaac Asimov predicted the Internet of today 20 years ago</a>\n									</p>',1348231325,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fri, 21 Sep 2012 13:53:06 +0200',NULL,'CDATA(0)',NULL,'What a brilliant man! #education Â  #onlineeducation Â  #mooc Â <hr/><p><strong><a href=&apos;https://plus.google.com/105985614558366179588/posts/B6rAfEGXe6s&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Original Post</a> from <a href=&apos;https://plus.google.com/105985614558366179588&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Peter Sipes</a>:</strong></p><p>Astonishing. I sometimes think about the future and never see things like this. Maybe he thought about the future more than I do. How could he have guessed at the direction of learning and schools like that?<br /><br />Oh, and the guy could write too.</p><p class=&apos;attachment video&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8ZmFEFO72gA&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=http%3A%2F%2Fi1.ytimg.com%2Fvi%2F8ZmFEFO72gA%2Fhqdefault.jpg&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/>Isaac Asimov predicted the Internet of today 20 years ago</a>\n									</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(482,0,0,'Process and products: thoughts on Oped12 week 2 http://t.co/Ggc9hsRM','twitter','http://twitter.com/AnneHole/statuses/249132924107120640',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/AnneHole/statuses/249132924107120640',NULL,NULL,29,'Process and products: thoughts on <em>Oped12</em> week 2 <a href=\"http://t.co/Ggc9hsRM\">http://t.co/Ggc9hsRM</a>',1348236123,NULL,NULL,'AnneHole','http://twitter.com/AnneHole','Fri, 21 Sep 2012 13:08:12 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(483,0,0,'Interesting comments on Slashdot http://t.co/ir76x7Tg  re AngryMath&apos;s  Udacity Statistics 101 review at http://t.co/b708c7VY  #oped12 #mooc','twitter','http://twitter.com/ifrank/statuses/249126917339480064',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/ifrank/statuses/249126917339480064',NULL,NULL,29,'Interesting comments on Slashdot <a href=\"http://t.co/ir76x7Tg\">http://t.co/ir76x7Tg</a> re AngryMath&apos;s Udacity Statistics 101 review at <a href=\"http://t.co/b708c7VY\">http://t.co/b708c7VY</a> #<em>oped12</em> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23mooc\" title=\"#mooc\" class=\" \">#mooc</a>',1348236123,NULL,NULL,'ifrank','http://twitter.com/ifrank','Fri, 21 Sep 2012 12:44:20 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(484,26,0,'Process and products: thoughts on Oped12 week 2','text/html','http://annehole.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/process-and-products-thoughts-on-oped12-week-2/','Uncategorized;#oped12',NULL,NULL,2,NULL,NULL,NULL,7,'As George Siemens acknowledged in his video intro to week 2, the openness in education MOOC didn&#8217;t get off to a great start. For me, the combination of emails not arriving, no blogs to engage with, inaccessible readings and the &#8230; <a href=\"http://annehole.wordpress.com/2012/09/18/process-and-products-thoughts-on-oped12-week-2/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=annehole.wordpress.com&#038;blog=38332438&#038;post=144&#038;subd=annehole&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348236483,NULL,NULL,'annehole','http://annehole.wordpress.com','Tue, 18 Sep 2012 17:07:52 +0000',NULL,'Teaching Talk','15','<p>As George Siemens acknowledged in his video intro to week 2, the openness in education MOOC didn&#8217;t get off to a great start. For me, the combination of emails not arriving, no blogs to engage with, inaccessible readings and the fact that I was on holiday meant that I didn&#8217;t really engage much last week. I am hoping to make up for that this week. </p>\n<p>A significant part of my interest in taking this MOOC was to experience the tools for this type of course and online peer learning in a more focused way that in my usual PLN which is based around Google plus and Twitter. So this week I really want to read other people&#8217;s blogs and make some comments, but first I want to do some more reading.</p>\n<p>Talking of tools, I am trying to do this whole thing digitally on my Android tablet so am starting with the readings that are downloadable as pdfs because these I can easily annotate with <a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=udk.android.reader&amp;hl=en\">EZpdf reader</a> which seems the &#8216;natural&#8217; way for me to engage with a text. I realise this is very rooted in my experience as a student in the 90s when scribbling on photocopies of chapters and papers was the most common way to work in my discipline area (literature and gender studies). When I have done the pdf readings it will be interesting to see how I can engage with Web-based readings. This is important for me to think about because in my day to day practice as an education developer I am frequently referring colleagues to Web pages (including ones I have created) without thinking too much about how the &#8216;reading&#8217; of such resources might differ from more traditional reading such as journal articles (though of course these too are often online these days).<br />\nLater&#8230;I actually found a <a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.nop.urltopdf&amp;hl=en\">URL-to-pdf Android app</a> so all my reading and annotating is now happening in EZpdf reader but still want to think about how people might be reading the materials I am creating. That&#8217;s one for the to-do list!</p>\n<p>I am intrigued that the Open University is to be used as an example because much as I love the OU, which got me started on Higher Education in the 80s, I am thinking back to the rather stringent definition of &#8216;open&#8217; we read last week and am not convinced that the OU I experienced met the requirements &#8211; although there were no formal entry requirements, the fees were (even then) quite considerable and the course materials were copyrighted&#8230;.. Having now read the piece on the history of the OU I am not sure that their materials are OERs, or at least not all of them. There are some free &#8216;openlearn&#8217; courses in recent years, but I am not sure whether they are copyrighted in a restrictive way. And are open access TV programmes produced by a university any more OERs than any TV documentary?</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"www.connectivism.ca/?p=111\">Cute Kitten Syndrome blog post by Stephen Downes</a> from 4 years ago was interesting in that it still seemed relevant, suggesting that the OER movement may not actually be moving very much or very fast. Apart from the sudden glut of MOOCs there does not seem to be a rush for HEIs to produce or use a wide range of OERs. I have seen YouTube lectures which seem as much about marketing as education and examples of digitizing archive materials to improve access (which seems like great idea for opening up research to students) but, at least in the UK there does not seem to be much use of OERs in HE teaching. In all my interactions with faculty I have only come across one or two people using such resources (a lab simulation from <a href=\"http://www.merlot.org/merlot/index.htm\">MERLOT</a> and <a href=\"http://webphysics.davidson.edu/Applets/about-physlets.html\">Physlets</a>) as part of teaching practice. As both of these examples are from the hard sciences I wonder if there is a disciplinary split going on here, with digitization of archives/resources on one hand and use of simulations/learning objects on the other? I would be interested to know whether anyone else has observed a humanities/science split in the use of OERs. </p>\n<p>Now I am off to do two things. First, to read and engage with some other #oped12 blogs and second, to think a bit more about what I wanted to get from this MOOC and what it wanted me to get from it (learning outcomes) and how either of us is going to evaluate / assess that.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/annehole.wordpress.com/144/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/annehole.wordpress.com/144/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=annehole.wordpress.com&#038;blog=38332438&#038;post=144&#038;subd=annehole&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(485,7,0,'The 60-Second Guide To Teaching With Tablets','Diigo','http://edudemic.com/2012/08/teaching-with-tablets/',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/infographic&quot;>infographic</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/tablet&quot;>tablet</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/design&quot;>design</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></p>',1348241043,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fri, 21 Sep 2012 14:48:59 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','7',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(486,5,0,'25 Ways To Use Twitter To Improve Your Professional Development','Diigo','http://edudemic.com/2012/09/25-ways-to-use-twitter-to-improve-your-professional-development/',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/twitter&quot;>twitter</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/design&quot;>design</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/networks&quot;>networks</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></p>',1348241043,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fri, 21 Sep 2012 14:45:38 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','5',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(487,0,0,'&#x201c;Mock MOOCS?&#x201d; Where do we fit in? TLTGroup&apos;s FridayLive! online free http://t.co/C2QAz412 Sept21 2pmET #TLTGfrlv #oped12 #moocmooc','twitter','http://twitter.com/ifrank/statuses/249165366310350849',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/ifrank/statuses/249165366310350849',NULL,NULL,29,'&#x201c;Mock MOOCS?&#x201d; Where do we fit in? TLTGroup&apos;s FridayLive! online free <a href=\"http://t.co/C2QAz412\">http://t.co/C2QAz412</a> Sept21 2pmET <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23TLTGfrlv\" title=\"#TLTGfrlv\" class=\" \">#TLTGfrlv</a> #<em>oped12</em> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23moocmooc\" title=\"#moocmooc\" class=\" \">#moocmooc</a>',1348241163,NULL,NULL,'ifrank','http://twitter.com/ifrank','Fri, 21 Sep 2012 15:17:07 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(488,0,0,'25 ways to use Twitter to improve your professional devmt. http://t.co/hJgHwZc9 MT @bonstewart #lrnchat #goc3 #oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/brainysmurf1234/statuses/249155083466584064',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/brainysmurf1234/statuses/249155083466584064',NULL,NULL,29,'25 ways to use Twitter to improve your professional devmt. <a href=\"http://t.co/hJgHwZc9\">http://t.co/hJgHwZc9</a> MT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/bonstewart\">bonstewart</a> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23lrnchat\" title=\"#lrnchat\" class=\" \">#lrnchat</a> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23goc3\" title=\"#goc3\" class=\" \">#goc3</a> #<em>oped12</em>',1348241163,NULL,NULL,'brainysmurf1234','http://twitter.com/brainysmurf1234','Fri, 21 Sep 2012 14:36:15 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(489,41,0,'I&apos;m glad someone else said it, so I don&apos;t have to be the bad guy. Quote: \"not only is this suppos...','text/html','https://plus.google.com/110117137800261731479/posts/SAhJnTVLx6s',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'I&#39;m glad someone else said it, so I don&#39;t have to be the bad guy.Quote: &quot;not only is this supposed to be a MOOC, but it&apos;s supposed to be a MOOC about openness in education, and there is literally no content on the website.&quot;Â Now, this is where it gets creepy:Quote from Stephen Downes in the comments section: &quot;I&#39;m not running the course, though of course I&#39;m handling the technical aspects of the platform. Typically we would have a separate page full of content - links, etc. - for each week, but they didn&#39;t want that. As [another post] suggests, it may be that there isn&#39;t any content&quot;.And it gets even creepier:How did I find out? From a Twitter post by George Siemens himself:&quot;reading @opencontent on slip sliding away: http://opencontent.org/blog/archives/2509 ... #oped12 &quot;https://twitter.com/gsiemens/status/248545607415902209 #oped12 Â <p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://opencontent.org/blog/archives/2509&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Slip Sliding Away: The Open in MOOC | iterating toward openness</a>\n									</p>',1348241405,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fri, 21 Sep 2012 15:05:02 +0200',NULL,'CDATA(0)','22','I&#39;m glad someone else said it, so I don&#39;t have to be the bad guy.Quote: &quot;not only is this supposed to be a MOOC, but it&apos;s supposed to be a MOOC about openness in education, and there is literally no content on the website.&quot;Â Now, this is where it gets creepy:Quote from Stephen Downes in the comments section: &quot;I&#39;m not running the course, though of course I&#39;m handling the technical aspects of the platform. Typically we would have a separate page full of content - links, etc. - for each week, but they didn&#39;t want that. As [another post] suggests, it may be that there isn&#39;t any content&quot;.And it gets even creepier:How did I find out? From a Twitter post by George Siemens himself:&quot;reading @opencontent on slip sliding away: http://opencontent.org/blog/archives/2509 ... #oped12 &quot;https://twitter.com/gsiemens/status/248545607415902209 #oped12 Â <p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://opencontent.org/blog/archives/2509&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Slip Sliding Away: The Open in MOOC | iterating toward openness</a>\n									</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(490,4,0,'Peer review essential for faculty participation in OER','Diigo','http://ojs.stanford.edu/ojs/index.php/a2k/article/view/445/271',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Comments:</strong><ul><li>from @yayin_ko on tiwtter - <small><a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/janherder&quot; title=&quot;View Jan Herder&apos;s content in group&quot;>Jan Herder</a></small></li></ul></p><p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/MDDE622&quot;>MDDE622</a>, <a