ugpete/apple\">apple</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/iphone\">iphone</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://ozgekaraoglu.edublogs.org/2012/09/24/youtube-new-interactive-quiz-feature/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=twitter&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+edublogs%2FNRsj+(Ozge+Karaoglu&apos;s+Blog)\">Ozge Karaoglu&#8217;s Blog &#8211; Youtube: New Interactive Quiz Feature</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">RT @shellterrell: Youtube: New Interactive Quiz Feature http://t.co/q6j44koY via @ozge #edtech</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/edtech\">edtech</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://teacherleaders.typepad.com/the_tempered_radical/2012/09/marzano-guaranteedcurriculum-atplc.html\">Do YOU Have 23 Years with YOUR Students? [SLIDE] &#8211; The Tempered Radical</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Do YOU Have 23 Years with YOUR Students? [SLIDE] &#8211; The Tempered Radical &#8211; http://t.co/T87gDm1l</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/students\">students</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/curriculum\">curriculum</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/toonfun-cartoon-fx-camera/id559845865?mt=8\">ToonFun &#8211; Cartoon Fx Camera for iPhone 3GS, iPhone 4, iPhone 4S, iPhone 5, iPod touch (3rd generation), iPod touch (4th generation), iPod touch (5th generation) and iPad on the iTunes App Store</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">RT @tcea: More free iOS apps today: Homework Stopwatch http://t.co/lpmmM8Lc; KiddyU HD http://t.co/3wX0ejr4; ToonFun http://t.co/v36XaqjD</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/cartoons\">cartoons</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ipad\">ipad</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/drawing\">drawing</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/kiddyu-hd-kid-university/id404518160?mt=8\">KiddyU HD (Kid University) for iPad on the iTunes App Store</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">RT @tcea: More free iOS apps today: Homework Stopwatch http://t.co/lpmmM8Lc; KiddyU HD http://t.co/3wX0ejr4; ToonFun http://t.co/v36XaqjD</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/homework-stopwatch-hd/id440245477?mt=8\">Homework Stopwatch HD for iPad on the iTunes App Store</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">RT @tcea: More free iOS apps today: Homework Stopwatch http://t.co/lpmmM8Lc; KiddyU HD http://t.co/3wX0ejr4; ToonFun http://t.co/v36XaqjD</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.technologytell.com/apple/102544/free-ipad-apps-for-note-taking/\">Free iPad apps for note taking | AppleTell</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">RT @ron_mill: Free iPad apps for note taking &#8211; AppleTell http://t.co/jwOsacmp via @Zite</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/notes\">notes</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/notetaking\">notetaking</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://crave.cnet.co.uk/software/ios-6-maps-vs-ios-5-maps-vs-android-maps-50009259/\">iOS 6 Maps vs iOS 5 Maps vs Android Maps | CNET UK</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Apple is taking some flak for ditching Google&#8217;s Map data in its latest iOS 6 update, with its own-brand replacement quickly becoming a hilarious Internet meme. But exactly how does Maps in iOS 6 compare to Maps in iOS 5? Should you upgrade? And how do both compare to Android&#8217;s map app? Read on to find out in this ultimate cartography clash.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ios\">ios</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/maps\">maps</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/android\">android</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/cnet\">cnet</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://askatechteacher.wordpress.com/2012/09/24/dear-otto-what-are-good-guidelines-for-younger-bloggers/\">Dear Otto: What Are Good Guidelines for Younger Bloggers? Â« Ask a Tech Teacher</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;I spent some time digging into what most people are using. Turns out, there&apos;s a list that seems pretty good adapted from Academy of Discovery wiki wiki. Everywhere I checked, this is the list I got (often, personalized to the school&apos;s unique situation):&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/dear\">dear</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/guidelines\">guidelines</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/younger\">younger</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/bloggers\">bloggers</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tech\">tech</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teacher\">teacher</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.dontwasteyourtime.co.uk/conferences/future-of-technology-in-education-app-fote12/\">Future of Technology in Education App #FOTE12 â€“ eLearning Blog Dont Waste Your Time</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Future of Technology in Education Conference (iPhone/iPad/iPod): If you&apos;re considering attending the Future of Technology in Education FOTE conference this year then you may want to think about downloading the dedicated App for it (also available for Android devices).&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/future\">future</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/technology\">technology</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/education\">education</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/app\">app</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/elearning\">elearning</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/blog\">blog</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/dont\">dont</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/time\">time</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://howeprincipal.wordpress.com/2012/09/24/the-power-of-a-pln/\">The Power of a PLN | Reading By Example</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;If anyone you know out there questions the usefulness of Twitter, or may not appreciate how powerful it is to have a Professional Learning Network (PLN), please share this post with them.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/power\">power</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/pln\">pln</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/reading\">reading</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/example\">example</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://justwonderingblog.com/2012/09/24/said-no-true-inquiry-teacher-ever/\">..said no true inquiry teacher ever.... Â« Justwondering</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;After years of publishing books and articlesÂ Â  â€“ you would think that the relatively simple act of \"blogging\" would come naturally. Â Strangely, like using twitter and facebook for professional purposes, I have been very slow to include blogging in my repertoire of professional communication vehicles.Â  For someone who loves writing, I have been curious as to why.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/inquiry\">inquiry</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teacher\">teacher</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.mguhlin.org/2012/09/explore-other-options-twitter-rss-magic.html\">Around the Corner-MGuhlin.org: Explore Other Options as Twitter RSS Magic Fizzles</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Unfortunately, Twitter recently announced that RSS feeds are dead, although they are offering to let you download your tweets. The truth is, I&#8217;d rather have the RSS feed feature. IMHO, Twitter just shot itself in the foot.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/org\">org</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/options\">options</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/rss\">rss</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/magic\">magic</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://thenextweb.com/apps/2012/09/23/this-chrome-extension-tells-key-people-articles-read-news/?awesm=tnw.to_m4k8\">Chrome Extension Tells You About Key People As You Read News</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Here&apos;s a pro tip for Chrome power users: Check out Summer, an extension that highlights key people while you read the news.Â Currently supporting 60+ sites, including The Next Web, Summer lets you avoid having to search for noteworthy people by showing you detailed snapshots on theÂ side of compatible sites.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/chrome\">chrome</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/extension\">extension</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tells\">tells</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/key\">key</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/people\">people</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/news\">news</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.tuaw.com/2012/09/23/one-not-so-secret-reason-apple-built-its-own-maps-for-ios-6-tal/\">One not-so-secret reason Apple built its own Maps for iOS 6 | TUAW &#8211; The Unofficial Apple Weblog</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;In the uproar over iOS 6&#8242;s move to Apple&#8217;s homegrown Maps service, the driving theme is user frustration (not to say outright anger). Even the most ardent apologists have to acknowledge that Maps has serious issues, and the company&#8217;s critics are having a field day.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/reason\">reason</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/apple\">apple</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/maps\">maps</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ios\">ios</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/unofficial\">unofficial</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/weblog\">weblog</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://searchenginewatch.com/article/2207431/Microsoft-to-Safari-Users-Google-Tracked-You-So-Try-Bing\">Microsoft to Safari Users: Google Tracked You, So Try Bing &#8211; Search Engine Watch (#SEW)</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Microsoft is using the fine levied against Google for its Safari privacy gaffe to tempt Safari users to use Bing.</p>\n<p>The company has added a &#8216;Privacy Protection&#8217; page to Bing&#8217;s website, and there it reminds anyone that will listen that earlier this year Google was fined $22.5 million by the FTC.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/microsoft\">microsoft</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/safari\">safari</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/users\">users</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/google\">google</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/bing\">bing</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/search\">search</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/search engine\">search engine</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/engine\">engine</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/watch\">watch</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.dr4ward.com/dr4ward/2012/09/what-is-the-difference-between-professional-vs-personal-social-network-mindset-video-infographic.html\">DR4WARD: What Is The Difference Between Professional Vs. Personal Social Network Mindset? #Video #Infographic</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;What Is The Difference Between Professional Vs. Personal Social Network Mindset? #Video #Infographic&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ward\">ward</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/difference\">difference</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/professional\">professional</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/personal\">personal</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/social\">social</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/social network\">social network</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/network\">network</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/mindset\">mindset</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/video\">video</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infographic\">infographic</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://mashable.com/2012/09/23/firefox-10th-anniversary/\">Mozilla Firefox Turns 10</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Firefox is unique among the browser titans, because it&apos;s the only one that&apos;s completely open source - meaning Mozilla makes all of the source code available to the public. This has led to the proliferation of add-ons, many of which are made by non-employees. They allow users to greatly customize their browser.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/mozilla\">mozilla</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/mozilla firefox\">mozilla firefox</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/firefox\">firefox</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/turns\">turns</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.shoutmeloud.com/blogging-skills.html\">3 Skills you Need to Have for Blogging</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Blogging is like any other task, if you know how to blog it&apos;s easy and it you don&apos;t, it will be as tough as walking in the Sand. &#8220;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/skills\">skills</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/blogging\">blogging</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.cultofmac.com/190843/the-ipod-nano-a-history-of-apple-quirkiest-ipod-gallery/\">The iPod Nano: A History Of Apple Quirkiest iPod [Gallery] | Cult of Mac</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Over the last eight years, the iPod Nano has experienced more design changes than any other Apple product. It&apos;s gone from metal to plastic, tall to fat, and click-wheel to touch, with more color changes than a chameleon.Â &#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ipod\">ipod</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/nano\">nano</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/history\">history</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/apple\">apple</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/gallery\">gallery</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/cult\">cult</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/mac\">mac</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.wired.com/geekdad/2012/09/its-super-scratch-programming-adventure/\">Super Scratch Programming Adventure Is an Awesome Way to Get Kids Into Programming | GeekDad | Wired.com</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;That&apos;s why I&apos;m so impressed with a new release from No Starch Press titled Super Scratch Programming Adventure (SSPA, for short). SSPA offers up 10 Stages (chapters) that use a comic book format to teach programming with the Scratch programming tool. Millions of kids have used it, and the simplicity of the tool is that it sneaks in real programming concepts and techniques in a fun, colorful manner.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/super\">super</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/scratch\">scratch</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/programming\">programming</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/adventure\">adventure</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/way\">way</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/kids\">kids</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/wired\">wired</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/com\">com</a></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"diigo-ps\">Posted from <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com&apos;>Diigo</a>. The rest of my favorite links are <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete&apos;>here</a>.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11118/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11118/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11118&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(564,0,0,'Permissions for research surveys??','text/html','https://landing.athabascau.ca/blog/view/167448/permissions-for-research-surveys',NULL,NULL,NULL,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,39,'<p>The last I heard, Canada was a free country and anyone has the right to ask anyone anything without permission.&nbsp; I have been asked to give my permissions for researchers to survey my students.&nbsp; As far as I know, it is up to each student whether or not they participate. My permission is not necessary.<br> I support&nbsp; research and I have no objections and would encourage any student to participate, but I am not giving consent to a process that is unnecessary and in opposition to the spirit of the Canadian Charter of Rights. In Canada you do not need permission to ask questions or conduct surveys. You may, as a researcher, request co-operation from the institution and the teacher. That is quite different than requesting permission.</p>\n<p>Am I mistaken on this???</p>\n<p>Rory</p>\n',1348558084,NULL,NULL,'Rory McGreal','https://landing.athabascau.ca/blog/owner/rory','Tue, 25 Sep 2012 00:15:47 -0600',NULL,'CDATA(0)',NULL,'<p>The last I heard, Canada was a free country and anyone has the right to ask anyone anything without permission.&nbsp; I have been asked to give my permissions for researchers to survey my students.&nbsp; As far as I know, it is up to each student whether or not they participate. My permission is not necessary.<br> I support&nbsp; research and I have no objections and would encourage any student to participate, but I am not giving consent to a process that is unnecessary and in opposition to the spirit of the Canadian Charter of Rights. In Canada you do not need permission to ask questions or conduct surveys. You may, as a researcher, request co-operation from the institution and the teacher. That is quite different than requesting permission.</p>\n<p>Am I mistaken on this???</p>\n<p>Rory</p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(565,0,0,'@glenfcochrane I&apos;m thinking in broader sense not with #oped12. Many OERs require u 2 register first, I don&apos;t always want 2 give them my info','twitter','http://twitter.com/FrznGuru/statuses/250493209476747264',NULL,NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/FrznGuru/statuses/250493209476747264',NULL,NULL,29,'@<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/glenfcochrane\">glenfcochrane</a> I&apos;m thinking in broader sense not with #<em>oped12</em>. Many OERs require u 2 register first, I don&apos;t always want 2 give them my info',1348559284,NULL,NULL,'FrznGuru','http://twitter.com/FrznGuru','Tue, 25 Sep 2012 07:13:29 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(566,10,0,'#oped12 Definire l&#8217;apertura, una sintesi','text/html','https://serenaturri.wordpress.com/2012/09/25/oped12-definire-lapertura-una-sintesi/','Mappe;oped12;istruzione aperta;movimento oer;OER;',NULL,NULL,20,NULL,NULL,NULL,36,'Compongo l&#8217;UnitÃ  1 attraverso: Letture della prima settimana Letture della seconda settimana OER una mappa con wikimindmap. Una seconda mappa che rappresenta i concetti piÃ¹ rilevanti delle letture proposte. &#160; &#160; &#160; &#160; Filed under: Mappe, oped12<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=serenaturri.wordpress.com&#038;blog=9618855&#038;post=2164&#038;subd=serenaturri&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348562764,NULL,NULL,'serenaturri','http://serenaturri.wordpress.com','Tue, 25 Sep 2012 08:35:57 +0000',NULL,'serenaturri&#039;s Blog','5','<p>Compongo l&#8217;UnitÃ  1 attraverso:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://open.mooc.ca/week1.htm\">Letture della prima settimana</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://open.mooc.ca/week2.htm\">Letture della seconda settimana</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://wikimindmap.org/viewmap.php?wiki=en.wikipedia.org&amp;topic=Open+educational+resources\">OER</a> una mappa con wikimindmap.</p>\n<p>Una <a href=\"https://serenaturri.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/definizione.pdf\">seconda mappa</a> che rappresenta i concetti piÃ¹ rilevanti delle letture proposte.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<br />Filed under: <a href=&apos;https://serenaturri.wordpress.com/category/mappe/&apos;>Mappe</a>, <a href=&apos;https://serenaturri.wordpress.com/category/oped12/&apos;>oped12</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/serenaturri.wordpress.com/2164/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/serenaturri.wordpress.com/2164/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=serenaturri.wordpress.com&#038;blog=9618855&#038;post=2164&#038;subd=serenaturri&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(567,0,0,'Customize your own Google Chrome','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/25/customize-your-own-google-chrome/','application;Computers;Google;Browsers;Clients;David Pogue;Google Chrome;Searching;Web browser;',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'&#160; Warning &#8211; slightly geeky post this morning. But, if you&#8217;re a Google Chrome user, I&#8217;ll bet you try it at least once! How many times have you looked for a Google Chrome theme that says &#8220;Hey, this is me&#8230;&#8221; and failed? Â You&#8217;ll end up going back to the defaults or compromising on something close. [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11114&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348565643,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Tue, 25 Sep 2012 09:00:00 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Warning &#8211; slightly geeky post this morning.</p>\n<p>But, if you&#8217;re a Google Chrome user, I&#8217;ll bet you try it at least once!</p>\n<p>How many times have you looked for a Google Chrome theme that says &#8220;Hey, this is me&#8230;&#8221; and failed? Â You&#8217;ll end up going back to the defaults or compromising on something close.</p>\n<p>Well, no longer! Â Head over to the Google Chrome Store and download &#8220;<strong><a href=\"https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/oehpjpccmlcalbenfhnacjeocbjdonic/related?utm_source=chrome-ntp-icon\">My Chrome Theme</a></strong>&#8220;.</p>\n<p>It only takes a few seconds &#8230; once installed, go ahead and launch the application.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"http://dougpete.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/theme.jpg?w=500&h=179\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"179\" /></p>\n<p>You&#8217;re there!</p>\n<p>Follow the three steps and you&#8217;ve created your own theme.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"http://dougpete.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/steps.jpg?w=500&h=435\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"435\" /></p>\n<p>Step 1 &#8211; If you&#8217;d like an image on the opening background, upload it from your computer or use your Webcam to take your perfect image. Â Read the fine print at the bottom before doing so&#8230;your content will be uploaded. Â The first time I ran this, I used an image that had already been posted on this blog &#8211; the image with Kerry, myself, and David Pogue digging my car out after the big snow storm at the RCAC Symposium a few years ago. Â It&#8217;s one of my favourites but, for me, a background image really isn&#8217;t usable since I use the Incredible StartPage anyway which overwrites the image.</p>\n<p>Step 2 &#8211; Choose some colours! Â Active tab, background tab, background tab bar, background area. Â Or, the infamous Google &#8220;I&#8217;m Feeling Lucky&#8221;.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"http://dougpete.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/colours.jpg?w=500&h=339\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"339\" /></p>\n<p>If you know me, you&#8217;ll know that there aren&#8217;t enough shades of green to keep me happy. Â I thought that pinky/orange was a nice contrast.</p>\n<p>Step 3 &#8211; Install your theme.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"http://dougpete.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/install.jpg?w=500&h=293\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"293\" /></p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re so inclined, share the themes with others. Â Just keep in mind the caveat about the images.</p>\n<p>Wasn&#8217;t that easy?</p>\n<p>You now have that perfect theme for yourself. Â Or, if you&#8217;re using Google Chrome with your class, you could pop an image of the school and populate Chrome with your school colours. Or&#8230;.</p>\n<h6 class=\"zemanta-related-title\" style=\"font-size:1em;\">Related articles</h6>\n<ul class=\"zemanta-article-ul\">\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://hothardware.com/News/Google-to-Drop-Chrome-Support-for-OS-X-105-Leopard/\" target=\"_blank\">Google to Drop Chrome Support for OS X 10.5 Leopard</a> (hothardware.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://www.webpronews.com/a-visual-evolution-of-googles-chrome-2012-09\" target=\"_blank\">A Visual Evolution Of Google&#8217;s Chrome</a> (webpronews.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://www.tomsguide.com/us/pictures-story/283-free-google-chrome-extension-add-in-app.html\" target=\"_blank\">The 40 Best Google Chrome Extensions</a> (tomsguide.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://wordsformwindows.com/2012/09/19/tools-of-the-trade-google-chrome/\" target=\"_blank\">Tools Of The Trade: Google Chrome</a> (wordsformwindows.com)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11114/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11114/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11114&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(568,0,0,'What the Heck is a MOOC? ','text/html','http://campusforcommunities.blogspot.com/2012/09/what-heck-is-mooc.html',NULL,NULL,NULL,29,NULL,NULL,'2012-09-16 20:43:57',46,'<h2></h2><h2></h2>September signifies back-to-school but, despite the best of intentions, I didn&apos;t sign up.<br /><br />I came pretty darn close this year in that I found an MBA being offered in Community Economic Development that caters to those in the workforce. Additionally, it was the only MBA I&apos;d ever found that acknowledged what I&apos;ve already learned and published, providing me with credit for 6 of the 15 courses that would be required. At $2000 per course that meant saving significant money as well as time.<br />Regardless, something still kept niggling and holding me back from completing the application forms despite the fact that I am committed and passionate about lifelong learning and have always made it a priority.<br />When I analyzed my reluctance to return to learning in a formal setting, I realized that it wasn&apos;t just the time and money that was holding me back. It was more about me rebelling against the accepted model of traditional top down, instructor-centric learning. I came to understand that what matters to me, in this world of data overload, is the network and what others are calling the&amp;nbsp;<em>meshwork</em>&amp;nbsp;that results.<br />My greatest learnings seem more apt to come from a network of both learners and instructors, readings, videos, blogs, conversations, reflections, webinars, writing, training, conferences, colleagues from other fields etc. While it is often messy and chaotic, I am moved on a regular basis by the excitement and richness of what I learn on an almost daily basis.<br />Imagine my delight when I found out this week about MOOCs-an emerging trend in post secondary online learning. MOOC is an abbreviation for&amp;nbsp;<em>Massive Open Online Course</em>.<br />While it began in 2007 as an online conference, it has since shifted into delivering courses that don&apos;t focus on mastering content as much as they do on developing networks that continue one&apos;s learning far beyond the actual course. In other words, as George Siemens of Athabasca University puts it, instead of having the social elements of a course wrapped around prescribed content, the social interaction serves as catalyst and contact for relationships with others who remain within their own spaces and bring their own learnings and resources.<br />Consequently, every participant becomes both a learner and a teacher. The end results are the connections, collaborations, and knowledge aggregation I&apos;ve been seeking.<br />While this sometimes results in a rather chaotic and messy environment many will find stressful, making sense of the chaos becomes part of the learning experience. While course outcomes are provided, the instructor does not help to make sense of the chaos as they would do traditionally, instead leaving that to each student.<br />The student&apos;s job is not to memorize but to instead use the tools and information provided during the course. This practice is in fact more important than the content so the learning becomes more of a modern day apprenticeship of learning-by-doing surrounded by many experts and resources.<br />MOOCs ultimately are another way of learning-albeit one that is open, participatory, and supportive of the development of lifelong networked learning.&amp;nbsp; The additional bonus is that one only pays if they want credit for the course.<br />All in all, it was just too much for me to resist. This fall I&apos;m not starting on my MBA but I have signed up for a MOOC at Athabasca called,&amp;nbsp;<em>Openness in Education</em>. Wish me luck!<br class=\"Apple-interchange-newline\" /><br /><h2></h2><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1192170824225367759-5691431961672202482?l=campusforcommunities.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',1348571883,NULL,NULL,'Brenda Herchmer','http://www.blogger.com/profile/10237169838657305465','2012-09-16T20:09:00.001-07:00',NULL,'Campus for Communities of the Future',NULL,'<h2></h2><h2></h2>September signifies back-to-school but, despite the best of intentions, I didn&apos;t sign up.<br /><br />I came pretty darn close this year in that I found an MBA being offered in Community Economic Development that caters to those in the workforce. Additionally, it was the only MBA I&apos;d ever found that acknowledged what I&apos;ve already learned and published, providing me with credit for 6 of the 15 courses that would be required. At $2000 per course that meant saving significant money as well as time.<br />Regardless, something still kept niggling and holding me back from completing the application forms despite the fact that I am committed and passionate about lifelong learning and have always made it a priority.<br />When I analyzed my reluctance to return to learning in a formal setting, I realized that it wasn&apos;t just the time and money that was holding me back. It was more about me rebelling against the accepted model of traditional top down, instructor-centric learning. I came to understand that what matters to me, in this world of data overload, is the network and what others are calling the&amp;nbsp;<em>meshwork</em>&amp;nbsp;that results.<br />My greatest learnings seem more apt to come from a network of both learners and instructors, readings, videos, blogs, conversations, reflections, webinars, writing, training, conferences, colleagues from other fields etc. While it is often messy and chaotic, I am moved on a regular basis by the excitement and richness of what I learn on an almost daily basis.<br />Imagine my delight when I found out this week about MOOCs-an emerging trend in post secondary online learning. MOOC is an abbreviation for&amp;nbsp;<em>Massive Open Online Course</em>.<br />While it began in 2007 as an online conference, it has since shifted into delivering courses that don&apos;t focus on mastering content as much as they do on developing networks that continue one&apos;s learning far beyond the actual course. In other words, as George Siemens of Athabasca University puts it, instead of having the social elements of a course wrapped around prescribed content, the social interaction serves as catalyst and contact for relationships with others who remain within their own spaces and bring their own learnings and resources.<br />Consequently, every participant becomes both a learner and a teacher. The end results are the connections, collaborations, and knowledge aggregation I&apos;ve been seeking.<br />While this sometimes results in a rather chaotic and messy environment many will find stressful, making sense of the chaos becomes part of the learning experience. While course outcomes are provided, the instructor does not help to make sense of the chaos as they would do traditionally, instead leaving that to each student.<br />The student&apos;s job is not to memorize but to instead use the tools and information provided during the course. This practice is in fact more important than the content so the learning becomes more of a modern day apprenticeship of learning-by-doing surrounded by many experts and resources.<br />MOOCs ultimately are another way of learning-albeit one that is open, participatory, and supportive of the development of lifelong networked learning.&amp;nbsp; The additional bonus is that one only pays if they want credit for the course.<br />All in all, it was just too much for me to resist. This fall I&apos;m not starting on my MBA but I have signed up for a MOOC at Athabasca called,&amp;nbsp;<em>Openness in Education</em>. Wish me luck!<br class=\"Apple-interchange-newline\" /><br /><h2></h2><img width=&apos;1&apos; height=&apos;1&apos; src=&apos;https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1192170824225367759-5691431961672202482?l=campusforcommunities.blogspot.com&apos; alt=&apos;&apos; />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(569,0,0,'The Beginning','text/html','http://elearnchristiana.wordpress.com/2012/09/15/the-beginning-2/','Uncategorized;',NULL,NULL,30,NULL,NULL,NULL,47,'I have started this blog because it is a requirement for participating in the online course &#8220;Openness in Education&#8221;. Â I live in Athens, Greece and we are in a weird stage right now&#8230; Teachers are not paid well, and they are striking. Same with University professors&#8230; It seems that education in Greece has taken a [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=elearnchristiana.wordpress.com&#038;blog=40494450&#038;post=6&#038;subd=elearnchristiana&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348572004,NULL,NULL,'elearnchristiana','http://elearnchristiana.wordpress.com','Sat, 15 Sep 2012 19:35:03 +0000',NULL,'elearnchristiana',NULL,'<p>I have started this blog because it is a requirement for participating in the online course &#8220;Openness in Education&#8221;. Â I live in Athens, Greece and we are in a weird stage right now&#8230; Teachers are not paid well, and they are striking. Same with University professors&#8230; It seems that education in Greece has taken a negative turn, and I really hope that something can happen that will save it! Â I hope that more teachers will take on the digital revolution and embrasse e-learning.. And if this is not possible, blended learning seems like a really good solution&#8230; Â Will see&#8230;.</p>\n<p>Â </p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/elearnchristiana.wordpress.com/6/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/elearnchristiana.wordpress.com/6/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=elearnchristiana.wordpress.com&#038;blog=40494450&#038;post=6&#038;subd=elearnchristiana&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(570,0,0,'Hello world!','text/html','http://elearnchristiana.wordpress.com/2012/09/15/hello-world/','Uncategorized;',NULL,NULL,30,NULL,NULL,NULL,47,'Welcome to WordPress.com! This is your very first post. Click the Edit link to modify or delete it, or start a new post. If you like, use this post to tell readers why you started this blog and what you plan to do with it. Happy blogging!<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=elearnchristiana.wordpress.com&#038;blog=40494450&#038;post=1&#038;subd=elearnchristiana&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348572004,NULL,NULL,'elearnchristiana','http://elearnchristiana.wordpress.com','Sat, 15 Sep 2012 17:37:10 +0000',NULL,'elearnchristiana',NULL,'<p>Welcome to <a href=\"https://wordpress.com/\">WordPress.com</a>! This is your very first post. Click the Edit link to modify or delete it, or <a title=\"Direct link to Add New in the Admin Dashboard\" href=\"/wp-admin/post-new.php\">start a new post</a>. If you like, use this post to tell readers why you started this blog and what you plan to do with it.</p>\n<p>Happy blogging!</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/elearnchristiana.wordpress.com/1/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/elearnchristiana.wordpress.com/1/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=elearnchristiana.wordpress.com&#038;blog=40494450&#038;post=1&#038;subd=elearnchristiana&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(571,0,0,'ZML Leseclub #2: Online Identity Formation und Bilder unserer Erde','text/html','http://www.reimerth.com/2012/09/zml-leseclub-2-online-identity-formation-und-bilder-unserer-erde/','personal;Identity;Leseclub;',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,58,'Als Jutta, Erika und ich bei der vergangenen Leseclub-Sitzung Ã¼ber IdentitÃ¤ten und IdentitÃ¤tsbildung diskutierten, entwarfen wir kreative Bilder fÃ¼r die vielen verschiedenen IdentitÃ¤tsaspekte. Jutta hat das netter Weise dokumentarisch festgehalten in ihrem Blogpost &#8211; und als ich diese Skizzen sah, &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.reimerth.com/2012/09/zml-leseclub-2-online-identity-formation-und-bilder-unserer-erde/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a>',1348572123,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Tue, 25 Sep 2012 01:30:41 +0000',NULL,'Reimerth',NULL,'Als Jutta, Erika und ich bei der vergangenen Leseclub-Sitzung Ã¼ber IdentitÃ¤ten und IdentitÃ¤tsbildung diskutierten, entwarfen wir kreative Bilder fÃ¼r die vielen verschiedenen IdentitÃ¤tsaspekte. Jutta hat das netter Weise dokumentarisch festgehalten in ihrem Blogpost &#8211; und als ich diese Skizzen sah, &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.reimerth.com/2012/09/zml-leseclub-2-online-identity-formation-und-bilder-unserer-erde/\">Continue reading &#8594;