S\">http://t.co/iYw6oPaS</a> #<em>oped12</em>',1348677004,NULL,NULL,'DimitrisTzouris','http://twitter.com/DimitrisTzouris','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 15:47:08 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(688,5,0,'At Home','Diigo','http://athome.nfb.ca/#/athome/home','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Comments:</strong><ul><li>Ongoing web documentary (to 2013) by the National Film Board (Canada) in which the traditional model of dealing with homelessness is flipped: housing first, other issues second. Eye-opening in terms of its design and its content. - <small><a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></small></li></ul></p><p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/homelessness&quot;>homelessness</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/happiness&quot;>happiness</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/design&quot;>design</a>, <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/networks&quot;>networks</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/brainysmurf1234&quot; title=&quot;View Brainy Smurf&apos;s content in group&quot;>Brainy Smurf</a></p>',1348683603,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Wed, 26 Sep 2012 18:12:56 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','5',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(689,0,0,'Things I dd wrong, but learn\"@cjgermano: Reading up on ethics and copyright check out http://t.co/Sb0aDjp4 and http://t.co/rxNdP7JM #oped12\"','twitter','http://twitter.com/FrankOUNL/statuses/251017172057456641','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/FrankOUNL/statuses/251017172057456641',NULL,NULL,29,'Things I dd wrong, but learn\"@<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/cjgermano\">cjgermano</a>: Reading up on ethics and copyright check out <a href=\"http://t.co/Sb0aDjp4\">http://t.co/Sb0aDjp4</a> and <a href=\"http://t.co/rxNdP7JM\">http://t.co/rxNdP7JM</a> #<em>oped12</em>\"',1348683723,NULL,NULL,'FrankOUNL','http://twitter.com/FrankOUNL','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 17:55:32 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(690,0,0,'RT @juandoming: http://t.co/H4MZirXj  Open and sharing public funded resources #oped12 #opedk12 @jjapsoft @Gsiemens','twitter','http://twitter.com/languages_web2/statuses/251007789621714944','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/languages_web2/statuses/251007789621714944',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/juandoming\">juandoming</a>: <a href=\"http://t.co/H4MZirXj\">http://t.co/H4MZirXj</a> Open and sharing public funded resources #<em>oped12</em> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23opedk12\" title=\"#opedk12\" class=\" \">#opedk12</a> @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/jjapsoft\">jjapsoft</a> @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/Gsiemens\">Gsiemens</a>',1348683723,NULL,NULL,'languages_web2','http://twitter.com/languages_web2','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 17:18:15 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(691,0,0,'Illustrating the Pain','text/html','http://tjbliss.org/illustrating-the-pain/','Uncategorized;edstartup;idea;pain;category',NULL,NULL,37,NULL,NULL,NULL,56,'This simple figure illustrates the barrier between teachers and (a) assessment training and expertise, (b) access to higher quality test items, and (c) self-awareness about actual assessment expertise. The barrier is multi-faceted and includes availability, opportunity, time, and money. Our &#8230; <a href=\"http://tjbliss.org/illustrating-the-pain/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a>',1348694284,NULL,NULL,'tjbliss','http://tjbliss.org','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 21:05:57 +0000',NULL,'aperta educationem &#187; Blog',NULL,'<p>This simple figure illustrates the barrier between teachers and (a) assessment training and expertise, (b) access to higher quality test items, and (c) self-awareness about actual assessment expertise. The barrier is multi-faceted and includes availability, opportunity, time, and money. Our <a href=\"http://tjbliss.org/openassessment-org-our-edstartup-idea/\" target=\"_blank\">edstartup idea</a>Â provides clear and innovative solutions to each of these facets.<br />\n<a href=\"http://tjbliss.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Pain-Illustration1.png\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-293\" title=\"Pain Illustration\" src=\"http://tjbliss.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Pain-Illustration1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1121\" height=\"764\" /></a></p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(692,0,0,'Validating Our Assumptions','text/html','http://tjbliss.org/validating-our-assumptions/','Uncategorized;assumptions;edstartup;pain;validation;category',NULL,NULL,37,NULL,NULL,NULL,56,'Today I chatted face-to-face with eight teachers from various schools and subject areas (as well as with a couple of people within a school of education) to verify that the assumptions we have made about teachers&#8217; pain are accurate. Through &#8230; <a href=\"http://tjbliss.org/validating-our-assumptions/\">Continue reading &#8594;</a>',1348694284,NULL,NULL,'tjbliss','http://tjbliss.org','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 20:12:11 +0000',NULL,'aperta educationem &#187; Blog',NULL,'<p>Today I chatted face-to-face with eight teachers from various schools and subject areas (as well as with a couple of people within a school of education) to verify that the assumptions we have made about teachers&#8217; pain are accurate.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignright\" src=\"http://www.innovationtools.com/images/assumptions.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<p>Through my interviews, I was able to confirm each of following seven basic assumptions:</p>\n<p>1. Teachers lack assessment training.</p>\n<p>2. Teacher training programs do not have curricular space (or priority) for assessment training.</p>\n<p>3. Assessment development is time consuming and often tedious.</p>\n<p>4. Teachers rely on test banks and other sources of assessment items that have unknown quality and alignment.</p>\n<p>5. Many teachers aren&#8217;t doing much to solve this problem. However, some teachers have started collaborative assessment development activities at the department, school or district levels. This means that some teachers, at least, are looking for ways to increase the test development efficiency and quality.</p>\n<p>6. Very few teachers obtain assessment training through professional development activities. Generally, teachers who do obtain some training are those who have been asked to help in the development of large-scale standardized tests. This kind of training has limited applicability at the classroom level.</p>\n<p>7. Teachers have limited access to high quality test items, but many teachers desire more access to such items.</p>\n<p>In addition, my conversations with these teachers (and other education experts) revealed at least one other critical reality:Â teachers often don&#8217;t know what they don&#8217;t know about assessment.</p>\n<p>It turns out that most teachers feel that they have sufficient capability in assessment development and evaluation. However, a few teachers that I talked to who had received minimal training (and one currently enrolled in a measurement Ph.D. program who has received significant training) were emphatic that their assessment knowledge prior to training was exceedingly limited but that they weren&#8217;t aware of the fact. What this means is that it will be critical to find the best way to help teachers realize the benefit that could be gained by using our product. One teacher (who is training to become a principal) recommended focusing our marketing toward administrators who, if bought-in, could persuade their teachers to use it. A second way to increase use would be to offer some sort of credit (college or licensure) for those who complete the training.</p>\n<p>Finally, most of the teachers I talked with gave very positive feedback about the idea itself, including saying things like &#8220;I would use your database&#8221; and &#8220;Your training and database would be so helpful to me and other teachers I know.&#8221;</p>\n<p>Photo Credit:Â <a href=\"http://www.innovationtools.com/\">http://www.innovationtools.com</a></p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(693,0,0,'RT @cjgermano: RT @cjgermano: Reading up on ethics and copyright check out http://t.co/bg4iz82i and http://t.co/iYw6oPaS #oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/paulasimoes/statuses/250979326726647808','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/paulasimoes/statuses/250979326726647808',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/cjgermano\">cjgermano</a>: RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/cjgermano\">cjgermano</a>: Reading up on ethics and copyright check out <a href=\"http://t.co/bg4iz82i\">http://t.co/bg4iz82i</a> and <a href=\"http://t.co/iYw6oPaS\">http://t.co/iYw6oPaS</a> #<em>oped12</em>',1348697163,NULL,NULL,'paulasimoes','http://twitter.com/paulasimoes','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 15:25:09 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(694,0,0,'RT @gsiemens: RT @gsiemens: We&apos;re going to do an #oped12 twitter chat on Thurs at 7 pm Mountain time.','twitter','http://twitter.com/cjgermano/statuses/250961237469450242','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/cjgermano/statuses/250961237469450242',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/gsiemens\">gsiemens</a>: RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/gsiemens\">gsiemens</a>: We&apos;re going to do an #<em>oped12</em> twitter chat on Thurs at 7 pm Mountain time.',1348697164,NULL,NULL,'cjgermano','http://twitter.com/cjgermano','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 14:13:16 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(695,0,0,'RT @gsiemens: We&apos;re going to do an #oped12 twitter chat on Thurs at 7 pm Mountain time. #TLTGmooc1','twitter','http://twitter.com/ifrank/statuses/251089241998766080','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/ifrank/statuses/251089241998766080',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/gsiemens\">gsiemens</a>: We&apos;re going to do an #<em>oped12</em> twitter chat on Thurs at 7 pm Mountain time. <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23TLTGmooc1\" title=\"#TLTGmooc1\" class=\" \">#TLTGmooc1</a>',1348703883,NULL,NULL,'ifrank','http://twitter.com/ifrank','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 22:41:54 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(696,0,0,'Readings on blended learning with Creative Commons license Nice. This is a very well-designed onl...','text/html','https://plus.google.com/110117137800261731479/posts/Q65tdZcrQk9','category',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'Readings on blended learning with Creative Commons licenseNice.This is a very well-designed online course. Check out the very cool message board:http://hootcourse.com/course/2554/<p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course-readings/&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>BlendKit Course: Readings | Blended Learning Toolkit</a>\n									</p>',1348704124,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Thu, 27 Sep 2012 00:31:52 +0200',NULL,'CDATA(0)',NULL,'Readings on blended learning with Creative Commons licenseNice.This is a very well-designed online course. Check out the very cool message board:http://hootcourse.com/course/2554/<p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course-readings/&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>BlendKit Course: Readings | Blended Learning Toolkit</a>\n									</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(697,0,0,'Very nice post from a classmate at the blended learning MOOC (http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blend...','text/html','https://plus.google.com/110117137800261731479/posts/62YpoBS2B6u','category',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'Very nice post from a classmate at the blended learning MOOC (http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course/)<p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://www.techconvoy.com/?p=518&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Evidence for blended learning</a>\n									</p><p class=&apos;attachment photo&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://www.techconvoy.com/?p=518&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.techconvoy.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2012%2F09%2Fblended.png&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/> </a>\n									</p>',1348704124,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Thu, 27 Sep 2012 00:07:27 +0200',NULL,'CDATA(0)',NULL,'Very nice post from a classmate at the blended learning MOOC (http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course/)<p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://www.techconvoy.com/?p=518&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Evidence for blended learning</a>\n									</p><p class=&apos;attachment photo&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://www.techconvoy.com/?p=518&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.techconvoy.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2012%2F09%2Fblended.png&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/> </a>\n									</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(698,0,0,'','text/html','http://moocmadness.wordpress.com/2012/09/26/65/','MOOC;cfhe12;cmc11;mobimooc;mooc;moocmooc;potcert;category',NULL,NULL,35,NULL,NULL,NULL,54,'...that covers most of the classes I am behind on blogging for or about. The notorious x-MOOC, a name hinting at both edX and (at least to me) the skull and cross bones flag, this time flown by edu-biz corporate raiders.Â Alas, traditional higher education is not doing so well at telling them apart. Such is [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=moocmadness.wordpress.com&#038;blog=39998452&#038;post=65&#038;subd=moocmadness&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348707488,NULL,NULL,'VanessaVaile','http://moocmadness.wordpress.com','Wed, 26 Sep 2012 23:19:39 +0000',NULL,'MOOC Madness',NULL,'<em>...that covers most of the classes I am behind on blogging for or about. The notorious x-MOOC, a name hinting at both edX and (at least to me) the skull and cross bones flag, this time flown by edu-biz corporate raiders.Â Alas, traditional higher education is not doing so well at telling them apart. Such is the inherent madness of MOOCs. Although POT Cert is currently sailing under a constructivist flag, so far no connectivists have walked the plank. x, c or not ~ it&#8217;s all connected.Â </em> <em>Webinar, links,Â files and other resources available online after the webinar should be of use and interest to all categories noted above. Steve Hardigan writes,</em> \nNetwork Email</p> <table width=\"98%\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\" width=\"100%\"> <table width=\"100%\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<a href=\"http://youtu.be/eW3gMGqcZQc\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignright\" style=\"border:0;\" src=\"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-tQkLzS2TNWc/UGNJ2mQB1_I/AAAAAAAAOn8/LPRTFU0LlSo/s200/mooc.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"154\" height=\"86\" border=\"0\" /></a>Join me today, Wednesday, September 26th, for a one-hour live and interactive<a href=\"http://futureofeducation.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">FutureofEducation.com</a>Â webinar on the &#8220;true history&#8221; of theÂ Massive Oen Online Course (MOOC) withÂ Dave Cormier, Alec Couros, Stephen Downes, Rita Kop, Inge de Waard, and Carol Yeager. While a wave of courses from prominent universities are now labeled as MOOCs, we&#8217;ll drill down on the constructivist roots of the early MOOC offerings and discuss the importance of the differences between them and the current breed.Â See you online!Â <a href=\"http://www.stevehargadon.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Steve Hargadon</a>\n<img src=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/trans.gif?w=1\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Date</strong>: Wednesday, September 26th, 2012</li>\n<li><strong>Time</strong>: 5pm Pacific / 8pm Eastern (<a href=\"http://timeanddate.com/worldclock/fixedtime.html?month=9&amp;day=26&amp;year=2012&amp;hour=17&amp;min=0&amp;sec=0&amp;p1=217\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">internaÂ Â tional times here</a>)</li>\n<li><strong>Duration</strong>: 1 hour</li>\n<li><strong>Location</strong>: In Blackboard Collaborate (formerly Elluminate). Log in atÂ <a href=\"http://futureofed.info/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://futureofed.info</a>. The Blackboard Collaborate room will be open up to 30 minutes before the event if you want to come in early. To make sure that your computer is configured for Blackboard Collaborate, please visitÂ <a href=\"http://support.blackboardcollaborate.com/ics/support/default.asp?deptID=8336&amp;task=knowledge&amp;questionID=1473\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">the support and configuration page</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Recordings</strong>: The full Blackboard Collaborate recordingÂ and a portable .mp3 recording will be available shortly after the show at<a href=\"http://www.futureofeducation.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.futureofeducation.com</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Mightybell Space</strong>: Resources, videos, links, and conversation about the interview can be foundÂ <a href=\"https://mightybell.com/spaces/9533999d6158d467\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>HERE</strong></a>.</li>\n</ul> <a href=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/davecormier.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignleft\" style=\"border:0;\" src=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/davecormier.jpg?w=160&h=106\" alt=\"\" width=\"160\" height=\"106\" border=\"0\" /></a><strong>Dave Cormier</strong>Â is an educational activist, researcher, online community advocate and the Manager of Web Communications and Innovations at the University of Prince Edward Island. He has published on open education, Rhizomatic Learning, MOOCs (Massive Open Online Courses), Digital Identity, and practical classroom uses of virtual worlds.His educational journey started in 1998 teaching little children to speak English. The pivotal moment of his career happened when he was teaching at Hannam University in South Korea in 2003 surrounded by the papers of 275 writing students and wondering if he had them all. That winter he started using discussion forums to bring all of his students together in a writing community (and to digitally keep track of their work) and he hasn&apos;t looked back. He&apos;s since helped organize online communities of teachers, spoken at events around the world and worked to understand how internet changes what it means to know. His educational exploration partners have included faculty and researchers from well-known universities, and lone teachers in small town classrooms. Some of them are even still talking to him.Dave&apos;s keynotes in the last couple of years have centred around how coming to know is a messy, imprecise process at once intensely individual and necessarily embedded in a community &#8211; Rhizomatic Learning. You can follow him on twitter atÂ <a href=\"http://twitter.com/davecormier\" target=\"_blank\">@DaveCormier</a>Â or follow his thoughts atÂ <a href=\"http://davecormier.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://davecormier.com</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/aleccouros2.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignright\" style=\"border:0;\" src=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/aleccouros2.jpg?w=150&h=130\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"130\" border=\"0\" /></a><strong>Dr. Alec Couros</strong>Â is a Professor of educational technology and media at the Faculty of Education, University of Regina. He has given hundreds of workshops and presentations, nationally and internationally, on topics such as openness in education, networked learning, social media in education, digital citizenship, and critical media literacy. His graduate and undergraduate courses help current and future educators understand how to use and take advantage of the educational potential offered by the tools of connectivity.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/stephendownesnew.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignleft\" style=\"border:0;\" src=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/stephendownesnew.jpg?w=160&h=120\" alt=\"\" width=\"160\" height=\"120\" border=\"0\" /></a><strong>Stephen Downes</strong>Â works for the National Research Council of Canada where he has served as a Senior Researcher, based in Moncton, New Brunswick, since 2001. Affiliated with the Learning and Collaborative Technologies Group, Institute for Information Technology, Downes specializes in the fields of online learning, new media, pedagogy and philosophy.</p>\n<p>Downes is perhaps best known for his daily nesletter,Â <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/news/OLDaily.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">OLDaily</a>, which is distributed by web, email and RSS to thousands of subscribers around the world. He has published numerous articles both online and in print, including The Future of Online Learning (1998), Learning Objects (2000), Resource Profiles (2003), and E-Learning 2.0 (2005). He is a popular speaker, appearing at hundreds of events around the world over the last fifteen years.</p>\n<p>Prior to joining the NRC, Downes worked for the University of Alberta as an information architect, and prior to that, as a distance education and new media design specialist for Assiniboine Community College in Brandon, Manitoba. This followed a decade of teaching experience both in person and by distance with Athabasca University, the University of Alberta, and Grande Prairie regional college.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/ritakop2.jpg?w=100\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignright\" style=\"border:0;\" src=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/ritakop2.jpg?w=165&h=167\" alt=\"\" width=\"165\" height=\"167\" border=\"0\" /></a><strong>Rita Kop:</strong>Â I currently work as an Associate Dean of Education at Yorkville University. I am involved in the design, development and maintainance of online educational programs, and in teaching and research of the learning experiences. I am also currently carrying out research of open educational practices, such as Massive Open Online Courses and am involved in research in learning analytics. The research entails the use of qualitative measures and data mining. A virtual ethnography was one of the recent methods I used, and the data analyses involved qualitative data mining and social network analysis of large amounts of learner data and research in the ethics of using &apos;Big Data&apos; in research.</p>\n<p>Till August 2012 I worked as a researcher at the National Research council of Canada on their Personal Learning environment Project. I left Swansea University in the UK for three years to work on the research and development of these PLEs. In Swansea I was assistant professor in the Department of Adult Continuing Education. Apart from research and teaching my remit there was to widen access to Higher Education through &#8216;reaching in&#8217; activities of working with University departments in developing progression routes for non-traditional students. Prior to this I managed a number of large Widening Access outreach projects in South West Wales and the Valleys. These projects were dynamic collaborations between the department and community partners in South West Wales and often involved the use of technology. I developed their MA in Lifelong Learning programme.</p>\n<p>My career in education started as a teacher and head teacher of an infant school in Alphen aan den Rijn in the Netherlands. I am interested in lifelong learning from early years to old age and am a bit of a nomad; I enjoy travelling and learning about people and cultures, not only in an educational context.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/ignatia_inge_de_waard.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignleft\" style=\"border:0;\" src=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/ignatia_inge_de_waard.jpg?w=160&h=160\" alt=\"\" width=\"160\" height=\"160\" border=\"0\" /></a><strong>Inge Ignatia de Waard:Â </strong>At the moment I work as the elearning coordinator at the Institute of Tropical MedicineÂ Antwerpen (ITM), Belgium and I am involved in educational research with Athabasca UniversityÂ in Canada. I have been immersed in eLearning from 1999 onward, with ever increasing passion.Â After a rocky learning start right up to late twenties, I managed to end up with a background inÂ IT and pedagogy. Thanks to many wonderful people and institutes I have had the privilege toÂ speak on the subject of TELearning, MOOCs and mLearning across different continents. I am aÂ firm believer in connecting with each other, so feel free to get into a conversation.Â For me MOOCs are an ideal way for organizing expert knowledge exchange, communityÂ strengthening and train-the-trainer options.</p> \n<strong>Online resources:Â </strong> <ul>\n<li>MobiMOOC course:Â <a href=\"http://mobimooc.wikispaces.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://mobimooc.wikispaces.com</a></li>\n<li>eLearning blog:Â <a href=\"http://ignatiawebs.blogspot.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://ignatiawebs.blogspot.com</a></li>\n<li>Twitter: @ignatia</li>\n<li>LinkedIn:Â <a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/in/ingedewaard\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.linkedin.com/in/ingedewaard</a></li>\n<li>Presentations:Â <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/ignatia/presentations\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.slideshare.net/ignatia/presentations</a></li>\n<li>Publications:Â <a href=\"http://www.ingedewaard.net/pubconsulpres.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ingedewaard.net/pubconsulpres.htm</a></li>\n</ul> <a href=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/carolyeager.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignright\" style=\"border:0;\" src=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/carolyeager.jpg?w=160&h=143\" alt=\"\" width=\"160\" height=\"143\" border=\"0\" /></a><strong>Carol Yeager:Â </strong>I am a practicing artist as well as a life long learner. I have been associated with SUNY since 1989. For 8 years I was traveling and teaching for ESC&#8217;s International Programs in Europe, Greece and Lebanon. In addition to my life and travel as an artist, and my work with SUNY, I can also be found working on Broadway shows in Manhattan from time to time. I discovered long ago that moving targets are hard to hit &#8211; so I keep moving!! In my spare time I have been, to name a few other pursuits, a magazine editor, a designer, real estate agent, writer, paralegal, painter, carpenter and a farmer &#8230; I have recently completed another graduate degree, an MS, through the ICSC program in Creativity and Change Leadership at SUNY/Buffalo State. Expanding my horizons as a life long learner offers great adventure now and for the future.\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table> Visit Student 2.0 at:Â <a href=\"http://www.student20.com/?xg_source=msg_mes_network\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.student20.com/</a> </td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>  \n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/moocmadness.wordpress.com/65/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/moocmadness.wordpress.com/65/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=moocmadness.wordpress.com&#038;blog=39998452&#038;post=65&#038;subd=moocmadness&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(699,14,0,'first steps in MOOC-land','text/html','http://www.cheshirepuss.co.uk/post1/','Uncategorized;category',NULL,NULL,41,NULL,NULL,NULL,64,'This is by way of an experiment. I came across MOOC #oped12 by chance, pottering about following education links across the web one evening. When I watched the videos on the welcome page the theory sounded good, and chimed with my own experience. In the nineties I started learning Spanish, going along for 2 hours once a week after work to university evening classes, gradually moving up year by year through the levels. It was obvious early on that for all the excellent teaching, and good social buzz, that the classes wouldn&#8217;t be enough on their own. So I built my own little learning network: regular coffees with Spanish friends, meeting classmates to see the latest AlmodÃ³var, email exchanges,Â  travelling &#38; meeting people in Spain &#38; South America. And slowly, over several years, I learned what worked best for me, and eventually got to the level of fluency I wanted. Of course that was before the boom in social media and collaborative web learning tools. The networks of online information we could build today appear almost infinite compared to the nineties.Â  But the principles seem to me essentially the same, and I&#8217;d like to see in practice how MOOCs use [...]',1348715765,NULL,NULL,'ian','http://www.cheshirepuss.co.uk','Tue, 25 Sep 2012 09:00:52 +0000',NULL,'Cheshire Cat','7','<p>This is by way of an experiment.</p>\n<p>I came across MOOC #oped12 by chance, pottering about following education links across the web one evening. When I watched the videos on the welcome page the theory sounded good, and chimed with my own experience.</p>\n<p>In the nineties I started learning Spanish, going along for 2 hours once a week after work to university evening classes, gradually moving up year by year through the levels. It was obvious early on that for all the excellent teaching, and good social buzz, that the classes wouldn&#8217;t be enough on their own. So I built my own little learning network: regular coffees with Spanish friends, meeting classmates to see the latest AlmodÃ³var, email exchanges,Â  travelling &amp; meeting people in Spain &amp; South America. And slowly, over several years, I learned what worked best for me, and eventually got to the level of fluency I wanted.</p>\n<p>Of course that was before the boom in social media and collaborative web learning tools. The networks of online information we could build today appear almost infinite compared to the nineties.Â  But the principles seem to me essentially the same, and I&#8217;d like to see in practice how MOOCs use the web to advance ways of &#8220;remote but integrated&#8221; learning, so I signed up for the course. Having worked in and around IT for 20 years I&#8217;m also very interested in the subject matter &#8211; it was a nice blast from the past to read Eric Raymond&#8217;s brilliant &#8220;Cathedral and the Bazaar&#8221; article again (my ten years of coding life were spent very much in a corporate cathedral).</p>\n<p>And having signed up I&#8217;m going to give it a proper go. So I&#8217;ve made my first steps in open source software, building this little WordPress blog so I can add my tuppenceworth.</p>\n<p>I can imagine where potential problems lie &#8211; participants not engaging with the course or each other, no focussed discussion but rather a series of tangents, etc. I&#8217;m not sure how much MOOC organisers can do in facilitating some sort of synergy of ideas across the course. Also, I like to talk and discuss face to face, in a cafe, at work, at a conference. I&#8217;ll find it a bit strange trying to connect with people I&#8217;ve never met.</p>\n<p>But then it&#8217;s not as if the old pre-internet universities were a golden age of personal exchanges. Way back in the 70s when I did my philosophy degree I spent my first year in lecture theatres of 200+ students being talked at by turgid lecturers who&#8217;d probably been doing the same presentation for decades. There was no engagement with the class, nor with individual students, nor any structure to facilitate the students themselves getting together to discuss ideas. Essentially it was just listen, read approved texts, regurgitate. It was well into second year before I made connections with some fellow students and lecturers, and thinking and learning finally became a social process, and a million times more interesting (and fun!)</p>\n<p>Anyway, I&#8217;m a bit older now, and the internet should be blowing away ye olde academic cobwebs and enabling new, exciting, connected learning. So let&#8217;s see how it works out in practice.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(700,9,0,'By: ~ FOAD connectiviste ~ Plan de travail Ã©tudiant (travaux notÃ©s) &#171; Fr#oped12','text/html','http://foadblog.wordpress.com/2012/09/06/foad_connectiviste/comment-page-1/#comment-2','category',NULL,NULL,42,NULL,NULL,NULL,63,'[...] a Ã©voquÃ©, dans la page de &#8216;mise en contexte&#8216;, la notion de plan de travail Ã©tudiant Ã  titre de caractÃ©ristique de la FOAD, Ã  savoir [...]',1348715884,NULL,NULL,'~ FOAD connectiviste ~ Plan de travail Ã©tudiant (travaux notÃ©s) &#171; Fr#oped12','http://foadblog.wordpress.com/2012/09/06/foad_connectiviste/','Mon, 24 Sep 2012 14:22:27 +0000',NULL,'Comments on: 01 ~ FOAD Connectiviste (MOOC) Mise en contexte','6','<p>[...] a Ã©voquÃ©, dans la page de &#8216;mise en contexte&#8216;, la notion de plan de travail Ã©tudiant Ã  titre de caractÃ©ristique de la FOAD, Ã  savoir [...]</p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(701,0,0,'Why I am liking #blendkit2012 ? They really know what they are doing. Here&apos;s a list of reasons: 1...','text/html','https://plus.google.com/110117137800261731479/posts/Pi61dRNBrMS','category',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'Why I am liking #blendkit2012 ? They really know what they are doing. Here&#39;s a list of reasons:1) A nice introduction to the course, with clear objectives and possibilities for participation (http://www.slideshare.net/drkelvinthompson/blend-kit2012)2) Interactive webinars (e.g., https://ucf.adobeconnect.com/_a826512158/p70farkxiiv/?launcher=false&amp;fcsContent=true&amp;pbMode=normal)Â 3) Nice readings (http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course-readings/)4) Student-student and student/instructor interaction via HootCourse (http://hootcourse.com/course/2554/)6) Instructure Canvas learning management system (https://canvas.instructure.com/courses/759279/)7) Creative commons license8) RSS blog feed (and yes, what students are posting is quite interesting. e.g., http://www.techconvoy.com/?p=518 and http://caseylundberg.posterous.com/blendkit-2012-week-1)9) The instructor is present, and engages with students (It&#39;s not just a course it&#39;s a real class)10) A badge evaluation system, in case you want to feel you &quot;completed&quot; the course (http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course-badges/)11) Everything seems fresh, seamlessly curated, and done with care. No cutting corners, careless mistakes or attitude. Similar to the #moocmooc Â in this sense.12) A very clear mission to &quot;change the world&quot;, starting with improving online/blended education ; )<p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course/&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>BlendKit Course | Blended Learning Toolkit</a>\n									</p><p class=&apos;attachment photo&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course/&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=http%3A%2F%2F4.bp.blogspot.com%2F-kX4F-CrWzEw%2FUGMP1UZ3FMI%2FAAAAAAAAAGI%2Fzvhc1r4z0iQ%2Fs320%2Fstick_figure_snorkel_400_clr_8690.png&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/> </a>\n									</p>',1348717807,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Thu, 27 Sep 2012 03:10:22 +0200',NULL,'CDATA(0)',NULL,'Why I am liking #blendkit2012 ? They really know what they are doing. Here&#39;s a list of reasons:1) A nice introduction to the course, with clear objectives and possibilities for participation (http://www.slideshare.net/drkelvinthompson/blend-kit2012)2) Interactive webinars (e.g., https://ucf.adobeconnect.com/_a826512158/p70farkxiiv/?launcher=false&amp;fcsContent=true&amp;pbMode=normal)Â 3) Nice readings (http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course-readings/)4) Student-student and student/instructor interaction via HootCourse (http://hootcourse.com/course/2554/)6) Instructure Canvas learning management system (https://canvas.instructure.com/courses/759279/)7) Creative commons license8) RSS blog feed (and yes, what students are posting is quite interesting. e.g., http://www.techconvoy.com/?p=518 and http://caseylundberg.posterous.com/blendkit-2012-week-1)9) The instructor is present, and engages with students (It&#39;s not just a course it&#39;s a real class)10) A badge evaluation system, in case you want to feel you &quot;completed&quot; the course (http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course-badges/)11) Everything seems fresh, seamlessly curated, and done with care. No cutting corners, careless mistakes or attitude. Similar to the #moocmooc Â in this sense.12) A very clear mission to &quot;change the world&quot;, starting with improving online/blended education ; )<p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course/&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>BlendKit Course | Blended Learning Toolkit</a>\n									</p><p class=&apos;attachment photo&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://blended.online.ucf.edu/blendkit-course/&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=http%3A%2F%2F4.bp.blogspot.com%2F-kX4F-CrWzEw%2FUGMP1UZ3FMI%2FAAAAAAAAAGI%2Fzvhc1r4z0iQ%2Fs320%2Fstick_figure_snorkel_400_clr_8690.png&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/> </a>\n									</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(702,0,0,'OTR Links 09/27/2012','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/27/otr-links-09272012/','Links;category',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'Learnable Programming Here&#8217;s a trick question: How do we get people to understand programming? tags: via:packrati.us programming learning education computer science computer studies Cube for K-12 Teachers Â« doug â€“ off the record Just blogged&#8230; Cube for K-12 Teachers http://t.co/8LWy8dCU tags: via:packrati.us How To Get The New Twitter Header and Look More Like Facebook &#124; [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11138&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348725963,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Thu, 27 Sep 2012 05:30:35 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<ul class=\"diigo-linkroll\">\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://worrydream.com/LearnableProgramming/\">Learnable Programming</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Here&#8217;s a trick question: How do we get people to understand programming?</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/programming\">programming</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/learning\">learning</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/education\">education</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/computer science\">computer science</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/computer studies\">computer studies</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2011/10/16/cube-for-k-12-teachers/?utm_source=dlvr.it&amp;utm_medium=twitter&amp;utm_campaign=dougpete\">Cube for K-12 Teachers Â« doug â€“ off the record</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Just blogged&#8230; Cube for K-12 Teachers http://t.co/8LWy8dCU</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://socialmediatoday.com/marketmesuite/844926/how-get-new-twitter-header-and-look-more-facebook\">How To Get The New Twitter Header and Look More Like Facebook | Social Media Today</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;We&#8217;ve seen #newlook, #newtwitter, so I guess this is #newlooknewnewtwitter? Twitter has released another styling update, which bears striking resemblance to the Facebook Timelines released earlier this year. Now you can have a header on the top of your profile. There are two ways to do it.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/how to\">how to</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/header\">header</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/facebook\">facebook</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/social\">social</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/social media\">social media</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/media\">media</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"https://www.thinglink.com/scene/294594670841823234?buttonSource=galleryPage\">An Interactive Image &#8211; ThingLink</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Interactive multiple intelligences map by application type</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ipod\">ipod</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/apps\">apps</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ipad\">ipad</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.21stcenturyfluency.com/blogpost.cfm?blogID=2975\">Technology Doesn&#8217;t Teach, Teachers Teach| The Committed Sardine</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Education is experiencing a seismic change. The chalkboard and print-based textbook classroom of yesterday is fast becoming the digital-whiteboard and e-book classroom of tomorrow. But as students across the country head back to school this month, the companies charged with helping to implement these changes cannot forget the golden rule: the motherboard and the memory chip will never replace the passion and inspiration of a real-life teacher.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/technology\">technology</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teach\">teach</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://it.mhsmi.org/?p=531\">The iPadâ€“ Becoming Embedded in MHS School Life</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Last week at school, over two school days, I walked into or observed a series of iPad moments. Â When they happened most did not seem remarkable. Â Reflecting back on them in total, they make me realize how quickly (and positively) the new iPad has become a pervasive part of our school.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/embedded\">embedded</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/school\">school</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/life\">life</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/ipad\">ipad</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://venturebeat.com/2012/09/25/google-unveils-first-ever-underwater-street-view-and-its-amazing/\">Google unveils first-ever underwater \"street-view\" (and it&apos;s amazing) | VentureBeat</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Google just unveiled underwater \"street views\" of the world&apos;s most popular undersea destinations: the Great Barrier Reef, Hawaii&apos;s Hanauma Bay, and Apo Island in the Philippines. And the amazing views are available in glorious 1080P high-definition.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/google\">google</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/streetview\">streetview</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/undersea\">undersea</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.petapixel.com/2012/09/25/this-is-the-most-zoomed-in-photograph-ever-created-by-mankind/\">This is the Most Zoomed-In Photograph Ever Created by Mankind</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;What you&apos;re looking at is the most zoomed-in photo ever shot by mankind. Titled the eXtreme Deep Field (XDF), it&apos;s a followup to the famous Hubble Ultra-Deep Field photo created in the mid-2000s. Scientists combined 10-years-worth of Hubble Space Telescope photos to create this resulting image that shows 5,500 individual galaxies, some of which are one ten-billionth the brightness of what our human eyes can see.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/photograph\">photograph</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/created\">created</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/mankind\">mankind</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://designrfix.com/freebies/45-awesome-free-icon-sets-website\">45 Awesome Free Icon Sets For Your Website | designrfix.com</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Well designed and free icons always come in handy, especially when designing that latest website/blog or app. In this article we have compiled a great collection of free icons ranging from the latest Pinterest icon pack to various social media icons all the way to some really great e-commerce icon sets. So if you are in search of some really great free icons for your next project, this post is not be missed. Enjoy!&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/free\">free</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/icon\">icon</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/sets\">sets</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/website\">website</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/com\">com</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"https://www.teachthought.com/social-media/100-of-the-best-twitter-tools-for-teachers-by-category/\">100 Of The Best Twitter Tools For Teachers By Category | TeachThought</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;In 2009, we sharedÂ our favorite tools for teachers on Twitter, with 100 resources for managing feeds, finding followers, and tackling classroom groups on the social media site. Since then, many tools have been revamped, replaced, or simply aren&apos;t available anymore. Clearly, an update is in order, so we&apos;re proud to present a new list for 2012, featuring the very best tools available to Twittering teachers today.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/twitter tools\">twitter tools</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/tools\">tools</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/category\">category</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.makeuseof.com/tag/7-funny-iphone-5-videos-apple-fanboys-hate/\">7 Funny iPhone 5 Videos Apple Fanboys Will Hate</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Unless you have been living under a rock for the past month you&apos;ll know that Apple recently unveiled the iPhone 5. It did so in its usual inimitable style, wowing the press with showmanship and hype. Unfortunately the product itself didn&apos;t live up to that hype or warrant the showy reveal. It is essentially just an iPhone 4S with a slightly bigger screen.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/funny\">funny</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/iphone\">iphone</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/videos\">videos</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/apple\">apple</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/hate\">hate</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.literacy20.com/2012/09/participatory-media-a-literacy-in-its-infancy/\">Participatory Media: A Literacy in Its Infancy Â« Literacy 2.0</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Literacy 2.0 spoke recently with Rheingold about his favorite subject: The existing, emerging and potential empowerment of individuals to act in collaboration â€“ mindfully.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/participatory\">participatory</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/media\">media</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/literacy\">literacy</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infancy\">infancy</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.theconsultants-e.com/ourblog/blog/2012/20_Resources_for_Integrating_Technology_Effectively_in_Your_Classes.aspx\">Blog > 20+ Resources for Integrating Technology Effectively in Your Classes</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Many new teachers are starting the school year and using various cool webtools. If you need a few ideas, we&apos;ve got some free resources to help you. Check these free lesson plans, training materials, and integration tips. You can download the pdfs and share them with staff as well.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/blog\">blog</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/resources\">resources</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/integrating\">integrating</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/technology\">technology</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/classes\">classes</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.topeducationalapps.com/2012/09/apps-that-can-make-science-come-alive/\">Apps That Can Make Science Come Alive! | Top Educational Apps</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;However, help is at hand with iPad and iPhone apps as the iOS system comes to the rescue of budding scientists everywhere. Â In today&apos;s post I&apos;ll discuss three of the top apps used in education for budding scientists.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/apps\">apps</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/science\">science</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://www.eweek.com/enterprise-apps/google-chrome-22-offers-3d-gaming-24-bug-fixes/\">Google Chrome 22 Offers 3D Gaming, 24 Bug Fixes</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;The new Google Chrome Browser Version 22 includes a key improvement aimed at making 3D gaming enthusiasts happier â€“ a Pointer Lock JavaScript API (also called Mouse Lock) that will allow more accurate gaming while using a computer mouse.</p>\n<p>&#8220;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/google\">google</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/google chrome\">google chrome</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/chrome\">chrome</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/offers\">offers</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/gaming\">gaming</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/bug\">bug</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/fixes\">fixes</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://gettingsmart.com/blog/2012/09/11-best-google-chrome-extensions-students/\">11 of the Best Google Chrome Extensions for Students &#8211; Getting Smart by Guest Author &#8211; DigLN, EdTech</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;Whether you are a high school freshman or a Doctoral candidate, you are most likely seeking tools for making your life easier as a student. Education has proliferated with the ever-changing advancements in technology. Blackboards and screen projectors have been replaced by interactive Smartboards, calling cards now come in the form of online databases of periodicals and eBooks, and a standard pen and paper has been replaced by high-speed, 8 Gb powered computers.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/google chrome\">google chrome</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/extensions\">extensions</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/students\">students</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/Chrome\">Chrome</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://educationaltechnologyguy.blogspot.ca/2012/09/infographic-on-technology-in-classroom.html\">Educational Technology Guy: Infographic on Technology in the Classroom &#8211; What Teachers Want</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8220;An interesting infographic from PBS on what teachers want for technology in the classroom:&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/educational technology\">educational technology</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/technology\">technology</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/infographic\">infographic</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/classroom\">classroom</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/teachers\">teachers</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/26/pinterest-to-focus-on-a-topic/?utm_source=dlvr.it&amp;utm_medium=twitter&amp;utm_campaign=dougpete\">Pinterest to Focus on a Topic Â« doug &#8211; off the record</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Just blogged&#8230; Pinterest to Focus on a Topic http://t.co/o0jRrjz9</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/pinterest\">pinterest</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/education\">education</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/26/otr-links-09262012/?utm_source=dlvr.it&amp;utm_medium=twitter&amp;utm_campaign=dougpete\">OTR Links 09/26/2012 Â« doug &#8211; off the record</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">Just blogged&#8230; OTR Links 09/26/2012 http://t.co/tN8IOkct</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/Links\">Links</a></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"diigo-ps\">Posted from <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com&apos;>Diigo</a>. The rest of my favorite links are <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete&apos;>here</a>.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11138/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11138/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11138&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(703,0,0,'#oped12 How Open Is It? - Request for Public Comment  http://t.co/Hy77rCux','twitter','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/251224534324215808','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/251224534324215808',NULL,NULL,29,'#<em>oped12</em> How Open Is It? - Request for Public Comment <a href=\"http://t.co/Hy77rCux\">http://t.co/Hy77rCux</a>',1348731727,NULL,NULL,'JaapSoft','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft','Thu, 27 Sep 2012 07:39:31 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(704,0,0,'#oped12 document draft on open access of SPARC  http://t.co/YbbYjxKp','twitter','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/251225855391576064','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/251225855391576064',NULL,NULL,29,'#<em>oped12</em> document draft on open access of SPARC <a href=\"http://t.co/YbbYjxKp\">http://t.co/YbbYjxKp</a>',1348738803,NULL,NULL,'JaapSoft','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft','Thu, 27 Sep 2012 07:44:46 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(705,0,0,'Cube Gets Groups','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/27/cube-gets-group/','Computers;Education;Read/Write Web;educator;K through 12;ontario;Professional Development;Teacher;Twitter;category',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'Late this summer, I was invited to test out the new Group feature that Cube for Teachers was incorporating into their excellent resource for Ontario Educators. Â I can&#8217;t believe that it&#8217;s been almost a year since I reviewed and blogged about the initial release of the online resource. Â At the time, there was a concern [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11130&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348740123,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Thu, 27 Sep 2012 09:00:00 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<p class=\"p1\">Late this summer, I was invited to test out the new Group feature that Cube for Teachers was incorporating into their excellent resource for Ontario Educators. Â I can&#8217;t believe that it&#8217;s been almost a year since I reviewed and <strong><a href=\"http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2011/10/16/cube-for-k-12-teachers/\">blogged</a></strong> about the initial release of the online resource. Â At the time, there was a concern from a reader that the service would become pay for use and Cube for Teachers replied that they would remain free and there&#8217;s no indication that has changed.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">The concept of groups really leverages the service.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">It now goes beyond the original concept of a repository &#8211; now you can use the area as a collaboration space for writing teams, planning groups, NTIP, &#8230; Â Rather than rehashing my thoughts, what follows below is the announcement from <strong><a href=\"http://www.cubeforteachers.com/\">Cube for Teachers</a></strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">There are a lot of repositories online but this grouping feature makes the Cube for Teachers really unique. Â Keep that in mind if you&#8217;re ever working on a project that requires pulling resources together. Â Even if you&#8217;re not ready for that yet, it&#8217;s still a nicely organized resource for Ontario teachers.</p>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\">As over 1800 teachers across the province have already discovered, Cube for Teachers allows teachers to search for, share, and save links to internet resources which will help them meet the needs of their students.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">And now, Cube for Teachers has introduced a powerful new feature:Â  Groups. Teachers across the province can now invite other teachers to form professional learning networks (PLNs) inside Cube for Teachers.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">The Group feature within Cube for Teachers can be used:</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">a) Â  Â  to share resources<br />\nb) Â  Â  to share teaching ideas<br />\nc) Â  Â  for professional development<br />\nd) Â  Â  as a forum for discussions on important educational topics</p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>Reasons Why Educators Will Want to Use the Groups Feature:</strong></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">1.Â Â Â Â  Ontario teachers can now connect with others throughout the province on specific topics or other areas of interest.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">2.Â Â Â Â  School departments can collaborate on resources for various courses.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">3.Â Â Â Â  School administrators can invite their staff to form groups for professional development.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">4.Â Â Â Â  Subject Council members can share ideas, resource links and next steps.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">5.Â Â Â Â  Administrators can form PLNs with other administrators.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">6.Â Â Â Â  School Family representatives can support each other and share ideas.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">7.Â Â Â Â  Faculties of Education instructors can establish networks for their teacher candidates to share ideas, resource links, and support each other.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">8.Â Â Â Â  New teachers (NTIP) can offer support and ideas for each other.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">9.Â Â Â Â  Teachers can form groups to continue collaborating after an in-service.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">10. Â  The Groups Feature helps make Cube for Teachers the one-stop shop for Ontario teachers to collaborate!</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">We welcome all Ontario educators to register with Cube For Teachers and try our latest feature! Remember that The Cube is a secure community designed exclusively for Ontario teachers. Teacher can search for, share, and save links based on grade, course, subject, and expectations based on the Ontario Curriculum.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">And please, spread the word!Â  Refer a friend. Let others know what a fabulous website <a href=\"http://cubeforteachers.us4.list-manage.com/track/click?u=cbc577209983e16f7c742ed95&amp;id=3e2b5789a1&amp;e=4208b399a2\">www.cubeforteachers.com</a> has become. The greater the number of teachers who register and contribute to the website, the more valuable it will be to you!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h6 class=\"zemanta-related-title\" style=\"font-size:1em;\">Related articles</h6>\n<ul class=\"zemanta-article-ul\">\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://teachingwithsoul.wordpress.com/2012/09/20/twenty-tips-for-success-for-new-teachers/\" target=\"_blank\">Twenty Tips for Success for New Teachers</a> (teachingwithsoul.wordpress.com)</li>\n</ul>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11130/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11130/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11130&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(706,0,0,'#oped12 Sign the Capetown Declaration http://t.co/Fd6os50n','twitter','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/251283866936020992','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/251283866936020992',NULL,NULL,29,'#<em>oped12</em> Sign the Capetown Declaration <a href=\"http://t.co/Fd6os50n\">http://t.co/Fd6os50n</a>',1348745883,NULL,NULL,'JaapSoft','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft','Thu, 27 Sep 2012 11:35:17 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(707,0,0,'#oped12 start  artikel http://t.co/Meju8BX0  wikipedia OER','twitter','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/251270528537620480','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/251270528537620480',NULL,NULL,29,'#<em>oped12</em> start artikel <a href=\"http://t.co/Meju8BX0\">http://t.co/Meju8BX0</a> wikipedia OER',1348745883,NULL,NULL,'JaapSoft','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft','Thu, 27 Sep 2012 10:42:17 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(708,0,0,'','text/html','http://www.reimerth.com/2012/09/vulkan-aside/','Bonmots;personal;SprichwÃ¶rter;category',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,58,'&#8220;Der Wunsch ist der Vulkan, der immer ausbricht.&#8221; Ein kleines Bonmot meiner Tochter; ist mir schon bei mancher Gelegenheit einfach so in den Sinn gekommen.',1348748643,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Thu, 27 Sep 2012 11:38:10 +0000',NULL,'Reimerth',NULL,'&#8220;Der Wunsch ist der Vulkan, der immer ausbricht.&#8221; Ein k