3848489411557637/posts/GvEb1yPP5xE&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Original Post</a> from <a href=&apos;https://plus.google.com/114103848489411557637&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Nathan Fong</a>:</strong></p><p>A culinary MOOC, from some of the folks behind Modernist Cuisine?</p><p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://www.chefsteps.com/&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Free to Learn Culinary School | ChefSteps</a>\n									</p><p class=&apos;attachment photo&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://www.chefsteps.com/&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=http%3A%2F%2Fd2eud0b65jr0pw.cloudfront.net%2Fcarousel_1.jpg&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/> </a>\n									</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(777,0,0,'#Oped12 What sort of education is needed in Higher Education? | http://t.co/R07mW9CQ','twitter','http://twitter.com/ediazsan/statuses/252163107571499008','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/ediazsan/statuses/252163107571499008',NULL,NULL,29,'#<em>Oped12</em> What sort of education is needed in Higher Education? | <a href=\"http://t.co/R07mW9CQ\">http://t.co/R07mW9CQ</a>',1348958523,NULL,NULL,'ediazsan','http://twitter.com/ediazsan','Sat, 29 Sep 2012 21:49:04 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(778,1,0,'Openness is an ideal','text/html','http://connectiv.wordpress.com/2012/09/29/openness-is-an-ideal/','change11;ideal;OER;open;category',NULL,NULL,38,NULL,NULL,NULL,57,'&#8221; It is built on the belief that everyone should have the freedom to use, customize, improve and redistribute educational resources without constraint. &#8221; Capetown declaration. In the Capetown declaration is no mention of the reasons why everyone should have this freedom. Unesco has a statement of some reasons to provide OER: &#8220;UNESCO believes that [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=connectiv.wordpress.com&#038;blog=19220396&#038;post=2137&#038;subd=connectiv&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348962483,NULL,NULL,'jaapsoft2','http://connectiv.wordpress.com','Sat, 29 Sep 2012 22:00:41 +0000',NULL,'connectiv','1','<p><a title=\"Samuel Dirksz van Hoogstraten [Public domain or Public domain], via Wikimedia Commons\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File%3ASamuel_van_Hoogstraten_-_Vrouw_bij_een_half_open_deur.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Samuel_van_Hoogstraten_-_Vrouw_bij_een_half_open_deur.jpg/256px-Samuel_van_Hoogstraten_-_Vrouw_bij_een_half_open_deur.jpg\" alt=\"Samuel van Hoogstraten - Vrouw bij een half open deur\" width=\"256\" /></a>&#8221; It is built on the belief that everyone should have the freedom to use, customize, improve and redistribute educational resources without constraint. &#8221; <a href=\"http://www.capetowndeclaration.org/read-the-declaration\">Capetown declaration</a>. In the Capetown declaration is no mention of the reasons why everyone should have this freedom.<br />\nUnesco has a statement of some reasons to provide OER: &#8220;UNESCO believes that universal access to high quality education is key to the building of peace, sustainable social and economic development, and intercultural dialogue. Open Educational Resources (OER) provide a strategic opportunity to improve the quality of education as well as facilitate policy dialogue, knowledge sharing and capacity building.&#8221; <a href=\"http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/access-to-knowledge/open-educational-resources/\">Unesco</a>.</p>\n<p>In my view Open Education and OER are necessary to help to build a better world. In a democratic system every person has a right to take part in the political process. But if education is not available to everyone this democratic rights are a joke.<br />\nOpen education is a means to give every person equal opportunities. Knowledge should not only be available to rich people.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>(Image:Â &#8221;Samuel van Hoogstraten &#8211; Vrouw bij een half open deur&#8221;)</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/connectiv.wordpress.com/2137/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/connectiv.wordpress.com/2137/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=connectiv.wordpress.com&#038;blog=19220396&#038;post=2137&#038;subd=connectiv&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(779,5,0,'Copyright and the internet: Letting the baby dance | The Economist','Diigo','http://www.economist.com/node/21561885?fsrc=scn/tw_ec/letting_the_baby_dance','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,30,'<p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/tag/openness&quot;>openness</a></p><p><strong>by:</strong> <a href=&quot;http://groups.diigo.com/group/oped12/content/user/gsiemens&quot; title=&quot;View gsiemens &apos;s content in group&quot;>gsiemens </a></p>',1348965483,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Sun, 30 Sep 2012 00:21:29 -0000',NULL,'Best content in oped12 | Diigo - Groups','5',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(780,0,0,'Third Culture, week 4, really?','text/html','http://moocmadness.wordpress.com/2012/09/30/third-culture-week4-really/','MOOC;#cmc11;3rd Culture;c-mooc;mooc;potcert;x-mooc;category',NULL,NULL,35,NULL,NULL,NULL,54,'It&#8217;s Week 4 in Â POT CertÂ but not everywhere in the electronic schoolyard. Other courses, are in other weeks. For example, Coursera&#8217;s Fantasy SF is in Week 10, the final week, essay on Cory Doctorow&#8217;s Little Brother due Tuesday. I&#8217;m not sure where CMC11 is, but students are blogging (Learning isn&#8217;t Linear and Neither is LivingÂ sure [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=moocmadness.wordpress.com&#038;blog=39998452&#038;post=81&#038;subd=moocmadness&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348983363,NULL,NULL,'VanessaVaile','http://moocmadness.wordpress.com','Sun, 30 Sep 2012 04:59:38 +0000',NULL,'MOOC Madness',NULL,'<a href=\"http://www.mymodernmet.com/profiles/blogs/thibault-brevet-grand-central\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-103\" title=\"3rdCulture\" src=\"http://moocmadness.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/thibaultbrevet_3rdculture2.jpeg?w=300&h=225\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">from Grand Central, installation by Thibault Brevet</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s Week 4 in Â <a href=\"http://pedagogyfirst.org/wppf12/\" target=\"_blank\">POT Cert</a>Â but not everywhere in the electronic schoolyard. Other courses, are in other weeks. For example, <a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/course/fantasysf\" target=\"_blank\">Coursera&#8217;s Fantasy SF</a> is in Week 10, the final week, essay on <a href=\"http://craphound.com/littlebrother/download/\" target=\"_blank\">Cory Doctorow&#8217;s Little Brother</a> due Tuesday.</p>\n<p>I&#8217;m not sure where <a href=\"http://www.cdlprojects.com/cmc11blog/\" target=\"_blank\">CMC11</a> is, but students are blogging (<a href=\"http://wolfinthenight13.wordpress.com/2012/09/25/learning-isnt-linear/\">Learning isn&#8217;t Linear and Neither is Living</a>Â sure suits my mood) and gRSShopper is gathering feeds. There are yet others (weeks, moocs, projects, schedules, assignments, digital artifacts) but going into them would be another post on the season of comparative mooc-ing.</p>\n<p>I am reading, bookmarking, commenting, taking courses, comparing them but not designing them because I am not teaching any.Â I haven&#8217;t written a Week 3 post yet, at least not on the prescribed topic. Maybe later. This one isn&#8217;t either:</p>\n<blockquote><p><em>Post your thoughts on planning one of your classes. What elements of design from Chapter 3 will you be considering as you build a class? What ideas did you gain from viewing the tours?</em></p></blockquote>\n<p>Being in the Deep End is like being in detention. Spitballs not homework.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/moocmadness.wordpress.com/81/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/moocmadness.wordpress.com/81/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=moocmadness.wordpress.com&#038;blog=39998452&#038;post=81&#038;subd=moocmadness&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(781,0,0,'RT @gsiemens: personally, I enjoyed the @moocmooc open course - lots of great resources/discussions #oped12 #moocmooc','twitter','http://twitter.com/jamesmichie/statuses/252293528720404481','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/jamesmichie/statuses/252293528720404481',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/gsiemens\">gsiemens</a>: personally, I enjoyed the @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/moocmooc\">moocmooc</a> open course - lots of great resources/discussions #<em>oped12</em> <a href=\"http://search.twitter.com/search?q=%23moocmooc\" title=\"#moocmooc\" class=\" \">#moocmooc</a>',1348986844,NULL,NULL,'jamesmichie','http://twitter.com/jamesmichie','Sun, 30 Sep 2012 06:27:19 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(782,0,0,'RT @gsiemens: RT @gsiemens: personally, I enjoyed the @moocmooc open course - lots of great resources/discussions #oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/allistelling/statuses/252283748840767489','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/allistelling/statuses/252283748840767489',NULL,NULL,29,'RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/gsiemens\">gsiemens</a>: RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/gsiemens\">gsiemens</a>: personally, I enjoyed the @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/moocmooc\">moocmooc</a> open course - lots of great resources/discussions #<em>oped12</em>',1348986844,NULL,NULL,'allistelling','http://twitter.com/allistelling','Sun, 30 Sep 2012 05:48:27 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(783,0,0,'I could leave it or take it. RT @gsiemens: personally, I enjoyed the @moocmooc open course - lots of great resources/discussions #oped12','twitter','http://twitter.com/trentmkays/statuses/252278178817642497','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/trentmkays/statuses/252278178817642497',NULL,NULL,29,'I could leave it or take it. RT @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/gsiemens\">gsiemens</a>: personally, I enjoyed the @<a class=\" \" href=\"https://twitter.com/moocmooc\">moocmooc</a> open course - lots of great resources/discussions #<em>oped12</em>',1348986844,NULL,NULL,'trentmkays','http://twitter.com/trentmkays','Sun, 30 Sep 2012 05:26:19 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(784,0,0,'OTR Links 09/30/2012','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/30/otr-links-09302012/','Links;category',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'How To Make Students Better Online Researchers &#8221; We never question the vital importance of teaching literacy, but we have to be mindful that there are many kinds of \"literacies\". An ever more important one that ALL teachers need to be aware of is digital literacy. I could go off in many directions on this, [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11161&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1348988163,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Sun, 30 Sep 2012 05:30:45 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<ul class=\"diigo-linkroll\">\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://edudemic.com/2012/09/students-online-researchers/\">How To Make Students Better Online Researchers</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">&#8221; We never question the vital importance of teaching literacy, but we have to be mindful that there are many kinds of \"literacies\". An ever more important one that ALL teachers need to be aware of is digital literacy. I could go off in many directions on this, but for the purpose of this post I&apos;m focusing strictly on the digital literacy of searching.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/how to\">how to</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/students\">students</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/online\">online</a>      <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/researchers\">researchers</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"https://foursquare.com/v/colchester-harbour/4dbb18e16e815ab0de62c2f0\">Colchester Harbour &#8211; Colchester, Ontario</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">I just ousted @vlbcanada as the mayor of Colchester Harbour on @foursquare! http://t.co/28eJmCOl</p>\n<p class=\"diigo-tags\">     tags:           <a href=\"http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete/via:packrati.us\">via:packrati.us</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p class=\"diigo-link\">        <a href=\"http://blog.darrencannell.com/2012/09/rules-for-teachers-in-1915.html\">Teaching and Developing online: Rules for teachers in 1915</a>   </p>\n<p class=\"diigo-description\">When someone whines about the good ol&#8217; days in education, send them here.