apos;http://www.diigo.com&apos;>Diigo</a>. The rest of my favorite links are <a href=&apos;http://www.diigo.com/user/dougpete&apos;>here</a>.</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11161/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11161/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11161&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(785,0,0,'http://t.co/gelhICwq  #oped12 openness and democracy','twitter','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/252295334645088256','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/JaapSoft/statuses/252295334645088256',NULL,NULL,29,'<a href=\"http://t.co/gelhICwq\">http://t.co/gelhICwq</a> #<em>oped12</em> openness and democracy',1348993923,NULL,NULL,'JaapSoft','http://twitter.com/JaapSoft','Sun, 30 Sep 2012 06:34:29 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(786,0,0,'Entry Points','text/html','http://dougpete.wordpress.com/2012/09/30/entry-points/','Computers;Education;learning;Read/Write Web;Teaching;coding;computer science;Douglas Rushkoff;GameMaker;JavaScript;Khan Academy;programming;Student;category',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,NULL,NULL,15,'&#160; I make no apologies when I admit my preferences and soft heart for computer science.Â  Over the years, no other subject has changed so much in content and pedagogical approach.Â  It&#8217;s a terrific computer science teacher who stays on top of all of this. Over the years, there has been no shortage of debate [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11158&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',1349002323,NULL,NULL,'dougpete','http://dougpete.wordpress.com','Sun, 30 Sep 2012 09:00:34 +0000',NULL,'doug - off the record',NULL,'<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>I make no apologies when I admit my preferences and soft heart for computer science.Â  Over the years, no other subject has changed so much in content and pedagogical approach.Â  It&#8217;s a terrific computer science teacher who stays on top of all of this.</p>\n<p>Over the years, there has been no shortage of debate as to what to teach, when to teach it, how to teach it, &#8230;</p>\n<p>If you do reading from many blogs who address one concept of computer science &#8211; coding &#8211; you&#8217;ll find that there are a number of posts giving &#8220;## reasons to teach coding to students&#8221;.Â  Some talk about it generally so that it could be understood that it should be taught somewhere in a child&#8217;s educational career and others specifically make reference to why you&#8217;d want to teach coding in elementary schools.Â  My preference would be, given the large number of places that computers are used in other ways in the curriculum, that the earlier the better.</p>\n<p>But the kids aren&#8217;t ready!Â  Really?Â  How many have helped mom and dad program their smartphone?Â  How many have their own and have customized it to their liking.Â  They&#8217;re already tinkering and learning.Â  They are ready.</p>\n<p>I&#8217;m a firm believer that since we&#8217;re big fans of technology, we really want to ensure that students become educated users of the technology, and part of that is to just get a sense of what it&#8217;s all about.Â  Now, I don&#8217;t think that we&#8217;re expecting our students to create the next great web browser, but there&#8217;s so much value in knowing what coding is all about and a sense of how it&#8217;s done.Â  I&#8217;ve mentioned it in this blog before but I really believe in the message of Douglas Rushkoff&#8217;s &#8220;<strong><a href=\"http://www.rushkoff.com/program-or-be-programmed/\">Program or be Programmed</a></strong>&#8220;.Â  Your school&#8217;s teacher-librarian needs to have a copy of that in your professional library.</p>\n<p>Through the introduction of this awareness, it also opens the doors to the whole discipline where the students just may wish to extend their abilities.</p>\n<p>The real question, to me, remains largely unanswered.Â  Where should coding, as an introduction to computer science, be introduced?Â  It&#8217;s amazing the number of teachers who will agree that it&#8217;s a good skill to have as long as someone else introduces it!</p>\n<p>I&#8217;ve been playing around with <strong><a href=\"http://www.crunchzilla.com/code-monster\">Code Monster from Crunchzilla</a></strong> and can see where it may solve the problem for implementation.</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img style=\"margin:5px;\" src=\"http://dougpete.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/about.png?w=506&h=232\" alt=\"\" width=\"506\" height=\"232\" /></p>\n<p>Code Monster is a number of things.Â  It&#8217;s an environment to learn about Javascript (not to be confused with Java), it&#8217;s a play as you go tutorial, it&#8217;s a place to see immediate results for instant feedback, and it&#8217;s a conversation with a monster who steps you through the process.</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img style=\"margin:5px;\" src=\"http://dougpete.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/monster.png?w=550&h=362\" alt=\"\" width=\"550\" height=\"362\" /></p>\n<p>The use of the tutorial provides feedback to the learner and gives an instant sense of achievement.Â  Recently, I tried it out here at dougpete labs.Â  (which is really a couch and two recliner chairs with a dog who wants to be part of everything)Â  Within minutes, my guinea pig made the comment &#8220;Hey, I could actually do this &#8230; it isn&#8217;t all that hard.&#8221;Â  The more I started to think about Code Monster, the more I liked it.</p>\n<p>As a beginning learning environment, you&#8217;re not presented with a large confusing interface with a tonne of options like you would find in a professional IDE and the concept of the code in one window and the results in another window right beside generates that instant feeling of gratification that comes from writing good code.</p>\n<p>With your friendly monster leading the way, learning is quick, efficient, and fun.Â  The deeper you get into the tutorials, the more you want to experience.</p>\n<p>I can see an application like this having multiple entry points in schools:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>in a computer studies class, an introduction to Javascript with a proceed at your own pace functionality;</li>\n<li>in an elementary school classroom, where the desire is there to easily introduce coding to students;</li>\n<li>in a computer club where students learn the concepts on their own in a group setting.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Working through the tutorial with the monster will indeed give a sense of what coding is about and hopefully generate enough interest to take on something else.Â  There is so much available once you get started &#8211; Scratch, Alice, GameMaker &#8211; and a good start to coding is a great way to ensure success.</p>\n<p style=\"color:#008;text-align:right;\"><small><em>Powered by</em> <a href=\"http://www.qumana.com/\">Qumana</a></small></p>\n<h6 class=\"zemanta-related-title\" style=\"font-size:1em;\">Related articles</h6>\n<ul class=\"zemanta-article-ul\">\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://glinden.blogspot.com/2012/09/code-monster-and-teaching-programming.html\" target=\"_blank\">Code Monster and teaching programming to kids</a> (glinden.blogspot.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://alfredtwo.blogspot.com/2012/09/interesting-links-10-september-2012.html\" target=\"_blank\">Interesting Links 10 September 2012</a> (alfredtwo.blogspot.com)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://www.good.is/post/khan-academy-wants-to-teach-you-coding/\" target=\"_blank\">Khan Academy Wants to Teach You Coding</a> (good.is)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://ejohn.org/blog/introducing-khan-cs/\" target=\"_blank\">Redefining the Introduction to Computer Science</a> (ejohn.org)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://developers.slashdot.org/story/12/09/12/0048209/is-a-computer-science-degree-worth-getting-anymore\" target=\"_blank\">Is a Computer Science Degree Worth Getting Anymore?</a> (developers.slashdot.org)</li>\n<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li\"><a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2012/08/14/khan-academy-launches-the-future-of-computer-science-education/\" target=\"_blank\">Khan Academy Launches The Future of Computer Science Education</a> (techcrunch.com)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<br /> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11158/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/dougpete.wordpress.com/11158/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=dougpete.wordpress.com&#038;blog=2477343&#038;post=11158&#038;subd=dougpete&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(787,0,0,'My post for #oped12 about creative commons licensing, moocification, and putting it all into practice. Reaction to Wk3 https://t.co/jQsNfe41','twitter','http://twitter.com/bernardotrejos/statuses/252367267554263041','edubloggers',NULL,NULL,342,'http://twitter.com/bernardotrejos/statuses/252367267554263041',NULL,NULL,29,'My post for #<em>oped12</em> about creative commons licensing, moocification, and putting it all into practice. Reaction to Wk3 <a href=\"https://t.co/jQsNfe41\">https://t.co/jQsNfe41</a>',1349008083,NULL,NULL,'bernardotrejos','http://twitter.com/bernardotrejos','Sun, 30 Sep 2012 11:20:20 +0000',NULL,'oped12 - Twitter Search',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(788,6,0,'I&apos;m still following #oped12 , but in a very loose way. Not interested in doing homework per se, b...','text/html','https://plus.google.com/110117137800261731479/posts/YtVg6zMFqMh','category',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'I&#39;m still following #oped12 , but in a very loose way. Not interested in doing homework per se, but I am quite interested in putting openness into practice in my teaching. To use a metaphor: I am more interested in becoming light than in talking about brightness.This week&#39;s topic is &quot;Licensing and Copyright Protection&quot; (http://open.mooc.ca/week3.htm). The readings and videos are quite counter-cultural; not that there&#39;s anything wrong with that.Nonetheless, the topic interest me a lot, because my teaching philosophy includes the following principles:- I combine teaching, research and service in all my work activities, therefore, I dedicate 100% of my time to teaching, 100% of my time to research, and 100% of my time to service.- I believe in open education and in making my work accessible to whoever can benefit from its use. #onlineeducation Â and #onlinecourses Â can help bring this into practice.Anyway, I came up with this idea that I wanted my classes to be available online for anybody to follow (This has been called MOOCificiation , an idea developed in the #MOOCMOOC , see http://storify.com/bernardotrejos/moocifying-my-courses.Â +Dominik LukeÅ¡Â further explains the concept here: http://researchity.net/2012/08/17/how-to-moocify-your-course/)So here are the three first presentations that I developed with a Creative Commons license:1) https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1PRUremnSHhpcUT93bq7080DgaGdP_R4iISar_9WuhrQ/edit2)Â https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1WGNewunQ9I37rPhBCVI0ywgm256A5oH0ZtrHqQd4fL8/edit3)Â https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1nounX3ANQFDVnuNxc02qX0WLJt44yXDlYZpx6aWHg_4/editI will be using them in class this week.This is the link to my teaching webpage:Â etourismlabComments? Suggestions?<p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://open.mooc.ca/week3.htm&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Week 3 - Licensing and Content Protection ~ Openness in Education</a>\n									</p>',1349008324,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Sun, 30 Sep 2012 13:05:30 +0200',NULL,'CDATA(0)','2','I&#39;m still following #oped12 , but in a very loose way. Not interested in doing homework per se, but I am quite interested in putting openness into practice in my teaching. To use a metaphor: I am more interested in becoming light than in talking about brightness.This week&#39;s topic is &quot;Licensing and Copyright Protection&quot; (http://open.mooc.ca/week3.htm). The readings and videos are quite counter-cultural; not that there&#39;s anything wrong with that.Nonetheless, the topic interest me a lot, because my teaching philosophy includes the following principles:- I combine teaching, research and service in all my work activities, therefore, I dedicate 100% of my time to teaching, 100% of my time to research, and 100% of my time to service.- I believe in open education and in making my work accessible to whoever can benefit from its use. #onlineeducation Â and #onlinecourses Â can help bring this into practice.Anyway, I came up with this idea that I wanted my classes to be available online for anybody to follow (This has been called MOOCificiation , an idea developed in the #MOOCMOOC , see http://storify.com/bernardotrejos/moocifying-my-courses.Â +Dominik LukeÅ¡Â further explains the concept here: http://researchity.net/2012/08/17/how-to-moocify-your-course/)So here are the three first presentations that I developed with a Creative Commons license:1) https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1PRUremnSHhpcUT93bq7080DgaGdP_R4iISar_9WuhrQ/edit2)Â https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1WGNewunQ9I37rPhBCVI0ywgm256A5oH0ZtrHqQd4fL8/edit3)Â https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1nounX3ANQFDVnuNxc02qX0WLJt44yXDlYZpx6aWHg_4/editI will be using them in class this week.This is the link to my teaching webpage:Â etourismlabComments? Suggestions?<p class=&apos;attachment article&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;http://open.mooc.ca/week3.htm&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>Week 3 - Licensing and Content Protection ~ Openness in Education</a>\n									</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,NULL),(789,0,0,'24-hour culinary adventure\n3 of my favorite places to eat in less than 24 hours.','text/html','https://plus.google.com/110117137800261731479/posts/f7GthVH9U2M','category',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'24-hour culinary adventure3 of my favorite places to eat in less than 24 hours.<p class=&apos;attachment photo-album&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;https://plus.google.com/photos/110117137800261731479/albums/5793970937508046353&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;>24 hr culinary adventure (14 photos)</a>\n									</p><p class=&apos;attachment photo&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-4DOX-O3gZmQ/UGhR3_TsukI/AAAAAAAAEmc/EXUaLf-_dKI/DSCN0475.JPG&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=https%3A%2F%2Flh4.googleusercontent.com%2F-4DOX-O3gZmQ%2FUGhR3_TsukI%2FAAAAAAAAEmc%2FEXUaLf-_dKI%2Fs288%2FDSCN0475.JPG&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/> DSCN0475.JPG</a>\n									</p><p class=&apos;attachment photo&apos;>\n										<a href=&apos;https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-SUTFx7dtAnM/UGhR4uUSUCI/AAAAAAAAEmo/SzRII7Xz9Z8/DSCN0476.JPG&apos; target=&apos;_blank&apos;><img src=&apos;https://images0-focus-opensocial.googleusercontent.com/gadgets/proxy?container=focus&gadget=a&resize_h=100&url=https%3A%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2F-SUTFx7dtAnM%2FUGhR4uUSUCI%2FAAAAAAAAEmo%2FSzRII7Xz9Z8%2Fs288%2FDSCN0476.JPG&apos; height=&apos;100&apos;/> DSCN0476.JPG</a>\n									</p><p class=&apos;attachment pho